<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WorldAIDS Bjt   04-19 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-World AIDS, Bjt,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS Cases Likely to Multiply Five Times in Next Three Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of full-blown AIDS cases in the
world is likely to increase fivefold in the next three years, and
hundreds of millions of people probably engage in activity that
leaves them vulnerable, says the head of the World Health
Organization's AIDS program.
   ``While it has become fashionable to reassure and state that
AIDS will never threaten large populations, we believe that
virology, immunology, sociology and epidemiology require us to take
the long view, and a more somber view,'' Dr. Jonathan Mann told the
White House AIDS commission Monday.
   ``Let us remember that we are still in the early phases of a
global epidemic whose first decade gives us every rational reason
for concern about the global future of AIDS,'' he said. ``HIV (the
AIDS virus) does not need to spread rapidly in a population to have
a tremendous and gradually expanding cumulative effect.''
   Mann said that while no precise figures are available, ``it is
likely that several hundred million people around the world may
have behaviors which make them potentially vulnerable to infection
with HIV.''
   While he did not spell out such behavior at that point in his
testimony, it was clear he was referring primarily to unprotected
sex with potentially infected partners and, secondarily, to drug
users sharing needles with people who may be carrying the virus.
   ``Individual behavior is responsible for most HIV
transmission,'' he said. ``This transmission requires the active
participation of two persons. Therefore, the chain of transmission
can be broken by the individual behavior of either the infected or
the non-infected person. For this reason, the proper focus of
prevention is behavior.''
   He said education is essential to combating the epidemic.
   ``If intravenous drug users do not understand the words you use
to describe needles, syringes and other drug equipment, they cannot
learn prevention. If adolescents are convinced that AIDS is being
used to deprive them of sexual freedom, they may refuse to listen
to prevention messages and even counterreact in ways that further
endanger their lives,'' Mann said.
   More than 81,000 AIDS cases were reported to the organization as
of the end of February, but the actual number of AIDS cases is
believed to be twice the reported total.
   WHO estimates that between 5 million and 10 million people are
infected with the virus and that 150,000 new cases of fully
developed AIDS will be reported during the coming year.
   ``If we adopt the conservative estimate then 5 million people
are infected today with HIV (the AIDS virus), a cumulative total of
1 million AIDS cases would be expected by 1991,'' he said. ``Thus,
the period 1988-91 will likely witness over five times more AIDS
cases than have thus far occurred.''
   Dr. Jean William Pape of the Cornell University Medical College
told the panel the epidemic in Haiti and Trinidad is shifting
dramatically to one of heterosexual transmission.
   Whereas only 26 percent of the cases reported in Haiti 1983 were
believed to have resulted from heterosexual sex, the number jumped
to 64 percent last year.
   In Trinidad, he said, only 12 percent of the cases reported in
1985 were attributed to likely heterosexual sex, compared to 58
percent last year.
</TEXT>
