<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Patriots'Day     04-19 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Patriots' Day,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Modern-Day Revere Rides To Lexington Dodging Manholes, Battling
Laryngitis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Revere's laryngitis made it hard for him to
shout, ``The British are coming.'' William Dawes got locked in a
men's room during a rest stop. And the rain made slippery manholes
treacherous for the patriots' horses.
   Otherwise, Patriots' Day on Monday was the occasion of a
satisfactory re-staging of the 13-mile mission to Lexington 213
years ago that alerted revolutionary colonists that British troops
were heading their way.
   ``I'm ready to go back,'' Harold Snow said in a cracking voice
at the end of the 2{-hour horseback ride from Boston. It was the
seventh portrayal of Paul Revere for the 72-year-old entrepreneur
from Wellesley who is a brigadier general in the Massachusetts
National Lancers.
   For decades, the ceremonial militia of 30 men has roughly
recreated in daytime the horseback ride that Revere, Dawes and Dr.
Samuel Prescott made in the late hours of April 18, 1775.
   By alerting the insurrectionary colonists that British troops
were on their way to Concord, the 18th century trio set in motion
the next day's confrontation that started the American Revolution.
   Monday, Douglas Dougherty, a lieutenant in the lancers who
portrayed Dawes, was freed from a men's room in Arlington in time
to meet up with Snow for their grand finale in Lexington where they
were met by a cheering crowd estimated at 500 people.
   This year's journey was considerably harder than the one taken
the first time around. Just before Snow left Boston with a send-off
from Mayor Raymond Flynn, he groused about the rain. His costume of
three-cornered hat, wig, cloak and boots made for a hot ride
compared to Revere's, who had the advantage of a cool, clear night
and his own clothes.
   Snow also had to watch out for slippery manholes.
   But Snow said he enjoyed himself and was grateful for the
audience along the way that ignored the Boston Marathon.
   When Snow left Boston's North End, where Revere lived in a house
that still stands, a throng of spectators stood under store awnings
and a makeshift canopy of umbrellas. There were grinning toddlers,
graying baby-boomers taking off for the state holiday and elderly
Italian widows.
   ``This is how America was founded,'' said Patti Gant, an
accountant from Everett, who recommended historical re-enactments
as a way to understand this country.
   ``You've got to get the concept of where you come from to know
where you go from here,'' said Ms. Gant, 50.
   Frank Federico, 35, a pharmacist who grew up in the old, narrow
streets of the North End, said he's been coming to see Revere ride
off his entire life. That's why he brought his 10-year-old son,
Michael, he said.
   ``It's a family tradition,'' the elder Federico said with a nod
toward his son. ``It's important to see what you read about in the
classroom.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
