<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 0150EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Dance     04-19 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dance,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ballet Theater Opens Season with Panache</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Ballet Theater opened its two-month
season at the Metropolitan Opera House with panache _ the kind of
dancing, style and brio that expects, deserves and receives bravos.
   Monday's program began with Mikhail Baryshnikov's new production
and staging of ``Raymonda (Grand Pas Classique).'' Martine van
Hamel, a commanding stage presence as well as a glorious ballerina,
was partnered superbly by Kevin McKenzie.
   Amanda McKerrow, who danced the fourth solo variation, which
requires lightness, long extension and some difficult balances, has
blossomed into the ballerina her early promise predicted.
   Baryshnikov staged the ballet after Marius Petipa, incorporating
the grand pas de dix from Act 3 and several variations from the
full-length ``Raymonda.'' Music is by Glazounov.
   Antony Tudor, who died last year, choreographed ``The Leaves Are
Fading'' for American Ballet Theater in 1975. The music is by
Dvorak. Sometimes this seems merely an overlong, pretty ballet, in
which the women's thin skirts ripple as the men lift them and they
seem to float.
   On Monday, it was a beautiful ballet. The various moods were
strongly defined. There is much more than a pastel sense of autumn
and saying goodby. Exquisite dancing _ which was seen opening night
_ is important. Dim lighting instead of very noticeable dappled
lighting helps, too, allowing the dancers and the music to hold
prominence.
   Leslie Browne and Robert Hill were the nimble leading couple,
their virtuosic dancing having a carefree air about it.
   The evening ended with the first New York performance of the
company's production of George Balanchine's ``Ballet Imperial.''
The company looks comfortable with this Balanchine piece, which is
more classical than his usual _ he based it on the Petipa style.
Also, in this 1941 ballet, there are intertwinings which are
Balanchine trademarks.
   ``Ballet Imperial'' is as visually regal as the ``Raymonda''
which began the evening and the dancing was as glittering as the
women's small crowns. Susan Jaffe and Ross Stretton were the
impressive leading couple and Miss McKerrow distinguished herself
again in solos.
   Michael Boriskin was the thundering soloist in Tchaikovsky's
``Second Piano Concerto'' for ``Ballet Imperial.'' Jack Everly
conducted the entire evening.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
