<DOCNO> AP880419-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 0151EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ChildLabor     04-19 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Child Labor,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Children Working Illegally In Areas Of High Employment, Department
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Employers in areas of low joblessness are
increasingly turning to using teen-agers in violation of child
labor laws as an alternative to paying higher wages to attract and
retain adults, Labor Department officials say.
   Illegal employment of children increased by more than 50 percent
in 1987, the Labor Department said Monday. It said the most
dramatic increase in violations occurred in the Northeast, where
unemployment rates are lowest.
   ``Because of the high levels of employment, we're finding a lot
of firms hiring minors illegally for positions formerly held by
older workers,'' said Nancy Flynn, deputy administrator of the
department's wage-hour division. ``It's a trend in that geographic
region.''
   The number of children nationwide that the department found to
be illegally employed last year was slightly more than 19,000, up
from 12,662 in 1986.
   The department said it assessed civil fines totaling $1.5
million last year against 811 companies illegally employing 10,160
minors.
   Under the labor protection laws, children ages 14 and 15 can
hold limited, non-hazardous jobs, but the number of hours they can
work is restricted. Children ages 16 and 17 can work full-time but
not in dangerous occupations such as roofing, excavation work and
mining or around hazardous machinery.
   The biggest violator, the department said, was a large chain of
supermarkets in the Northeast which was working children too many
hours a week and illegally employing them in hazardous occupations
such as meat cutting.
   Ms. Flynn would not identify the supermarket chain, saying the
case is still being litigated.
   The department said it found that nearly 488,000 U.S. workers
were cheated out of $126 million last year through employer
violations of minimum wage, overtime pay and other provisions of
the Fair Labor Standards Act.
   At least 155,000 workers were due $28.5 million in minimum wage
violations and 329,000 employers were underpaid at total of $98
million in overtime due them, said Assistant Labor Secretary Fred
Alvarez.
   Of those amounts, the department recovered about $20.2 million
in minimum wages for 136,000 of the workers who were underpaid and
$79.5 million for 293,000 of those not paid overtime.
   The department also assessed $873,430 in civil penalties against
farm labor contractors for violations of pay and health and safety
standards under the Migrant Worker Protection Act.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
