<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 0155EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-EuropeanTrade     04-19 0666</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-European Trade,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Freer Trade in Europe Would Help US, Other Countries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Knocking down barriers to trade among the 12
countries of the European Community by 1992 will also benefit
outside countries such as the United States and Japan, a researcher
says.
   The main advantage to outside trading partners from greater
unification would be in having only a single set of rules to deal
with, instead of a dozen, said Paolo Cecchini, assigned by the
Community to study the issue.
   ``A foreign company that sells to only one of the 12 will have
jumped over the culture gap,'' he said Monday.
   Ella Krucoff, press officer for the Community's Washington
office, gave labeling requirements on European imports as an
example. Now each of the 12 governments has its own rules.
   Cecchini added that since there would be no official
discrimination against subsidiaries of foreign firms within the
Community, they too would benefit from any additional growth.
   Cecchini said that over the ``medium term'' _ about five years _
new measures of unification also could create as many as 5 million
new jobs in Europe, where unemployment is higher than in this
country. .
   He said about 200 people have contributed to his project called
``The Cost of Non-Europe'' _ the cost of not having unified the
economy of the Community yet. In addition to Cecchini's own Italy,
members include Britain, France, West Germany, Belgium, Holland,
Denmark, Ireland, Luxembourg, Spain, Portugal and Greece.
   Together, these countries have as many people as the United
States. Turkey has also asked to join, and Community officials say
Norway, Sweden and Austria are possibilities. The European Common
Market program is conducted under the auspices of the Community.
   Cecchini noted that in some matters the Community already has
more unity than the United States. For example, a doctor licensed
in one of the 12 countries is qualified to practice in all of them,
unlike the rules here which differ from state to state.
   Next month Cecchini will start publishing more than 6,000 pages
of research. He said his study has found that European economic
gains from greater unification could be worth more than $300
billion and prices paid by consumers could be 6 percent less than
in a divided continent.
   ``Five million new jobs would cover half of Europe's unemployed,
or all the young unemployed,'' he added.
   He also cited the example of Japanese auto exporters, whose
sales to Italy are limited under a quota imposed by the Italian
government. The effort is now being made to ``Europeanize'' this
quota, so that Japanese sales could go to any of the 12 countries
on the same terms. Community officials emphasized there would have
to be some hard bargaining with Japan first.
   Michael Calingaert is a State Department official on leave to
study the European effort for the National Planning Association, a
private group. He said the European plans are moving ahead fast.
   ``In 1957 industrialists were frightened of the possible results
and opposed it,'' he said. ``Now they are in favor.''
   He said the private sector is acting as if the effort will
succeed, and that attitude could be self-fulfilling.
   The idea of a unified Europe, which dates back centuries, got a
boost after World War II when Americans held up the economic
advantages of a ``common market'' like that of the United States.
West European countries had to organize themselves to distribute
the U.S. aid offered in the Marshall Plan, and began to eliminate
import quotas in trade with one another.
   In 1957 six of the present 12 members signed the Treaty of Rome,
pledging the removal of all barriers among them. Progress has been
slow.
   ``Now things are accelerating,'' Cecchini said.
   ``Six months ago nobody was even talking about a central bank
for the Community. Now the prospect is that the summit meeting in
Hanover (West Germany) in June will set up a study of something
like the U.S. Federal Reserve system.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
