<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 0158EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ArmsTreaty     04-19 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arms Treaty,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Committee Sends Senate Report Urging That INF Treaty Be Passed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Critics of the U.S.-Soviet treaty banning
medium-range missiles should be satisfied with Soviet assurances
the pact covers both existing missiles and future weapons using
exotic technologies, the chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee says.
   The State Department told the committee on Monday that the
Soviet position was spelled out last week in a conversation between
Secretary of State George P. Shultz and Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard A. Shevardnadze.
   The dispute centers on the treaty signed Dec. 8 by President
Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, eliminating nuclear
missiles with a range of 300 to 3,400 miles.
   The Reagan administration said the treaty banned both existing
missiles and any ``futuristic'' weapons, such as those using lasers
or beam rays, as long as the weapons had a range covered by the
treaty.
   But critics, including members of the Senate Armed Services
Committee, questioned whether the Soviets might have a different
view of the treaty and suggested that the ambiguity should be
cleared up.
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., the chairman of the Foreign
Relations Committee, said Shevardnadze's ``unequivocal statement
should allay concerns that have been raised about this subject.''
   Pell's committee sent the full Senate a report Monday that said
the Senate should approve the treaty and protect its constitutional
rights by blocking presidential attempts to change the way treaties
are interpreted.
   The 515-page report sums up the panel's three months of hearings
and its votes on the historic pact.
   The report was approved by the same 17-2 majority which
recommended two weeks ago that the treaty should be ratified by the
full Senate. The opposition votes were cast by Sens. Jesse Helms,
R-N.C., and Larry Pressler, R-S.D.
   Ratification requires a vote of 67 of the 100 senators. Leaders
of both parties estimate that 90 or more senators will support the
Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty when it finally comes to a
vote.
   Publication of the committee report means the way is finally
clear for formal consideration on the Senate floor.
   Republicans say the most contentious issue will likely be the
Democratic-backed amendment that would bar the United States from
changing the interpretation of the INF treaty.
   The amendment, approved 12-7 by the committee, arises from a
fight over the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty.
   Reagan has asserted that the White House can unilaterally change
how the ABM pact is viewed, a move that would permit expanded
``Star Wars'' testing, but congressional Democrats dispute that
claim.
   ``A presidential right to adopt a different interpretation of a
treaty, irrespective of the understanding on which the Senate based
its consent, would tend to nullify the Senate's share of the treaty
power and thus undermine a basic provision of the Constitution,''
the report said.
   ``The Senate's only recourse, to prevent its share of the treaty
power being nullified, would be to attach elaborate and numerous
conditions to treaties in order to have the Senate's understanding
become an integral and explicit part of the ratification
documents,'' the report said.
   ``Such procedures could easily overburden the treaty process to
the point of paralysis,'' it warned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880419-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 0159EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CommunityColleges     04-19 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Community Colleges,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commission Says Community Colleges Get Short Shrift</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's community colleges meet
ambivalence about their role and often ``receive the state's budget
leftovers'' when they can be of great help both to their
neighborhoods and the nation, an educational commission said today.
   ``The community college, at its best, can be a center for
problem-solving in adult illiteracy or the education of the
disabled,'' said a report by the Commission on the Future of
Community Colleges. ``It can also be the place where education and
business leaders meet to talk about the problems of displaced
workers.
   ``It can bring together agencies to strengthen services for
minorities, working women, single parent heads of households and
unwed teenage parents. ... The community college can take the lead
in long-range planning for community development and it can serve
as the focal point for improving the quality of life in the inner
city.''
   Community colleges enroll 43 percent of the nation's
undergraduates and 51 percent of all first-time freshmen, but the
schools ``encounter ambivalence in the larger community about their
role and mission, and competing priorities within the college,''
the report said.
   Such schools ``are threatened by excessive fragmentation and
division'' and increasing cultural separations and racial tensions,
the report said.
   ``We propose therefore, that the theme `Building Communities'
become the new rallying point for the community college in America.
We define the term `community' not only as a region to be served
but also as a climate to be created.''
   The commission was headed by Ernest L. Boyer, former U.S.
commissioner of education and president of the Carnegie Foundation
for the Advancement of Teaching. It conducted the study for the
American Association of Community and Junior Colleges.
   The panel said community colleges must help solve the dropout
problem or minority students will continue to leave. It recommended
that every college develop an aggressive outreach plan for
disadvantaged students.
   Among other recommendations:
   _ An ``early warning system'' to spot and help students who are
at risk of dropping out.
   _ Each community college should commit itself to recruiting and
retaining a top-quality faculty and increase the percentage of
members who are black, Hispanic and Asian.
   _Careful assessment of reading, writing and mathematical ability
of all first-time community college students and an intensive
developmental education program for those who need it.
   _Completion of a core curriculum by all associate degree
students.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
