<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ATVs     04-19 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-ATVs,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Debates Whether Flawed Ban Is Better Than No Ban At All</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge says he must decide whether to
approve a flawed consent decree regulating all-terrain vehicles or
do nothing to regulate the vehicles blamed for 900 deaths in five
years.
   ``Is it best to move in the direction of doing what one can do
to reduce it as opposed to doing nothing about it?'' U.S. District
Judge Gerhard A. Gesell said after a hearing on a proposed
out-of-court settlement between the Consumer Product Safety
Commission and five manufacturers.
   Opponents of the consent decree argued at Monday's hearing that
the agreement between federal regulators and manufacturers is
flawed because it doesn't provide for refunds to people who
purchased the vehicles, popularly known as ATVs.
   Lawyers for consumer groups and 32 states said the consent
decree also fails to protect children from the hazards of the
four-wheel machines, particularly smaller models marketed for
children, which would still be sold.
   ``We don't believe these child-sized ATVs should be sold at
all,'' said Massachusetts Attorney General James Shannon, who
called ATVs ``some of the most dangerous consumer products sold in
this country.''
   The decree would ban future sales of three-wheel ATVs unless the
manufacturers devised performance standards that would be approved
by the CPSC. It would also require warning labels on four-wheel
models and distributors would have to offer training about the safe
use of the machines to owners of vehicles currently in use.
   Gesell appeared troubled by the decree's ban on further action
by the CPSC against ATVs during the 10-year period the agreement is
in effect.
   ``The mechanism provided by Congress is stymied by the consent
decree,'' Gesell told a lawyer for the manufacturers.
   ``As I understand the decree, the agency represented here _ CPSC
_ is not able to issue a rule under the statute which would be in
many respects more severe'' than the sanctions imposed by the
consent decree, Gesell said.
   ``You take the agency out of the game, you can't tell me with
quite the same assurance the agency is going to continue to perform
its function,'' the judge said.
   Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., who is sponsoring legislation to
force manufacturers to give refunds, called that provision ``a wolf
in sheep's clothing.''
   The senator urged Gesell to modify the decree to give the agency
the option of taking further action after a year or 18 months if
the agreement has not led to safer use of ATVs.
   But Justice Department attorney Stephen Hart said the agreement
allows the government to avoid a lengthy court battle during which
it would be difficult to prove the allegations that the ATVs are an
``imminent hazard'' as defined by the consumer protection statute.
   ``This is an outstanding resolution of the matter in light of
the facts as they exist and the law as it exists,'' Hart told
Gesell. ``The government will get some of what it asked for, the
other alternative is the government will get none of what it asked
for.''
   Gesell also expressed concern about the mechanics for
supervising the decree's enforcement, saying he was particularly
dismayed that it empowered the CPSC's general counsel to extend
deadlines.
   Nevertheless, the judge said the unprecedented decree could be
``a technique that could be of great value to consumers.''
</TEXT>
