<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MarinePaint     04-19 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marine Paint,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bill Passes to Ban Common Barnacle Blocker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate has some bad news for boat owners
who hate to scrape barnacles off the hull.
   The chamber gave voice-vote approval Monday to legislation to
regulate the use of tributyltin, or TBT, a hull paint additive that
is effective against barnacles but poses dangers to other marine
life.
   The bill would ban the use of paints containing TBT on vessels
under 82 feet in length and would impose limits on the amount of
TBT that can be released into the water from hull paint on larger
vessels.
   The restrictions would last until the Environmental Protection
Agency decides on an environmentally safe release rate for paints
containing TBT, which have been regulated by England and France
because of damage to shellfish.
   Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I., said TBT ``is without a doubt the most
effective anti-fouling compound yet developed, and it cannot be
matched for preventing the attachment of barnacles, algae and other
marine organisms that hasten the decay of wood and cause drag on
boats.
   ``On the other hand, there is growing evidence that TBT is
extremely toxic and is affecting `non-target' marine and freshwater
organisms rather than just organisms that are trying to grow on
boat hulls.''
   He said TBT produces toxic effects in some marine organisms at
exposures of less than 100 parts per trillion _ ``the equivalent to
one drop of water in 100,000 tanker trucks of liquid.''
   Chafee said TBT's effects on humans are not known, although high
levels of the substance have been found in some chinook salmon by
federal researchers.
   The regulatory legislation originated in the House, which now
will be asked to consider an amendment approved by the Senate.
</TEXT>
