<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FishingPorts     04-19 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fishing Ports,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scallops Make New Bedford Nation's Richest Fish Port</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Bedford, Mass., was the nation's richest
fishing port last year thanks to a banner year for scallops,
government and industry officials say.
   Other New England fishing cities slumped because of a decrease
in fin fish such as cod and haddock, and some ports around the Gulf
of Mexico suffered from problems in the shrimp industry, analysts
said Monday.
   New Bedford led in 1987 with catches valued at $143.7 million,
up nearly 36 percent from $106 million in 1986, according to the
National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration. The 1987 figure
was a record, the agency said.
   Lee Weddig, executive vice president of the National Fisheries
Institute, a trade association, attributed New Bedford's big
increase to strong scallop harvests and scallop price increases.
   NOAA said scallops accounted for nearly half of New Bedford's
total dollar value, but made up only 21 percent of the port's catch
in weight.
   Alaskan ports also enjoyed a profitable year. Kodiak was second
to New Bedford with catches valued at $132.1 million, up from $89.8
million, and Dutch Harbor-Unalaska was up from $37.2 million to
$62.7 million, NOAA reported.
   Weddig said the healthy Pacific Northwest industry was due to
strong salmon and crab harvests and a sharp increase in exports due
to the fall of the dollar overseas.
   Nationwide, foreign sales in 1987 were more than $2 billion, up
from $1.6 billion the previous year, according to Weddig.
   Texas and Louisiana ports suffered from falling shrimp
production and prices, he said.
   Cameron, La., led the nation for the 10th consecutive year in
the amount of fish caught, NOAA reported. Cameron landings rose
from 616.8 million pounds to 672.4 million pounds, bringing it
nearly back to its 1985 level. The record was 848.2 million pounds
landed in Los Angeles in 1960.
   Pascagoula-Moss Point, Miss., was second at 391.6 million
pounds, up from 365.5 million pounds.
   More than two-thirds of the major U.S. fishing ports were up in
volume from last year, but nearly half had value decreases.
   While New Bedford enjoyed a robust year, most of the other major
New England fishing ports suffered declines in both volume and
value, according to the NOAA report.
   Down in both categories were Gloucester, Mass., Point Judith,
R.I., and Boston. Only Portland, Maine, showed increases, largely
because of the operation of the new Portland Fish Exchange, Weddig
said.
   He said decreases in cod, haddock and flounder, as well as the
emergence of the Portland exchange, led to the decline in landings
at the other New England ports.
</TEXT>
