<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Trade     04-19 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Lawmakers Deadlock Over Foreign Investment Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers are nearing final action on a
sweeping, 1,000-page trade bill, still uncertain if it will contain
a plan to force public disclosure by foreign investors of their
U.S. holdings.
   ``If you're interested in passing a trade bill, which I am, then
I think the best course of action is to drop the Bryant
amendment,'' Sen. J. James Exon, D-Neb., said Monday after
lawmakers failed to break a deadlock over the issue.
   A House-Senate panel has been stalemated for more than a month
over the amendment sponsored by Rep. John Bryant, D-Texas, which
would require public disclosure of much foreign investment within
the United states.
   Exon said that dropping the plan would reduce the chance of a
presidential veto, or if President Reagan vetoes the bill anyway,
increase the chance of an override.
   He noted there already are presidential veto threats over a
separate provision that would require 60-day notice of plant
closings and large-scale layoffs.
   The foreign ownership dispute is the last unresolved controversy
in fashioning the trade bill, which House Speaker Jim Wright,
D-Texas, said could come to the floor as early as Wednesday.
   Most of the compromise provisions were drawn up by House and
Senate conferees before the congressional recess Easter week but
they left farm items, the plant closings feature and the foreign
disclosure plan until the last minute.
   Wright told reporters he was pushing for inclusion of the Bryant
provision. But he added he would not seek to attach the measure to
the trade bill if it would ``put its life in jeopardy.''
   The speaker said that if conferees would not accept the plan ``I
would be inclined to give Bryant a run on its own merits'' by
bringing it to the House floor later as a separate bill.
   Under the plan, foreign investors would be required to register
with the Commerce Department if they owned 5 percent or more of any
American company or real estate in this country if such assets were
worth at least $5 million.
   Some of this information already must be filed with the
department but is not public record. That would change under
Bryant's plan.
   Companies with a 25 percent share in a U.S. business or property
with assets or annual sales of more than $20 million would have to
disclose much of the detailed information required of corporations
by the Securities and Exchange Commission on its 10-K form. The
items range from a list of directors and officers to a financial
balance sheet.
   Critics say the measure would reduce new capital from overseas
that helps prime the U.S. economic pump; proponents say it would
put a spotlight on foreign investment that could be harmful to
American interests.
   Most lawmakers believe the trade bill itself will clear both the
House and Senate without much difficulty. The question is whether
it will get the two-thirds support it would need for a veto
override.
   Three major petroleum industry associations called on Reagan to
sign the bill because it would repeal the windfall profits tax on
oil companies.
   ``We cannot allow the stagnation of domestic oil exploration and
production to continue,'' the groups said in a letter.
   The letter was sent by the American Petroleum Institute, the
Independent Petroleum Association of America and the Midcontinent
Gas and Oil Association.
</TEXT>
