<1ST_LINE>r p PM-ANewJackson?     04-19 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-A New Jackson?,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Adjusts Stance On Some Issues; Aide Calls It `Evolution'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson told a business group he favors
continued research on the Star Wars missile defense system and then
told an East Harlem audience a few hours later: ``We do not need
Star Wars. We need decent housing and education and day care.''
   Robert Borosage, a top adviser to Jackson's presidential
campaign, said the former civil rights activist has always
supported research on Star Wars. But it was not until the New York
primary campaign that Jackson began to readily discuss his support
for that research.
   ``Keep the research; we don't need to deploy it,'' Jackson told
the Association for a Better New York, an organization of business
and civic leaders, a few hours before his East Harlem appearance.
   An even more publicized shift in position was Jackson's
statement that he would not meet with Yasser Arafat, the leader of
the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Ten years ago, Jackson embraced Arafat at a meeting that became
a focus of Jewish opposition to his candidacy.
   During an interview on the CBS show, ``Face the Nation,''
Jackson said Arafat was an ``extreme element'' in the Middle East
and that it would be a mistake to negotiate with him.
   On the same program, Jackson said he had no plans to scrap
existing weapons in the U.S. arsenal, including many he opposed in
the past.
   Is Jackson shifting toward the mainstream as he has become a
credible challenger to Michael Dukakis' claim on the Democratic
presidential nomination?
   Ann Lewis, a top Jackson adviser, called the shifts part of a
``two-way evolution.''
   She said that as Jackson has been taken more seriously as a
presidential candidate he has been asked more substantive policy
questions and they have forced him to re-examine many of his views.
   ``His position on Star Wars has been the same since Reagan
launched it,'' said Borosage. But he conceded the candidate's
stance on any Arafat role in Middle East negotiations has changed.
   ``He believes you've got to deal with the PLO,'' said Borosage.
But, he added, Jackson also has come to believe that Arafat is too
``inciteful'' to be included in peace negotiations.
   Jackson has explained his earlier meeting with Arafat as an
effort to persuade the PLO leader to accept Israel's right to
exist. He repeatedly told New York audiences that Israel must be
guaranteed secure borders. He also has advocated an independent
Palestinian state.
   In the CBS interview, Jackson also denied having advocated
elimination of such systems as the MX missile.
   ``We've got to keep the systems we have,'' said Jackson.
   In a letter published in Monday's New York Times, Borosage took
issue with a story on Jackson's views that had appeared in the
newspaper.
   ``Mr. Jackson has never stated he `would scrap a range of
weapons systems' already deployed,'' wrote Borosage.
   However he went on to say that the candidate would oppose
further development of the Stealth bomber ``because we have just
spent billions purchasing the B-1 for the same mission.''
   In speeches, Jackson advocates a freeze in the military budget.
</TEXT>
