<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 0226EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-DelawareDemocrats     04-19 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Delaware Democrats,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jesse Jackson Wins Delaware Caucuses On Eve Of New York Primary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW CASTLE, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential hopeful Jesse Jackson
headed into today's New York primary with a new win in his column _
in Delaware's Democratic caucuses, where he handily beat rival
Michael Dukakis.
   With all 41 precincts reporting, Jackson had 86.5 delegates for
45 percent, Dukakis had 51.5 delegates for 27 percent and Tennessee
Sen. Albert Gore Jr. had four delegates for 2 percent.
   Forty-seven delegates were uncommitted for 25 percent. The
delegates selected will attend the state convention May 23, where
Delaware's 15 national convention delegates will be chosen.
   Based on the results, Jackson picked up seven delegates, Dukakis
five and three are uncommitted.
   The Delaware caucuses were overshadowed by today's New York
contest, with its primary prize of 255 delegates.
   Jackson had been organized statewide in Delaware for several
months, while Dukakis opened shop about three weeks ago. Gore has
no organization in the state.
   Before the caucuses, there had been predictions that Jackson
supporters would turn out in force. Samuel L. Shipley, the state
party chairman, predicted a heavy turnout, spurred by a Jackson
organizing drive.
   Jackson coordinator Vivian Houghton said Jackson supporters in
the state were ``fervent and committed.''
   Caucuses were being held in 41 state representative districts to
select 189 delegates to the state convention. Candidates had to win
at least 15 percent of the vote to receive a share of the delegates.
   Party leaders have stayed neutral since favorite son Sen. Joseph
Biden Jr. dropped out of the race in September.
   Biden called it quits in a campaign rocked by charges he
plagiarized in law school, plagiarized speeches and exaggerated his
academic credentials.
   Republican caucuses began April 5 and will continue until April
25 to select delegates to the GOP state convention, scheduled for
May 14.
</TEXT>
