<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 0242EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CanadianPower     04-19 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canadian Power,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Industry-Funded Study Says Canadian Power Imports Save Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Harvard University study strongly endorses
Canadian electricity imports as a cheap alternative to Mideast oil
and rejects a proposal from the domestic coal industry to limit the
hydroelectric power.
   The report, released Monday by the Energy and Environmental
Policy Center at Harvard's John F. Kennedy School of Government,
dismisses arguments that Canadian producers have unfair advantages
over domestic utilities.
   It also dismisses assertions that reliance on Canadian imports
could leave the United States vulnerable, and that government
subsidies and lower environmental standards make the exports
possible.
   Instead, it says, Canadian utilities can export hydroelectric
power at a cheaper price than it costs to build new coal facilities
because of Canada's vast water resources.
   ``Arguments about Canadian subsidies, lax environmental
standards and national security implications are not only often
factually wrong, but also divert attention from the real public
policy issue,'' said Henry Lee, executive director of the center
and co-author of the study.
   ``If Canada has greater access to inexpensive natural resources,
should the U.S. federal government limit the ability of U.S.
consumers to purchase those resources?'' Lee asked.
   The Harvard researchers estimated that the 35,300 gigawatt hours
of Canadian electricity purchased by the United States in 1986
would increase by 1995 to between 52,000 and 63,000 gigawatt hours.
A gigawatt is a billion watts.
   Canadian power imports represent only 2 percent of U.S.
consumption nationwide, but they account for about 10 percent of
the electricity used in New England and New York.
   The $75,000 study was paid in large part by utilities that
benefit from Canadian imports.
   Lee said buying large chunks of Canadian power does not pose a
national security risk since it is unlikely Canada would cut off
electricity for political reasons.
   ``The security costs of any practically attainable level of
Canadian imports are far outweighed by the national security
benefits which accrue to the United States from reducing oil
imports'' from Mideast nations, the report said.
   Rep. Nick Joe Rahall II, D-W.Va., countered, ``Political
relationships are volatile with changes in leadership, and in no
way can we use today's stable relationship (with Canada) as a basis
for the future.''
   Rahall, chairman of the House Interior subcommittee on mining
and natural resources, introduced legislation last year that would
prohibit Canadian power imports unless they adhered to
environmental safeguards similar to those in the United States.
   The study also said that Canadian imports displace mostly
imported oil and domestic natural gas, not coal.
   If all Canadian power contracts were cancelled, the coal
industry would see a 2,479 increase in jobs, but it would cost U.S.
consumers $114,123 per job, the study said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880419-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 0135EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua 3dLd-Writethru a0882 04-19 0863</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua, 3d Ld - Writethru, a0882,0883</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas, Rebels Postpone Talks For 10 Days</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Inserts 4 grafs after 6th bgng: ``Our army will... with
President Ortega warning U.S. pressure might collapse talks. Pick
up 7th pvs: Negotiations between the...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government and rebel leaders
adjourned peace talks Monday without reaching agreement after four
days, but they agreed to meet again in Managua at the end of the
month.
   Gen. Humberto Ortega, the defense minister and head of the
Sandinista government's negotiating team, read a statement signed
by both parties saying they would meet in the capital April 28-30
to continue talks on a permanent truce in the 6{-year-old war.
   Adolfo Calero, a leader of the rebels known as Contras, told
reporters the two sides were ``on the road to an understanding.''
He refused to elaborate on what they discussed during the talks.
   ``This isn't an automobile race in Indianapolis to run at 200
miles per hour,'' Ortega said. ``Our interest is to negotiate the
definitive cease-fire, but it can't be reached overnight, for which
we consider that what was discussed here was an advance and not a
failure.''
   He claimed the rebels' political directorate was being pressured
to avoid signing an agreement by the Contra military chief, Enrique
Bermudez.
   ``Our army will continue clutching their rifles to dissuade the
enemies of Sapoa, and I'm referring to Enrique Bermudez and the
guerrillas, so that they don't continue sabotaging the accords,''
Ortega said. Sapoa is the town where the two sides signed a
cease-fire agreement last month.
   President Daniel Ortega, the defense minister's brother, told a
rally Monday night that the Contra political leaders should not
cave in to what he said was pressure from the United States and
Bermudez.
   Addressing thousands of Sandinista supporters in Managua's Plaza
de la Revolucion, the president claimed Bermudez had told Contra
political leaders that if they signed a truce with the government
the rebels ``would liquidate them.''
   He said if the political leaders submit ``to the pressures of
the Yankee administration and the threats of Bermudez, they would
not continue to come to Managua and if they did it would be to
break the Sapoa accords.
   ``If this happens, it would leave us no other road but to
achieve a total victory in the military field.''
   Negotiations between the rebels and government have been
deadlocked over the so-called ``democratization'' issue.
   The Sandinistas have insisted the rebels sign a permanent truce
immediately. They say Contra delegates would then be allowed to
take part in a ``national reconciliation dialogue'' with leaders of
the country's 14 legally recognized political parties.
   Contra leaders are demanding that Sandinistas first carry out a
series of democratic reforms, or at least pledge to do so.
   On Monday afternoon, Contra leader Alfredo Cesar told a cheering
crowd the rebels will press for an end to the military draft and
the release of thousands of political prisoners.
   ``We are in Managua to negotiate with the Sandinistas the
freedom of Nicaragua and the restoration of democracy and, as long
as we do not achieve this, we will not lay down our weapons,''
Cesar told about 800 supporters in the capital.
   He spoke outside La Prensa before he and other Contra leaders
visited the editors of the only opposition newspaper.
   Cesar and five directors of the rebel umbrella group, known as
the Nicaraguan Resistance, traveled to Managua on Friday to try to
negotiate with the government an end to the war that has killed an
estimated 26,500 people.
   It was the first time the Sandinistas agreed to negotiate with
their foes in the capital. The Contras' 20-minute visit to La
Prensa was their first venture outside the Camino Real Hotel where
they have been staying.
   Contra leaders visited with Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo and
other Roman Catholic church officials in the afternoon and said
afterward they would free 40 government soldiers.
   ``At the request of the bishops we have decided to free the
Sandinista prisoners that we have in our power as a show of good
faith for national reconciliation,'' said Calero, highest-ranking
official in the Contra directorate.
   Official Voice of Nicaragua radio claimed the Contras had more
Sandinista prisoners and releasing only 40 was ``ridiculous in
seven years of war.''
   The two sides signed a peace agreement March 23 which provided
for a temporary cease-fire while they negotiated a permanent truce.
The 60-day cease-fire went into effect April 1.
   The Contras on Monday proposed that the temporary cease-fire be
extended another month while both sides seek agreement. There was
no immediate response from the government.
   Soon after the March 23 accord was signed, the Sandinistas freed
100 of the 3,300 political prisoners and promised to release the
rest as peace negotiations progressed.
   Among the Contra directors who visited La Prensa Monday was
Pedro Joaquin Chamorro, whose mother, Violeta Chamorro, is
publisher.
   His publisher father, also named Pedro Joaquin Chamorro, was
killed on Jan. 10, 1978. The assassination, widely blamed on the
right-wing government in power at the time, unleashed a revolt that
toppled President Anastasio Somoza and swept the Sandinistas into
power in July 1979.

</TEXT>
