<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 0243EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-StockStudy     04-19 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stock Study,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Program Trading Pushed January 8 Market Plunge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission
believes that heavy program trading may have helped force down
stock prices last Jan. 8, the day of the third-worst market plunge.
   In a report released Monday, the SEC said it has detected high
levels of computer-driven transactions late in that day's session,
particularly in stocks frequently traded by institutional investors
using programs.
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average plunged 140 points that day.
   The SEC, using information it obtained from the New York Stock
Exchange, said that 75.4 million of the 197.3 million shares traded
that day were sold after 2:30 p.m. Two-thirds of the decline
occurred after 2:30 p.m.
   ``This heavy late selling activity occurred on relatively little
fundamental economic news,'' the report said.
   The report stated that the role in the Jan. 8 plunge of
index-related trading _ transactions involving baskets of stocks
and futures _ ``was comparable to that during the week preceding
Oct. 19.''
   That was the day of the worst plunge in the stock market's
history, a 508-point Dow Jones decline.
   The study concluded that ``stock selling from index arbitrage
may have accelerated the steepest portion of the market decline''
that day after 2:30 p.m.
   Index arbitrage is a strategy by which institutional traders,
usually using computers, attempt to profit from price discrepancies
between stocks and stock index futures. It and other forms of
so-called program trading, in which computers guide huge
transactions, have been called factors in the stock market's wildly
surging price swings of recent months.
   The study said that only 13 percent of the shares traded Jan. 8
were generated by program selling.
   But more than one-third of the transactions after 2:30 p.m.
involving stocks comprising the Standard & Poor's 500 stock index
were made by program traders, the report said. Stocks in the
Standard & Poor's index are frequently bought and sold by program
traders.
   The report was released by Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass.,
chairman of the House telecommunications and finance subcommittee.
Markey had requested the study, which was dated April 7 and sent to
the congressman by SEC Chairman David S. Ruder.
   ``I am deeply concerned about the impact of this continued
volatility on our capital formation process and long-term economic
growth,'' Markey said in a prepared statement.
   Markey has been working on legislation designed to control
market volatility.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
