<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Canned Air,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canned Air Selling Fast In Black Sea Port</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cooperative and a factory made a tidy profit by
selling cans of air for up to $8 each, a government newspaper said.
   Izvestia on Monday ran a front-page article about sales of air
from the Black Sea port of Odessa, praising the enterprise as a
``living illustration of the possibilities of free initiative.''
   Izvestia said the state-run Odessa firm Studio was seeking
financial sponsorship for a new cooperative when it turned for help
to a factory that cans fruit, juices and jams. The factory offered
to sell thousands of cans it had purchased several years earlier
and then decided it could not use.
   The cooperative obtained the cans for 16 cents apiece,
``although it would seem the goods were completely useless,''
Izvestia said.
   The cooperative labeled the cans ``Odessa Air. Gathered on the
City's Streets During the Days of `Humor,''' and sold them on April
Fool's Day.
</TEXT>
