<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0806,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Over Much of Nation, Severe Weather Injures Four in Georgia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with damage, injuries in Georgia
from possible tornado, picking up 4th graf ``The Ohio''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain fell over much of the country Monday, with parts of Texas
receiving almost an inch and hail the size of golf balls, while
severe weather in Georgia damaged mobile homes and injured at least
four people.
   Showers were scattered from western Montana across the Idaho
panhandle and eastern Washington and south into western Utah.
Showers also reached from southern New England and southern New
York and along the Atlantic Coast through northern Florida.
   A possible tornado touched down about 9:45 p.m. at Bainbridge,
Ga., said Tim Merkison, a dispatcher for the Decatur County
Sheriff's Department. He said four people were hurt, though he did
not know the severity of the injuries.
   About 15 mobile homes were damaged and several trees were
uprooted, he said.
   The Ohio Valley, and parts of Texas and Louisiana also had rain.
Thunderstorms produced 0.86 inches of rain at George West, Texas,
with hail the size of golf balls west of the community and at
Beeville, Texas. Strong wind knocked down trees and limbs near
Beeville.
   Afternoon thunderstorms produced half-inch-diameter hail from
Zachary to Watson, La. In Atlanta, 0.79 inches of rain fell in six
hours Monday, with nearly as much in Ogden, Utah.
   Snowshowers continued in parts of Michigan, but the only report
of measurable snowfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT
was from Mount Washington, N.H., where snow cover was 41 inches
deep at noon.
   Valentine, Neb., reached 15 degrees Monday, breaking a
32-year-old record of 17 degrees. International Falls, Minn., tied
its record, 17 degrees, set in 1960.
   Temperatures at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 27 degrees at Sault Ste.
Marie, Mich., to 92 at McAllen, Texas. The morning low was 12
degrees at both Bismarck and Fargo, N.D.
   Tuesday's forecast called for snowshowers over northern Maine
and rain scattered over parts of Florida and from Montana and
Wyoming across the northern half of the Pacific coast.
   High temperatures were expected to reach the 30s and 40s over
upper Michigan; 40s and 50s from New England and New Jersey, across
the northern Appalachians, the remainder of the Great Lakes, the
upper Mississippi Valley, the northern Plains, the upper Missouri
Valley and the northern Rockies.
   Highs in the 70s and 80s were forecast for South Carolina across
Florida and west over the central Gulf of Mexico states, the
southern Plains, the desert Southwest and the inland portions of
southern California. High in the 60s and 70s were predicted for the
rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
