<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Sweden-AIDS     04-19 0139</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Sweden-AIDS,0143</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sweden Criticizes Company For Halting AIDS Research</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The health minister criticized Astra
AB, Sweden's largest pharmaceutical company, for deciding to halt
its research into AIDS.
   ``I think the company should care more about its international
image,'' Gertrud Sigurdsen was quoted as saying by the national
news agency TT.
   Astra on Friday announced plans to abandon the research, saying
it was too expensive and the competition from the United States was
too great.
   Astra employed more than 20 scientists and invested $1.6 million
annually for five years in researching AIDS, or acquired immune
deficiency syndrome.
   The company said it made ``interesting progress'' in some
medicines and plans to sell its results to other companies.
   ``The government has not been able to influence the (company's)
decision, although it has supported the research,'' Sigurdsen said.
</TEXT>
