<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Cuomo     04-19 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Cuomo,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuomo Earned More From Speaking Than From Governor's Salary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Mario Cuomo earned more as a speaker in
1987 than he did as governor, his tax returns show.
   In addition, Cuomo donated almost $90,000 of his $278,988 in
earnings last year to the state, according to the returns released
Monday.
   The Democrat's income included $134,000 from speaking
engagements and $125,988 from the state, which is slightly less
than his $130,000 gubernatorial salary because of state payroll
scheduling and tax deferring, aides said.
   He paid $44,166 in federal income taxes and $22,641 in state and
local taxes for 1987, according to the joint return filed by Cuomo
and his wife, Matilda.
   Cuomo also donated $3,855 to 14 charities.
   ``The governor's favorite charity, in this case, turns out to be
the state,'' said Cuomo spokesman Gary Fryer.
   Cuomo returned to the state $30,000 of his salary and $59,498 in
speaking engagement fees.
   Cuomo's office would not disclose the amounts organizations paid
the governor for speaking or the charities to which he contributed.
Fryer said that was at the request of some of the groups.
</TEXT>
