<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 0306EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MilwaukeeMayor     04-19 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Milwaukee Mayor,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Henry Maier Leaves Office After 28 Years</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Swearing-in at 1 p.m. EDT; lead prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The signs of change were apparent as Milwaukee
prepared to swear in a new mayor for the first time in 28 years,
bidding farewell to feisty veteran Henry W. Maier and welcoming
newcomer John O. Norquist.
   Maier, whose 28-year tenure was the longest of any big-city
mayor in the nation, was scheduled to give up the office today with
the swearing in of Norquist.
   Maier, 70, a past president of the U.S. Conference of Mayors and
National League of Cities, announced last year he would not seek
re-election because of his age.
   The 38-year-old Norquist, like Maier a Democrat, planned to
resign as a state senator this morning before being sworn in as
mayor.
   Aides said Monday that Norquist wants broader powers that would
enable him to hire and fire certain officials of this city of
636,000 who now have set terms of office. H. Carl Mueller, who
headed Norquist's transition team, said Gov. Tommy G. Thompson
supported proposed legislation to make the change.
   ``We were elected here with a mandate for change,'' Mueller
said. ``It would be an attempt to establish a true cabinet-style
government.''
   Norquist also said he would support naming a city viaduct in
honor of civil rights leader James Groppi, who died in 1985.
   Maier, who often found himself at odds with Groppi's protest
tactics during open-housing marches and other campaigns of the
1960s, vetoed the name-change proposal last year, and the Common
Council failed by one vote to override the veto.
   Maier, who fought for increased federal and state aid for
cities, marked his last day in office by taking a jab at a familiar
adversary: the city's afternoon newspaper.
   The mayor ran an advertisement in Monday morning's Milwaukee
Sentinel to respond to a column April 10 by Sig Gissler, editor of
The Milwaukee Journal. The column focused on the sometimes stormy
relationship between the mayor and the Journal.
   Gissler wrote that Maier's ``combative style, so evident in his
scornful attitude toward the suburbs, has made it hard to build a
metropolitan partnership to address grave challenges such as
economic development and racial segregation.''
   Maier, in the ad, charged that the Journal viewed the
metropolitan area with a suburban orientation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
