<HEAD>Vicar Loses Bid To Remove Church Pews To Facilitate Dancing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTLEY WINTNEY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A church court rejected a
vicar's request to remove the pews of his church to make room for
dancing during services.
   John Spokes, chancellor or chief legal officer for the diocese,
ruled on Monday after a three-day hearing that Rev. John Earp could
not make renovations to St. John's church in this town 30 miles
southwest of London.
   Among other changes, Earp had applied to the diocese to replace
pews with chairs facing each other and put an altar on wheels.
   Brian Carlisle, leader of a group opposing the changes,
testified at the hearing that the alterations would ruin the
``dignity and majesty'' of the Victorian church's interior and make
it look like a ``social club.''
   The Bishop of Winchester, the Right Rev. Colin James, said in a
statement that he and his senior staff would do ``everything
possible to work for reconciliation, mutual understanding and above
all healing in the parish.'' James is bishop of the region that
includes Earp's church.
