<HEAD>Jackson Fails to Woo Jews, Says Outspoken Civil Rights Commission
Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chairman of the U.S. Civil Rights
Commission says Jesse Jackson ought to go to Israel to prove he
isn't anti-Jewish and to repair the damage wrought by his overtures
to PLO chairman Yasser Arafat.
   Clarence Pendleton Jr. told the Heritage chain of Jewish weekly
newspapers in Southern California such a move would make ``real
overtures to the Jewish community like there was to Arafat, like
there was to Castro.''
   Pendleton, a conservative Republican who has been commission
chairman for six years, made the remarks in an interview at his San
Diego office on April 6 that was published last Friday.
   Pendleton wondered: ``Why doesn't he (Jackson) go now to Israel
and say, `I'm sorry for what happens to you, let's see if we can
get this thing straightened out.'''
   Jackson was campaigning in New York on Monday, the eve of the
presidential primary in that state, which has a significant Jewish
vote. There are 255 delegates at stake and polls have shown
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis leading with Jackson in second.
