<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Only One Ohio Debate Seen; May Exclude Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ohio's public radio and television
stations will sponsor the only televised debate between Democratic
presidential candidates scheduled in Ohio before the state's May 3
primary.
   George Zimmermann, spokesman for the network and executive
producer for the debate, said Monday it will be held in Columbus on
April 27, from 9 p.m. to 10 p.m., and will be carried live from
Columbus.
   Since the Republican nomination is virtually assured for Vice
President George Bush, the debate, moderated by Robert Seigel, host
of National Public Radio's ``All Things Considered,'' will only
involve Democrats.
   Zimmermann said the campaigns of Jesse Jackson and Sen. Al Gore
Jr. of Tennessee have tentatively confirmed the date, but
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis has a previous commitment in New
Jersey which has its primary June 7.
   Zimmermann said he is hopeful that Dukakis can re-arrange his
schedule so that he can appear with the others on the Ohio program.
``We believe it's important that Ohio voters be given a chance to
see and hear the three Democratic candidates for president on the
issues, side by side,'' Zimmermann said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Officials Certify McCrery vs. Campbell Votes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHREVEPORT, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials open the voting machines today
and certify results from a special weekend election in which
Republican Jim McCrery apparently defeated Democrat Foster Campbell
for the congressional seat vacated by Gov. Buddy Roemer.
   Unofficial returns gave McCrery only a 1,300-vote lead and, if
the victory holds up, the former Roemer aide would become the first
Republican since Reconstruction to represent northwest Louisiana's
4th District in the House of Representatives.
   Campbell, a Democratic state senator, and other party officials
refused to concede.
   ``We're not going to really say anything until we take a look at
what the official count is,' State Democratic Party Chairman Jim
Brady. ``I'm not saying it's decided at all. We're going to wait
until Tuesday and see what develops.''
   The voting machines from the nine-parish district were back in
the warehouse, where they have been locked since Saturday when
Roemer called for private guards to augment state police to keep an
eye on the machines until the official canvass of the votes.
   Unofficial returns compiled by the secretary of state after
Saturday's voting showed McCrery with 63,488 or 50.5 percent, to
62,139 for Campbell.
</TEXT>
