<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 0351EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Demjanjuk-USReax Bjt   04-19 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Demjanjuk-US Reax, Bjt,0580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conviction Strains Relationship Of Ukrainian And Jewish Americans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOROTHY GAST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters of retired autoworker John Demjanjuk
were outraged that Israeli judges convicted him as the Nazi death
camp guard ``Ivan the Terrible,'' and said the decision will rouse
anti-Semitism in America.
   Demjanjuk, a Ukrainian immigrant to the Cleveland suburb of
Seven Hills, was convicted Monday in Israel of war crimes in
connection with the deaths of 850,000 Jews at the Treblinka death
camp in Nazi-occupied Poland in 1942 and 1943.
   Peter Jacyk, a Toronto resident of Ukrainian descent who helped
raise money for Demjanjuk, said Monday the effect the verdict has
on the world view of the Jewish community will be similar to the
``crucifixion of Jesus Christ.
   ``I think people will be outraged because they know Demjanjuk is
innocent,'' Jacyk said. ``In the long run, it will have a very
negative effect on Israel and Jews. It will definitely be
long-remembered.''
   Demjanjuk, who could be sentenced to death or life imprisonment
when the court reconvenes April 25, has gotten some of his
strongest backing from Cleveland area residents of Ukrainian
descent. More than 200 people gathered Sunday at St. Vladimir's
Cathedral in Parma, a Ukrainian Orthodox church, to pray for
Demjanjuk, 68, and his family.
   ``It (the conviction) is bound to have a negative effect on the
American population's view of Israel,'' said Bill Liscynesky of
Parma, who heads the Cleveland-area United Ukrainian Organizations.
``The majority of Americans feel that Demjanjuk is innocent.''
   Liscynesky said ``telephones are probably very hot'' spreading
the word among local Ukrainians about Demjanjuk's conviction. He
said his coalition has about 20,000 active members. There are an
estimated 2 million people of Ukrainian descent in the United
States.
   ``I understand very well why they (Ukrainians) are hurting very
badly,'' said Martin J. Plax, Cleveland director of the American
Jewish Committee. ``It's like when someone gets cut and you yell
`ouch' and you start cursing. That's what they're doing right now.
In time I suspect the dust will settle and we'll get back to doing
things to bring the two communities together.''
   Plax said he was ``profoundly shocked by the sternness of the
judges' verdict.'' But a former Cleveland lawyer who helped win
Demjanjuk's extradition to Israel in 1986 said the conviction
didn't surrprise him.
   ``I think there was no doubt that he was given a fair trial,
that every possible defense was raised and thoroughly defended,''
said Alvin Lodish, a former Justice Department lawyer who practices
in Miami. ``There can be no doubt who John Demjanjuk really is.''
   Abraham H. Foxman, national director of the Anti-Defamation
League of B'nai B'rith, hailed the conviction of Demjanjuk as
``gratifying evidence that even 40 years after the Holocaust,
justice can prevail over evil.''
   Foxman said the year-long trial ``reflected Israel's commitment
to the democratic rule of law.''
   In Albany, N.Y., Deborah Rausch, who attended the trial, said on
behalf of her local chapter of Holocaust Survivors and Friends in
Pursuit of Justice, ``We commend the state of Israel for accepting
this reponsibility and we hope they will continue to prosecute Nazi
war criminals who have found haven throughout the world.''
   Elizabeth Holtzman, a New York City prosecutor who formerly
sponsored legislation in Congress to allow for deportation of Nazi
war criminals, said the conviction ``sends the world a signal that
Nazi war criminals cannot escape.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
