<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0307,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Stocks Slide On Gulf Fighting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with closing figures. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar climbed against the Japanese yen in
Tokyo Tuesday, while stock prices declined slightly following the
news of fighting in the Persian Gulf and the overnight setback on
Wall Street.
   The dollar finished the day at 124.37, up 0.59 yen from its
close of 123.78 yen Monday. It had opened the day at 124.30 yen and
fluctuated between 124.25 yen and 124.53 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average,
a sharp 222.12-point loser Monday, shed a modest 14.45 points, or
0.05 percent, closing the day at 26,657.00.
   U.S. forces destroyed two Iranian oil platforms in the gulf on
Monday in retaliation for an Iranian mine attack that damaged a
U.S. frigate on patrol in international waters last week.
   ``Participants sidestepped the market following the Middle
Eastern turmoil and the overnight setback on Wall Street,'' said
Taketomi Kikuchi of Sanyo Securities.
   A wait-and-see attitude also has prevailed since the Nikkei
index surged to a record high of 27,111.35 points last Thursday,
surpassing the 27,000-point level for the first time before falling
back, Kikuchi said.
   ``The dollar was being purchased in morning trading following
renewed tension in the Persian Gulf,'' said an exchange dealer at a
major commercial bank in Tokyo.
</TEXT>
