<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AbortionSuit     04-19 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abortion Suit,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Abortion Rights Advocates Sue To Block Parental Consent Provision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents of new abortion restrictions sued
in state and federal courts to head off provisions of a
Pennsylvania law before it takes effect next week.
   ``The goal is to block the implementation of the nation's most
restrictive abortion control law,'' Barry Steinhardt, executive
director of the American Civil Liberties Union of Pennsylvania,
said of the lawsuit filed Monday.
   ``This law seeks to make an abortion as difficult to obtain as
possible, physically, financially and emotionally,'' said Susan
Cary Nicholas, a lawyer for the Philadelphia-based Women's Law
Project.
   Gov. Robert P. Casey is confident the law, which he signed March
25, will stand up in court, said his press secretary, Robert
Grotevant.
   ``We drafted it with the constitution in mind,'' said Francis
Viglietta, a spokesman for the anti-abortion Pennsylvania Catholic
Conference. ``It will pass the constitutional muster.''
   The law is scheduled to take effect Sunday, but Steinhardt said
lawyers would press this week for court injunctions to prevent that.
   ``We have a number of reasons for believing that this law will
not go into effect as scheduled,'' said Steffan Presser, the state
ACLU legal director.
   The suit filed in U.S. District Court challenges the law's
requirement that minors obtain parental or judicial consent before
abortions. The restrictions violate rights of privacy, due process
and freedom of association guaranteed by the U.S. Constitution and
other federal laws, the suit says.
   It also challenges reporting requirements that would force
clinics and doctors that provide abortions to supply information to
the state. Those provisions could open clinics, doctors and women
seeking abortions to harassment and potentional violence from
anti-abortion activists, Ms. Nicholas said.
   A companion suit filed in Commonwealth Court is aimed at a
provision that would require indigent rape and incest victims to
report the crimes to law-enforcement agencies before they could
receive Medicaid funding for an abortion.
   The suit was filed on behalf of an unidentified Medicaid
recipient who has twice been the victim of rape and was mistreated
by police when she reported the crime, the suit says.
   Additional plaintiffs include Women Organized Against Rape, the
Elizabeth Blackwell Health Center and the counseling organization,
Choice.
   Mary Beliveau, legislative coordinator for the Pennsylvania
Pro-Life Federation, said the lawsuit seeks to ``allow the abortion
industry to keep parents in the dark'' about the health of their
children.
   ``It is inconceivable that pro-abortion groups would challenge
legislation that provides parents with the right to supervise the
health care of their minor children,'' she added.
   In 1986, the U.S. Supreme Court struck down key provisions of a
1982 law. Those provisions required doctors to make a record that
could be made public of every abortion they performed; required
doctors to inform women seeking abortions about potential risks and
available benefits for prenatal care and childbirth; and required
the presence of two doctors for abortions performed in the third
trimester.
   In December, Casey, a Democrat, vetoed an abortion control bill
that would have required notification of sexual partners or
parental notification in the case of a minor.
</TEXT>
