<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Contras     04-19 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contras,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras Return To Miami; Express Satisfaction With Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contra leaders, treated to a heroes' return by
dozens of Nicaraguan exiles here, expressed satisfaction with the
progress made during peace talks in Managua even though no
agreement was reached.
   ``We were able to come out of the four days and still keep
negotiating,'' said Adolfo Calero, one of four Nicaraguan
Resistance directors who arrived at Miami International Airport
late Monday.
   Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government and the U.S.-backed
rebels are scheduled to meet again in the capital of their country
at the end of the month.
   The peace talks that were adjourned Monday marked the first time
in the 6{-year-old war that the Sandinistas have agreed to
negotiate with their foes in Managua.
   ``Things are better than they were,'' Calero said after the
singing and cheering died down at the airport.
   ``Our major accomplishment has been to sit with the Sandinistas
face to face,'' said director Pedro Joaquin Chamorro, adding that
the climate of the talks was ``sincere.''
   ``In my opinion, the Sandinistas behaved responsibly,'' Chamorro
said.
   But he also said his expectations going into the talks were not
high, and he emphasized that the government needed to institute
democratic changes.
   Negotiations have been deadlocked over the so-called
``democratization'' issue.
   The Sandinistas have insisted the rebels sign a permanent truce
immediately. They say Contra delegates would then be allowed to
take part in a ``national reconciliation dialogue'' with leaders of
the country's 14 legally recognized political parties.
   Contra leaders are demanding that the Sandinistas first carry
out democratic reforms, or at least pledge to do so.
   The Contras and the Sandinistas last month signed a peace
agreement that provided for a temporary cease-fire while they
negotiated a permanent truce. The 60-day cease-fire went into
effect April 1.
   In Managua on Monday, the Contra leaders visited Roman Catholic
officials and editors at La Prensa, the only opposition newspaper
and whose publisher is Chamorro's mother, Violeta.
   His father, also named Pedro Joaquin Chamorro, was slain Jan.
10, 1978, in a killing widely blamed on the right-wing government
in power at the time. The slaying helped unleash the revolt that
toppled President Anastasio Somoza and swept the Sandinistas into
power in July 1979.
   Also returning here were Alfredo Cesar and Azucena Ferrey,
directors of the Nicaraguan Resistance, an umbrella rebel
organization based in Miami.
</TEXT>
