<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Reardon     04-19 0144</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Reardon,0149</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opera Singer Dies At Age 58</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Reardon, a baritone who regularly
appeared as the opera maker ``Reardon'' in the children's public
television program ``Mister Rogers' Neighborhood,'' has died of
pneumonia. He was 58.
   Reardon died Saturday at his Santa Fe home, officials of the
Pittsburgh-based program said Monday.
   Reardon's career spanned 30 years of opera and musical theater,
beginning with his Broadway appearance in ``Do Re Mi.''
   At the Metropolitan Opera in New York, he starred in many new
productions, including ``Carmen.'' His long association with
composer-conductor Leonard Bernstein included recordings of
Bernstein's ``On the Town'' and Haydn's ``Creation.''
   His last public performance was March 11 with the Buffalo (N.Y.)
Philharmonic Orchestra.
   His manager, Ethel Siegel of Washington, D.C., said there was no
funeral. She said a memorial scholarship will be established in his
name.
</TEXT>
