<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TempletonPrize     04-19 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Templeton Prize,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Award Postponed Amid Charges of Winner Fostering Anti-Semitism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presentation of the $369,000 Templeton Prize for
Progress in Religion has been postponed because of an investigation
of charges that this year's winner helped spread anti-Semitism, a
newspaper reported today.
   Inamullah Khan of Pakistan, secretary-general of the World
Moslem Congress, was to have received the award May 10, according
to an announcement last month by the sponsors of the annual prize.
He was the first Moslem to win the award, which has been presented
15 times.
   The New York Times reported that prize officers have delayed the
presentation pending an investigation that centers on complaints by
the American Jewish Committee and the Anti-Defamation League of
B'nai B'rith that Khan and his organization have fostered
anti-Semitism for years.
   Khan says he has difference with Zionists ``because the U.N.
General Assembly has declared Zionism a racist creed.'' But he
said, ``I can never support anti-Semitic feelings because I am
myself a descendant of Semitic ancestors from the Middle East.''
   The Templeton officers praised Khan last month for promoting
interreligious cooperation, and his supporters say he and his
organization have been more willing than other Islamic groups to
maintain contacts with Jews.
   But the Times reported that the newsletter of the World Moslem
Congress, while under Khan's direction, published praise of
anti-Semitic tracts and accused Jews and Zionists of controlling
U.S. politics and media.
   The newsletter, The Moslem World, advertised and endorsed ``The
Protocols of the Elders of Zion'' and Henry Ford's ``The
International Jew,'' two notoriously anti-Semitic tracts, in the
mid-1970s.
   Past recipients of the Templeton Prize include Mother Teresa,
the Rev. Billy Graham and Alexander I. Solzhenitsyn.
   Sir John Templeton, an American-born financier living in the
Bahamas, established the prize in 1972 as a religious counterpart
to the Nobel Prizes for peace, science and literature.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
