<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Markets     04-19 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises, Stocks Fall In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed higher today against the Japanese
yen in Tokyo, while stock prices declined modestly following the
news of increased fighting in the Persian Gulf and the overnight
easing on Wall Street.
   The dollar closed at 124.37 yen, up 0.59 yen from its close of
123.78 yen Monday. It had opened the day at 124.40 yen and
fluctuated between 124.25 yen and 124.53 yen.
   ``The dollar started the day substantially higher, boosted by
the overnight advance in New York, but it moved in a narrow range
throughout the day,'' said Michiko Kawai of the Bank of Tokyo.
   Trading was relatively calm as participants sidestepped the
market, watching the development of the Middle Eastern turmoil, she
said.
   U.S. forces destroyed two Iranian platforms in the gulf on
Monday in retaliation for an Iranian mine attack that damaged a
U.S. frigate on patrol in international waters.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average,
a 222.12- point loser Monday, shed a modest 14.45 points, or 0.05
percent, to end the day's trading at 26,657.
   Share prices rallied during the afternoon session to erase most
of their losses and ended little changed. The Nikkei index was down
226.64 points at the end of the morning session as participants,
nervous about the gulf fighting, sidestepped the market, traders
said.
   The release of a number of U.S. and Japanese economic indicators
later this week and the approach of the holiday-studded ``Golden
Week'' have also kept some investors on the sidelines, they said.
The week begins Friday, April 29, which is Emperor Hirohito's
birthday, which is a holiday. It includes other non-trading days on
Sunday, May 1, and three other national holidays May 3-5.
   Volume on the first-section trade was estimated at a thin 600
million shares, up slightly from 550 million shares Monday.
Declining issues outpaced advancers 509 to 375, while 174 issues
were unchanged.
   Losers include steels and chemicals. Textiles, papers and drugs
also lost ground. Electricals and oils were firm.
</TEXT>
