<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LiberaceEstate     04-19 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Liberace Estate,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Liberace Friends, Attorney, Trade Charges In Suit Over Estate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM DAHLBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer persuaded Liberace to sign a
will he didn't want shortly before his death, then ``began robbing
Liberace's grave'' by mismanaging hundreds of thousands of dollars
from the estate, an attorney says.
   Los Angeles lawyer Joel Strote, executor of the estate, wanted
Liberace's money and even went to the entertainer's Palm Springs,
Calif., home after his death and declared, ``I am Liberace,''
attorney Harold Gewerter charged during opening arguments in a
civil suit.
   But Strote testified Monday in state district court that
Liberace called him three weeks before his death and asked that the
will be updated and that longtime manager Seymour Heller be
replaced as executor by Strote.
   ``He said he did not want to use Seymour anymore and asked me if
I could do it,'' said Strote.
   Strote said the flamboyant entertainer wanted to make sure that
most of the estate went to a trust to fund the Liberace Foundation
for the Performing Arts, which provides scholarships at 22
colleges. The will named Strote trustee of the foundation.
   Outside court, Heller, who is one of the five plaintiffs,
estimated Liberace's estate at $20 million. About $2 million was
raised last week in a Los Angeles auction of Liberace's belongings.
   Gewerter charged Monday that Strote executed Liberace's will 13
days before the multi-millionaire's death and the performer had no
idea what he was signing.
   ``Liberace was in such a mental state on (Jan.) 22nd that he
couldn't understand or read independently,'' Gewerter said. ``If
(comedian) Pee Wee Herman had walked into his room and said he
wanted to be executor, he (Liberace) would have said `yes.' He
(Strote) goes into that room owning nothing and comes out with a
bag of goodies.''
   Gewerter said Strote has mismanaged hundreds of thousands of
dollars from the estate, and that Strote is spending the estate's
money on personal possessions.
   ``The fraud of Mr. Strote doesn't stop with the will,'' Gewerter
said. ``He believed he was the embodiment of Liberace. He wanted to
be Liberace. More important _ he wanted Liberace's money. Once he
became trustee he began robbing Liberace's grave.''
   The suit seeks to replace Strote as trustee with Heller,
Liberace's close friend and manager for 36 years, and Frank
DiBella, the late performer's accountant. It also seeks to remove
Strote as executor of the will.
   In his opening remarks, Strote's attorney, John O'Reilly, said
the plaintiffs were only angry that they did not get more money out
of the estate and that Strote had served well as executor.
   Strote said Liberace's doctor declared him physically and
mentally fit just before they met to sign the will at the
entertainer's Palm Springs home Jan. 22, 1987.
   ``He read what I highlighted but I don't think he read every
word,'' Strote said. ``He asked me generally what was the
importance of each paper.''
   Liberace died Feb. 5, 1987, of complications stemming from AIDS.
He was 67.
   Gewerter said Liberace had vowed three months earlier to fire
Strote, who had served as Liberace's attorney on various occasions.
   The other plaintiffs are Dorothy McMahon, Liberace's longtime
friend and housekeeper at the Palm Springs home; Cary James, a
companion of Liberace's for six years before his death; Angie
Liberace, the only living sibling of the family; and Gladys Luckie,
the housekeeper at Liberace's Las Vegas home.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
