<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BRF-Eastern-Hydraulics     04-19 0149</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF-Eastern-Hydraulics,0153</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jet Experiences Hydraulic Problems, Lands Safely</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT MYERS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hydraulic problem forced a Fort
Myers-bound Eastern Airlines jet to use a backup system as a
precaution, but the plane landed safely, officials said.
   Flight 697 from Boston, carrying 115 passengers and six crew
members, landed shortly after 6 p.m. Monday at Southwest Regional
Airport, said V.H. Steed, a duty officer with the Federal Aviation
Administration in Atlanta.
   No emergency was declared, according to Steed and Virginia
Sanchez, a spokeswoman for Miami-based Eastern.
   After realizing there was a problem with the Boeing 707's
primary hydraulic system, the flight crew switched to the backup
unit, which functioned perfectly, Eastern shift manager Mike Hemmer
said.
   As of Sunday, FAA inspectors had checked about 200 of Eastern's
267 aircraft under an investigation announced last week. Whether
the Boeing 707 had been checked was uncertain, Eastern officials
said.
</TEXT>
