<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BankTheft     04-19 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Theft,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank's Safe-Deposit Boxes Looted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 300 safe-deposit boxes were cleaned out
after thieves cut a bank's alarm system and drilled a hole through
a concrete floor into the vault, police say.
   Everything of value contained in the boxes at the Liberty Bank
and Trust Co. in downtown Boston was stolen over the weekend,
police said.
   ``They knew just where they were going and acted in a
calculating and intelligent manner,'' said a police source The
Boston Globe quoted without naming.
   Bank officials and investigators from the FBI and Boston police
wouldn't comment, but the Globe quoted police sources as saying the
robbery was believed to have occurred over several hours Sunday.
   Bank President William Fitzgerald and investigators declined to
estimate the value of the loss.
   According to police, the thieves were believed to have gained
entrance to the bank's second floor through an emergency fire door,
although there was no evidence of forced entry. Several panels from
a dropped ceiling were pushed out, and alarm wires behind them
apparently were cut and a bypass wire slipped into place.
   The thieves entered an unlocked and empty second-floor vault,
from which they drilled a hole into the first-floor vault that
contained the safe-deposit boxes, the Globe reported.
</TEXT>
