<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PennState-Blacks     04-19 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Penn State-Blacks,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meeting With Penn State President A Beginning, Student Leader Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A meeting with Penn State University
President Bryce Jordan and his top administrators represents only
the first step for improving life for blacks at the school, says a
black student leader.
   ``I think the students are aware that this is just a beginning
and what's going to be needed is further organization, further
commitment and further negotiations,'' said Robert Blair, a
spokesman for the Black Caucus, a student organization.
   Before the meeting, Jordan announced he would withdraw
trespassing charges and the threat of university sanctions against
89 students arrested for a 15-hour sit-in that ended April 9.
   Blair and nine other black student leaders negotiated with
Jordan and four senior administrators for five hours Monday on
minority issues ranging from financial aid for blacks to creating a
vice president for minority affairs.
   ``I think we made some progress,'' Jordan said. ``There were
some things we had to say no to. There were some things we could
say yes to and some things we had to look at.''
   Jordan agreed to create a vice president for minority affairs
and also agreed in principle to work toward a goal of 8 percent
black student enrollment and faculty membership.
   Last fall, Penn State failed to reach a court-mandated goal of 5
percent black enrollment.
   Of the school's 67,000 students, a total of 2,424, or 3.6
percent, are black. Penn State has 57 black faculty members, or 1.6
percent of its 4,100 instructors.
   Jordan said he couldn't commit the university to more financial
aid for blacks.
   ``We think your arguments make good sense. ... We simply are not
going to make budget decisions in this setting,'' he said.
   Before the negotiations began, Jordan granted amnesty to the
protesters.
   More than 150 students occupied the telecommunications building
April 8 after Jordan canceled a meeting with student activists
because ground rules could not be reached in advance.
   Jordan had sent two administrators to meet with student leaders
behind closed doors, but the students demanded an open meeting.
   Students still in the building at dawn the next day were charged
with trespassing and faced university sanctions, including possible
dismissal.
</TEXT>
