<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Armenians     04-19 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Armenians,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Being Replaced After Rioting in Sungait</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many police officers in the Azerbaijan city of
Sumgait are being replaced because they were incapable of dealing
with ethnic rioting that claimed the lives of at least 32 people,
an official said.
   Nikolai Demidov, deputy minister of internal affairs, said in an
interview Monday on the Vremya television news program that younger
people, many of whom recently served in the army, were replacing
the policemen. He did not say how many officers were being removed.
   Riots broke out in Sumgait on Feb. 28 and continued for three
days as Armenian demonstrators demanded annexation to Soviet
Armenia of Nagorno-Karabakh, which is part of the neighboring
Azerbaijan republic. About three-quarters of the residents of
Nagorno-Karabackh are Armenians.
   Soviet officials rejected the annexation demand but promised a
program to improve cultural and economic development in the area.
   Demidov said, ``Unfortunately, many Sumgait policemen were not
up to the extreme conditions'' during the rioting.
   He did not elaborate but balanced his criticism with praise,
citing a police Col. Filipov who he said blocked a mob from
attacking a bus.
   Soldiers and internal security forces sent to Sumgait to quell
the violence succeeded without firing their weapons, he said.
   Demidov said the death toll of 32 was correct, and repeated the
government and Communist Party claims the rioting was instigated by
criminal elements.
</TEXT>
