<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Tibet     04-19 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Tibet,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tibet Remains Closed To Individual Travelers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese authorities do not plan to reopen Tibet
to the thousands of backpackers who streamed through before
pro-independence protests began last year, a U.S. official said.
   ``The thrust of the message is Tibet is open and they intend to
keep it open but they intend to keep it (travel) in groups,'' said
J. Stapleton Roy, deputy assistant secretary of state, on Monday.
   Roy said that in talks with authorities during a four-day visit
to Tibet, they did ``not rule out'' the possibility of further
unrest in the region's capital, Lhasa.
   He said he carried no message from the U.S. government but
expressed concern for human rights in Tibet and pressed authorities
to allow more journalists and U.S. congressmen to visit.
   Roy said he did not discuss Chinese conditions for the return of
the Dalai Lama, Tibet's spiritual and former political leader, who
fled to India in 1959.
   Individual travel into Tibet officially was halted shortly after
three protests in September and October by Buddhist monks and
others opposed to Chinese rule.
   Enforcement of the provision that all tourists to Tibet join
guided tour groups slackened early this year but has tightened
since a protest March 5 in which at least five people died.
   Chinese authorities alleged after the protests in September and
October that some foreigners joined in or encouraged participants.
   In 1987, 43,500 foreigners visited Tibet, spending $15 million,
according to official figures. Many arrived individually from
Chengdu in southwest China or overland from Nepal, which borders
Tibet.
   Roy said authorities told him future travelers would be required
to travel in groups charging at least $27 per day for expenses.
Such a restriction probably will discourage travel by youthful
backpackers on tight budgets who in the past often spent one or two
months at a time in Lhasa mingling with Tibetans without close
official supervision.
   He said there were ``at most a handful'' of foreigners in Lhasa
while he was there, Wednesday through Sunday. The Western-managed
Lhasa Hotel, with 476 rooms, has had only about two dozen guests at
a time since the protests began, he said.
   Nevertheless, Roy said local authorities claimed tourism had
increased 133 percent in the first quarter of 1988, with 1,184
visitors.
   Roy said Lhasa was not heavily patrolled by armed police, and he
encountered no roadblocks. ``The general impression is one of
surface normality, but you didn't have to dig deep to find views
that there was ... potential for future problems,'' he said.
   Roy said that when he raised the issue of U.S. concern over
reported human rights violations in Tibet, ``the response was that
we and the Chinese have differing views on the human rights
question.''
   China has denounced any criticism of its human rights policy as
interference in its internal affairs. It acknowledges holding some
political prisoners in Tibet, but denies charges they are
mistreated or that religious rights are not respected.
   Roy said authorities responded positively to his request that
more U.S. congressmen be allowed to visit Tibet. Four visited Lhasa
on April 7.
   He said officials told him journalists were allowed to visit if
they apply for permission. In practice, almost all reporters'
requests to visit Lhasa have been denied since last year's
protests, when 14 foreign journalists were expelled from Tibet.
   Chinese Communist troops entered Tibet in 1950, ending a
theocracy headed by the Dalai Lama.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
