<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica     04-19 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Use Tear Gas To Break Up Student Protests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police used tear gas to
disperse hundreds of high school students who demonstrated in
support of the ``Sharpeville Six,'' a group of blacks waging a
court battle to escape the gallows.
   Police said tear gas was fired after youths outside a secondary
school threw stones at police vehicles in Mitchell's Plain, a large
township for mixed-race people outside Cape Town.
   Journalists said police ordered the protesters to leave and used
tear gas and batons to disperse other students marching to the
meeting.
   No injuries or arrests were reported in Monday's clash.
   Boycotts of classes were reported at mixed-race and black
schools throughout the Cape Town area. Some boycotters reportedly
protested the suspension of teachers while others supported the
Sharpeville Six, five men and a woman convicted of complicity in
the 1984 mob killing of black town councilor. The fate of the six
is in limbo while their lawyers seek to reopen the trial to
consider claims that police coerced a state witness.
   P.J. Van Zyl, registrar of the Pretoria Supreme Court, said on
Monday that the Transvaal Province attorney general's office was
studying the application to reopen the trial. He said a decision
would be made by April 27.
   A one-month stay of execution was granted March 17, a day before
the six had been sentenced to hang. The stay would have expired
Monday but was extended indefinitely last Friday when defense
lawyers submitted the application.
   Many Western and Soviet-block governments have sent appeals for
mercy for the Sharpeville Six. President P.W. Botha has refused to
commute the death sentences, saying he won't interfere in the
judicial process.
   No evidence was produced that the defendants contributed
physically to the councilor's death. They were convicted under the
doctrine of ``common purpose,'' which held them responsible for
being part of the mob that committed the killing during
anti-apartheid riots.
   Apartheid is South Africa's system of racial segregation whereby
the minority 5 million whites control the government and the
economy and the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs.
</TEXT>
