<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 0652EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Cuba-O'Connor     04-19 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuba-O'Connor,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>O'Connor Says He Hopes Visit Brings Cubans Closer to Christ</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TINA SUSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAVANA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government-controlled media has barely
mentioned that Cardinal John O'Connor of New York is visiting Cuba.
   O'Connor, the highest-ranking U.S. Roman Catholic leader to
visit Cuba in 29 years, said before leaving for the Caribbean
nation on Monday night that he hoped the trip would bring Cubans
closer to God.
   ``I ask that you remember me in your prayers, that my trip to
Cuba may bring our brothers and sisters there closer to Christ and
His Blessed Mother,'' he said Monday in a written statement in the
Dominican Republic. The archdiocese of New York provided reporters
with copies of the statement.
   O'Connor spent two days in the Dominican Republic and plans to
arrive in Havana today, after spending the night in the city of
Santiago, Cuba.
   There has been no mention of the cardinal's trip in the official
Communist Party daily Granma. A four-paragraph story appeared
Sunday in Juventud Rebelde (Rebel Youth), the newspaper of the
Young Communist League.
   O'Connor was invited to Cuba by the country's bishops to
commemorate the 200th anniversary of the birth of the Rev. Felix
Varela, a Cuban priest who spent many years in New York and became
vicar general of the archdiocese.
   Cuban leader Fidel Castro, who came to power in 1959 and
established a communist government, recently has eased restrictions
on religious activities in the Caribbean nation.
   There was no word on whether O'Connor would get to talk to
Castro during his four-day visit.
   Earlier Monday, O'Connor addressed an AIDS conference in the
Dominican Republic with a plea that victims of the incurable
disease be treated with compassion and dignity.
   ``We have 17 Catholic hospitals in the archdiocese of New
York,'' the Roman Catholic prelate said. ``I have personally urged
that any person coming to any one of these hospitals seeking
assistance because of the possibility of AIDS be treated with
absolute, total and unconditional dignity.''
   ``I spend many nights in one of those hospitals, St. Clare's,''
visiting AIDS patients, he said. ``Often, I empty their bedpans,
comb their hair or mop their brow ... I have realized more and more
that every single one is a sacred human person made in the image
and likeness of almighty God.''
   Following his address at Catholic University in Santo Domingo,
the 68-year-old O'Connor flew by private plane to Cuba.
   Cuban Archbishop Jaime Ortega said in a newsletter made
available Monday that O'Connor's visit underlines the ``brotherly''
relations between Roman Catholic churches in Cuba and United States.
   To worshipers, he said, there is no such thing as one church
being more ``influential'' or ``powerful'' than another. ``These
adjectives have been taken from the language of international
politics and translated without thought sometimes to church
relations,'' Ortega said.
   Catholics account for 41 percent of Cuba's 10.2 million people,
as compared with 92 percent of the Dominican Republic's 6.6 million
people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
