<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Slightly Higher In Europe, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose slightly in early European trading
today as markets awaited developments in the Persian Gulf. Gold
prices were lower.
   Foreign exchange dealers said Monday's initial flurry of
dollar-buying in response to U.S. and Iranian attacks in the gulf
had calmed down.
   But one dealer at a major West German bank in Frankfurt said any
new reports or rumors of clashes were likely to boost the dollar
significantly.
   Otherwise, traders said, the market's underlying bearishness
toward the U.S. currency would likely reassert itself.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.59 yen to a closing 124.37 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted fractionally lower at 124.35 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday's
rates:
   _1.6624 West German marks, up from 1.6615
   _1.3755 Swiss francs, up from 1.3745
   _5.6495 French francs, up from 5.6410
   _1.86495 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8630
   _1,236.25 Italian lire, up from 1,234.37
   _1.2335 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2322
   In London, the British pound fell back from a six-year high
against the dollar. It cost $1.8915 to buy one pound, cheaper than
late Monday's $1.9015.
   Bullion dealers said trading was quiet as gold prices eased in
response to the dollar's slight gains.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $457.75 a troy ounce and
at midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $456.55. Both were down from Monday's late bid
of $459.25.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $456.75, down from $458.50 late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 39 cents to close at a bid
$457.59.
   Silver also fell in London where it was selling a bid price of
$6.42 a troy ounce compared with $6.49 late Monday.
</TEXT>
