<HEAD>Baseball Cap Sparks Drive-By Shooting That Leaves 6-Year-Old Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A baseball cap that was the wrong color
apparently sparked a drive-by shooting that left a 6-year-old girl
dead and four family members wounded, the girl's brother said.
   ``It started with this hat,'' said Martin Saucedo, 13, who
suffered a minor stomach wound in the attack Sunday night. An
argument with suspected gang members who tried to take his blue
Kansas City Royals cap apparently prompted the attack, Martin said
Monday after returning to his Compton home.
   ``The guys that jumped me said it was a gang hat and I should
give it to them. I said no, I bought it with my own money at the
Paramount swap meet and it was mine.''
   During a fight with a suspected gang member over the hat Sunday,
Martin's parents called deputies. But the gang members apparently
returned.
   Martin's sister Irma was struck in the chest and killed by one
of about two dozen bullets that ripped through the family's home
while they were watching ``America's Most Wanted,'' an anti-crime
television program, authorities said.
   The girl's parents, Salvador Saucedo, 39, and Maria Hernandez,
39, were wounded and were hospitalized in critical condition today,
said sheriff's Deputy Dan Cox. Her 7-year-old brother, David
Sanchez, and a cousin were reported in fair condition.
   Three other family members, including an infant, were unhurt.
   ``Shootings happen every night. I don't want to stay here,''
Martin's 16-year-old sister, Alexandra, said Monday as she sobbed
and clung to a photo of her slain sister.
   Authorities investigating the attack were seeking two gunman who
apparently fired a high-powered rifle and semi-automatic pistol
from lime green Cadillac, then fled.
   ``The investigation so far indicates it was a gang-related
retaliation shooting,'' said Deputy Hal Grant, ``although we're not
yet sure exactly who it was targeted against.''
   Martin Saucedo is not known to be a gang member, said Detective
R.M. Graves.
   Meanwhile, Mayor Tom Bradley warned in a speech Monday that the
police department's recent crackdown on gangs, which has included
weekend sweeps that have resulted in hundreds of arrests, will
continue.
   ``As mayor, I am resolved that we will not surrender one square
inch of people's turf to gangs and drugs,'' Bradley said. ``We are
in a war, and the enemy is within _ poisoning our children and our
neighborhoods.
</TEXT>
