<HEAD>Grammy Goose Wins A Round Against Granny Goose</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PETALUMA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Grammy Goose of babywear has won a
round in court against the Granny Goose of potato chips.
   ``I assume they'll go to trial,'' said Sandy Gotelli, who runs a
babywear store called Grammy Goose. ``After all, they've carried it
this far.''
   On Monday, a judge refused to order her to stop using the name
Grammy Goose, deciding against a preliminary injunction sought by
Oakland potato chip maker Granny Goose.
   Sonoma County Judge Lloyd von der Mehden said the company would
not suffer any ``dilution'' to its trademark if Gotelli continues
to use a logo at her business showing a bonneted goose with the
name ``Grammy.''
   He said that based on the evidence presented at a hearing in
February ``it is doubtful'' that Granny Goose could prevail at a
trial.
   Granny Goose attorney Katherine Spelman had no immediate comment.
   ``I'll have to talk with my clients,'' she said.
   The judge said that Gotelli would be hurt financially if she had
to change the name and logo of her store.
