<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CuomoLawsuit     04-19 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuomo Lawsuit,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parties In Savings Lawsuit Settle Amicably</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nasty legal fight that pitted New York Gov. Mario
Cuomo's son and a group of business associates against the founders
of a Florida savings and loan has ended with an out-of-court
settlement.
   In a joint statement issued Monday, the settlement with the
dissident shareholders was called ``economically attractive to the
shareholders, and operationally prudent for the Fensters,'' the
founding family.
   The family, which now owns 24.9 percent of the stock in
Oceanmark Federal Savings and Loan Association, will acquire the 37
percent interest in the institution owned by Andrew Cuomo and his
associates. Newspapers in Broward County reported that the price
was about $10 a share.
   Under the agreement, Lynn Fenster Smith will be reinstated as
acting chairwoman of the board. She was ousted in the battle over
the company.
   Smith, in a press release, said, ``The statements made in the
heat of the moment were unfortunate. I regret any personal hardship
this purely business dispurt may have caused Mr. Andrew Cuomo. I
have always considered him an outstanding professional.''
   The parties and their attorneys agreed, as part of the
settlement, that they would have no further comment on the
settlement or its terms, which are subject to the approval of the
Federal Home Loan Bank.
   The Fensters founded the thrift in North Miami Beach in 1986.
   Lynn Fenster Smith filed suit in December against some dissident
shareholders of Oceanmark, charging that thay had moved to assume
control of the institution without going through proper federal
channels.
   After Ms. Smith filed suit, Andrew Cuomo countersued, accusing
her of libel and defamation.
   ``The settlement will allow us to return to the business of the
thrift,'' said Ms. Smith.
   Sheldon Goldstein, the largest minority shareholder and a Cuomo
associate, said that ``two years ago, we thought that we could all
work together to build a strong institution.''
   ``Unfortunately, sometimes even relationships forged with the
best of intentions don't work out,'' said the Rockland County,
N.Y., real estate developer.
   Andrew Cuomo, 30, is a Manhattan lawyer who also has been his
father's chief political adviser since the elder Cuomo's successful
run for governor in 1982.
</TEXT>
