<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 0856EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Denmark-Nuclear     04-19 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Denmark-Nuclear,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nuclear Arms Policy Prompts Political Crisis in Denmark</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANK POWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prime minister today called
parliamentary elections to resolve a political crisis over the
country's ban on peacetime nuclear weapons.
   Prime Minister Poul Schlueter said a more strictly enforced ban,
which the leftist opposition approved last week, ``goes beyond the
limit where Denmark's full membership in NATO is put in danger.''
   Britain and the United States, fellow members of the military
alliance, have criticized the tighter ban. Britain has threatened
to forgo NATO maneuvers in Denmark.
   Schlueter, who heads a governing center-right coalition, called
the elections for May 10.
   In the latest elections in September, his four-party coalition
lost seven seats to control 70 of the parliament's 179 members. It
has kept enough support on economic issues to command a majority
but lost 23 votes on defense issues since Schlueter took office in
1982.
   The opposition's new policy requires the government to notify
visiting warships that nuclear weapons are banned in Danish ports.
Until now, Denmark has simply announced a general policy and
assumed individual foreign vessels were observing it.
   Defense Minister Bernt Johan Collet has said the reinforced ban
would be put in abeyance until after the election.
   The new ban fell short of measures adopted by New Zealand
demanding that ship captains affirm their vessels have no nuclear
weapons. That policy prompted the United States to break off
military cooperation with the south Pacific nation.
   Schlueter said today Britain had vowed to bow out of military
maneuvers to practice reinforcing Denmark in wartime because it
would have to disclose whether its ships carried nuclear weapons.
   U.S. Secretary of State George Shultz said Friday the U.S.
government was ``deeply distressed'' with the new Danish ban. He
said the U.S. policy of never disclosing the presence of nuclear
weapons ``is central to the U.S. ability to fulfill its NATO
commitments. We are not going to change it.''
   NATO Secretary General Lord Carrington also said the Danish
action could have ``extremely serious consequences'' for the
16-nation alliance.
</TEXT>
