<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 0938EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Sea-TacCrash     04-19 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sea-Tac Crash,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigators told of Previous Dash 8 Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM COUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A flaming engine blamed for the crash-landing of
a Horizon Air turboprop last week had emitted a strong odor of fuel
before an earlier flight, an investigator said.
   National Transportation Safety Board member Joseph T. Nall,
heading the investigation of Friday's accident here, also discussed
other engine problems suffered by de Havilland Dash-8s at a news
conference Monday night.
   The crash-landing injured 19 of the 40 people aboard as it
smashed into a passenger ramp at Seattle-Tacome International
Airport. The plane was one of 10 Dash-8s in the Horizon fleet.
   Pilot Carl Carlson also told investigators of a maintenance log
entry April 8, a week before Friday night's crash, that described a
strong fuel odor coming from the same engine that caught fire
Friday night, Nall said.
   ``There was some maintenance done and nobody complained of the
smell after (the April 8 report),'' Nall said.
   Nall noted that in 1987 an engine fire in a Horizon Air de
Havilland Dash-8 had forced an emergency landing.
   And Nall said that Carlson told NTSB investigators that a
different Dash-8 turboprop he was flying earlier this month
suffered a brief power loss in one of its Pratt & Whitney engines.
   Nall said although the engine immediately regained power,
Carlson aborted that flight and landed. Carlson told the safety
board he understood from other pilots that such a problem ``was not
uncommon but it was certainly not a regular occurrence,'' he said.
   ``The investigation is obviously intense at this point,'' Nall
said.
   The June 1987 engine fire aboard involved fuel spilled into the
engine cowling and forced the plane, which had taken off from
Sea-Tac, to make an emergency landing at Boeing Field, Nall said.
   Horizon Air changed maintenance procedures after that fire, Nall
said, adding, ``We don't know at this point if the (June '87 and
the latest fire) are related.''
   ``...The direction and focus of the investigation is obviously
to determine why there was the fuel in the right (cowling over the
engine) _ passengers noted there was fuel there before the crash _
and the cause of the ignition of that fuel,'' Nall said.
   Passengers in the plane that crashed Friday told investigators
they could see fuel accumulated on the right wing.
   The Dash-8 engine is made by Pratt & Whitney Canada, and Nall
said the NSTB planned to take a long, hard look at all U.S. planes
with similar engines.
   Horizon Air President John Kelly said Monday that airline crews
checked engines on the company's fleet of Dash-8s, but found no
problems that would have led to a fire like the one that preceded
Friday night's crash.
   Three of the 19 injured passengers remained hospitalized Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
