<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Gulf-FortCampbell     04-19 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Fort Campbell,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fort Campbell Security Tightened In Wake of Persian Gulf Clashes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT CAMPBELL, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security at Fort Campbell Army Base
has been tightened because of clashes between U.S. forces and
Iranian forces in the Persian Gulf, but the Army's chief of staff
said no Army personnel were being alerted for combat duty.
   Residents and personnel on the base have been asked to be alert
to ``suspicious and inquisitive strangers,'' unidentified vehicles
and abandoned cars or packages, and to keep unused areas around
home and work secured.
   ``This is FORSCOM-wide,'' Maj. Randy Schoel, public affairs
officer for the 101st Airborne Division, said Monday. ``We have not
been singled out,''
   FORSCOM, or the U.S. Army Forces Command, directs the activities
of about 950,000 active and reserve troops, about two-thirds of the
Army's ground combat forces.
   Schoel said he did not know of any specific threats to military
installations that might have caused the extra precautions.
   Gen. Carl E. Vuono, on a routine visit to the base to assess the
readiness and training of the troops here, declined Monday to
speculate if there was a possibility Army personnel might be called
to combat.
   ``There are no plans to deploy the 101st to the Persian Gulf,''
he said, adding that the Army could execute any mission and that
soldiers are ``ready to go on a continuous basis.''
   Only Navy and Marine Forces have been involved in the Persian
Gulf action so far.
</TEXT>
