<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Strike,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federally Mediated Talks Last 20 Minutes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contract negotiations between scriptwriters
and producers broke off again after a meeting with a federal
mediator and no new talks are scheduled in the six-week-old strike.
   Each side accused the other of intransigence Monday. The
deadlock could affect the networks' announcement next month of
their fall schedules, with production of new shows and their pilot
episodes thrown into question.
   The Writers Guild of America had requested a meeting with the
Alliance of Motion Picture and Television Producers, which the
guild struck on March 7 over issues of residual fees from foreign
markets and hourlong shows sold into syndication.
   ``They had nothing new to offer. They said, `We have no change
in our position,''' alliance spokesman Herb Steinberg said of
Monday's meeting. ``They just called the meeting to tell us that. I
don't understand it.''
   But Guild spokeswoman Cheryl Rhoden said the alliance,
representing about 200 studios and producers, insisted that writers
accept their final offer from March 6, the day before the
9,000-member union struck.
   ``At a time when the industry is at a standstill, the guild
regrets the companies' unwillingness to deal seriously with
writers' proposals and to continue to negotiate,'' Ms. Rhoden said.
   She said the session presided over by federal mediator Leonard
Farrell lasted only 20 minutes.
   Until writers are willing to discuss the producers' final offer,
``We saw no reason to continue the meeting, or to schedule another
meeting,'' said Steinberg.
   Producers have said several times that they are standing by
their final offer. The alliance has said its proposal would raise
writers' pay by $50 million over three years, even though it would
reduce residual payments for some one-hour TV shows.
   Writers say their own analysis of the offer shows it would
result in a loss of more than $37.8 million for its members.
   The strike has caused several television shows, such as
``Moonlighting,'' ``L.A. Law,'' and ``The Cosby Show,'' to fall
three or four shows shy of a full seaso3ptk.WkKkCC
</TEXT>
