<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MarathonNewspage 1stLd-Writethru a0506 04-19 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marathon Newspage, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0506,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One-Second Lead Secures Trophy For East African Runner</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to raise Mota into lead; picks up 6th
graf, `In the wheelchair...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ibrahim Hussein made Boston Marathon history with
a one-second winning margin, while Rosa Mota was five minutes ahead
of her nearest competitor as she scored her second consecutive
victory.
   Hussein, of Kenya, bolted past fellow East African Juma Ikangaa
on Monday with 100 yards left, becoming the first African to win
the 26-mile, 385-yard race.
   His margin surpassed the two-second victories of Bill Rodgers
over Jeff Wells in 1978 and Alberto Salazar over Dick Beardsley in
1982.
   Hussein won in 2:08:43, the second fastest time in Boston. Rob
de Castella finished in 2:07:51 in 1986. Hussein was within two
minutes of the world record of 2:06:50 set by Ethiopia's Belayneh
Dinsamo in Sunday's Rotterdam Marathon.
   Mota, of Portugal, completed Monday's marathon in 2:24:30,
compared with her 1987 winning time of 2:25:21. She was five
minutes ahead of her competition.
   In the wheelchair competition, Moussetapha Badid of France beat
the world record by 6 seconds with a time of 1:43:19.
   The marathon had a heavy international flavor since the top
Americans plan to run in the U.S. Olympic Trials. They will be held
next Sunday in New Jersey for men and the following Sunday in
Pittsburgh for women.
   Hussein and Mota each won $45,000 and a car valued at more than
$35,000. The 92nd running of the world's oldest marathon drew about
6,700 official entries.
</TEXT>
