<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iran-Iraq     04-19 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Fires Missiles Into Iran, Iranian Jets Hit Faw</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq fired missiles into Tehran and other
Iranian cities today as Iranian warplanes blasted the Faw
peninsula, which the Iraqis recaptured in a major land offensive.
   The official Iraqi News Agency, monitored in Nicosia, said one
long-range missile was fired into Tehran, one into Shiraz and a
third into Isfahan, the 16th century capital of the Persian Empire.
   Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency, also monitored in Nicosia,
reported the missiles crashed in residential neighborhoods, killing
and wounding civilians. It gave no casualty figures.
   Iraq has fired 135 missiles into Tehran, 22 into Isfahan, two
into Shiraz and 22 into Qom, seat of Iran's religious hierarchy,
since the resurgence of the so-called ``war of the cities'' Feb. 29.
   Iran says it fired 59 such projectiles into Baghdad, the Iraqi
capital, and dozens into other Iraqi cities in the same period.
   Tehran Radio reported Iranian warplanes staged 16 successful
bombing raids on Iraqi positions in the Faw peninsula.
   Iraqi troops, led by the Presidential Guard, retook Faw and
forced the Iranians to retreat to the eastern flank of the Shatt
al-Arab waterway in a two-day battle. Iran had occupied the
peninsula in an offensive in February 1986.
   It was the first time Iraq had launched a major ground offensive
since the early years of the 7{-year-old war.
   There were no reports of major ground combat in the region today.
   Thousands of Iranians were killed or wounded in the thrust,
named ``Blessed Ramadan'' after the Moslem fasting month, the Iraqi
News Agency reported.
   ``Victorious Iraqi armed forces entered Faw town today and
hoisted the Iraqi flag,'' the state-run agency reported Monday.
   Salvos of gunfire thundered over Baghdad and other Iraqi cities
and people took to the streets to rejoice, the agency said.
   Iranian state-run news media on Monday charged that U.S.
helicopters attacked Iranian troops to support the Iraqi offensive.
It accused Washington of ``direct involvement'' in the gulf war.
   Pentagon officials denied the claim.
</TEXT>
