<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HairFlap     04-19 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hair Flap,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cafeteria Refuses To Rehire Worker With Do, Despite ACLU Complaint</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM PAUL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cafeteria that fired an employee for having
an ``extreme'' hairdo refuses to re-hire her despite a formal
complaint filed by the American Civil Liberties Union.
   ``If her hairstyle is in conformity with our policy, then she
can have her job back,'' said John Fountain, an attorney for
Mobile, Ala.-based Morrison Inc., which fired Renee Randall April 4
from its Morrison Cafeteria in Annapolis.
   Ms. Randall, 19, says she had been told not to return to work
until she changed her long ponytail ``cornrow'' hairstyle.
   ``Not only is this policy ridiculous but it is discriminatory
against blacks,'' Stuart Comstock-Gay, executive director of the
Maryland ACLU chapter said at a news conference Monday to announce
the complaint filed with the federal Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission. ``It ay not be intended to be racism, but black girls
are the only ones who wear this style.''
   Ms. Randall, 19, wears her hair in tightly braided cornrows with
a ponytail in the back, Comstock-Gay said in an interview. ``The
fall-back part is a black-red, black-orange _ there is a slightly
different hue to it.''
   Fountain said by telephone that the company objects to the
ponytail, not to Ms. Randall's cornrows.
   ``Apparently it was the ponytail that was standing on her head
about six or eight inches,'' Fountain said. ``And the color of the
hair was different than that of her normal hair, which combined to
make the hairdo extreme.''
   Fountain said another employee in the Annapolis store has a
cornrow hairstyle that is acceptable.
   Ms. Randall said she knew of no customers who had complained
about her hairdo before she was removed from her job. She paid for
the hairstyle and she shouldn't be forced to change it to please
her employer, she said.
   ``She certainly wants her job back and we're going to try to
convince (Morrison's Cafeteria) to give her her job back,''
Comstock-Gay said.
   Ms. Randall has not talked with Morrison management since she
was told to leave April 4, he said.
   Morrison Inc. operates more than 150 cafeterias, primarily in
the South and East, Fountain said.
   Comstock-Gay said if the complaint before the EEOC runs its full
course, it may be six months or longer before a decision is
rendered. ``I think she may have to look for (another job),'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
