<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0459 04-19 0681</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0459,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says U.S. Gulf Action ``Appropriate''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Dukakis on Middle East, New York primary in top
9 grafs, picking up in 5th graf pvs, But aides; cuts last graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis, trying to end
confusion over his position on fighting in the Persian Gulf, said
today the U.S. action against Iran ``was appropriate under the
circumstances.''
   The Massachusetts governor, who was looking for a victory in
today's presidential primary to propel him toward the nomination,
greeted subway commuters in Queens and stopped for a visit at the
T-Bone Diner before returning to Boston.
   Dukakis made a brief statement to reporters on the Persian Gulf
situation but took no questions on the issue during a news
conference on the steps of the diner. On Monday he had told one
reporter he considered the U.S. action a ``measured response'' but
then refused to comment at two news conferences.
   ``Based on the facts that I have, I think the president took the
appropriate action,'' he said today. ``It was a measured response.''
   He said it was ``a responsibility of the international community
to do something about'' the long Iran-Iraq war in the region. He
mentioned an embargo on shipments of arms.
   Dukakis called the New York campaign ``a wonderful experience.''
   ``I hope I can do well today and win today, and I hope I can
come back as the nominee,'' he said. ``It's been a terrific,
exciting, interesting couple of weeks and I hope if all goes well
today a sign of things to come.''
   Dukakis was returning to Boston for the day before traveling to
Philadelphia's Democratic Party Dinner in the evening, an event
held one week before Pennsylvania's presidential primary. He
planned to return to New York to be with supporters when the
state's primary returns are counted tonight.
   Campaigning back and forth across the state on the eve of New
York's primary, the Democratic front-runner generally refused to
speak with reporters about the quickly changing developments in the
Middle East.
   But aides confirmed he told one reporter early in the day that
he considered the U.S. attack on the platforms a ``measured
response,'' language considered supportive of the action.
   When reporters traveling with him asked for explanations,
Dukakis declined to come talk to them on the plane and sent two
aides to respond instead.
   Madeleine Albright, campaign foreign policy adviser, said that
because events were shifting so rapidly, ``he felt he didn't want
to continue with the initial statement.''
   Asked if he had withdrawn the statement or stood by it, she
said, ``A combination of several series of escalations makes one
question whether it was an appropriate reaction.''
   As he departed his campaign jet a final time in New York Monday
night, Dukakis turned away from a reporter who asked about the
issue. Dukakis referred the questions to campaign press secretary
Mark Gearan, who had already told reporters, ``Given how the story
has developed, he's withholding comment.''
   The 11th-hour flap came against a backdrop of caution by the
candidate, who could go a long way toward the nomination with a
victory in New York, and following a campaign in which rival Albert
Gore Jr. accused the Massachusetts governor of displaying foreign
policy inexperience.
   Dukakis urged crowds throughout his final full day of
campaigning in New York to ignore polls showing him in the lead and
to help get other supporters out to vote, saying turnout would be
the deciding factor.
   ``I pay no attention to polls, and I hope you pay no attention
to polls,'' he told college students in Rochester.
   At a lunchtime rally in Manhattan, Dukakis appeared with his
actress cousin Olympia Dukakis and spoke optimistically.
   ``Here on the eve of the New York primary, I just want to say to
all of you that I'm grateful for your support, grateful for all
you've done, and we're looking forward to a great victory tomorrow
here in the state of New York, and we're going to get it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
