<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Agent-Coroner     04-19 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Agent-Coroner,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coroner Claims Secret Service Agent Terrorizing Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCEVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A county coroner has accused a U.S.
Secret Service agent of subjecting him to ``utter terror'' in an
effort to block an inquest into the death of the agent's
2{-year-old daughter.
   The federal agency's Atlanta office said no disciplinary action
is planned against the agent.
   Agent Robert E. Edwards of Duluth, northeast of Atlanta, has
filed a lawsuit seeking to block an inquest by Gwinnett County
Coroner Randy Simpson into the death of his daughter, Brittany Leah
Edwards, arguing there is no evidence of foul play.
   Snellville and Gwinnett County police officers said in
affidavits filed in that lawsuit that Edwards told them he was
conducting his own investigation of Simpson, the Gwinnett Daily
News reported Sunday.
   Among other things, Edwards said he was checking whether Simpson
had paid his taxes, the officers said in the affidavits.
   Simpson accused Edwards of ``abuse, harassment and utter terror
to me and my family.''
   Edwards told the newspaper he did not abuse his position.
   ``In no way did I ever insinuate that it was an official Secret
Service investigation,'' he said.
   William R. Hoskyn, who heads the Secret Service office in
Atlanta, said ``our people looked at it'' and found no reason to
discipline Edwards.
   Asked in a Monday night telephone interview if the matter is
closed, Hoskyn said, ``At this point, right.''
   Brittany died Aug. 24. Records at Joan Glancy Hospital show
Edwards said he had given her a hot dog for supper and that she
regurgitated parts of it when he gave her mouth-to-mouth
resuscitation after his wife found her in bed with no pulse.
   Both Simpson and Medical Examiner Gerald Gowitt initially told
police they found ``nothing remarkable'' about the case, but
Simpson later sought an opinion from Fulton County Associate
Medical Examiner Saleh Zaki.
   Zaki said he found no evidence that the child choked on
partially chewed food. Gowitt now says no explanation for the death
has been found.
</TEXT>
