<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Marines-Homosexuals     04-19 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marines-Homosexuals,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Women Discharged From Marines Because Of Lesbianism
Investigation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PARRIS ISLAND, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two women have been discharged from
the Marine Corps as a result of a continuing investigation of
lesbianism at the Marine Corps Recruit Training Depot, a Corps
spokesman said.
   The women, whose names were not released, were given honorable
discharges, Maj. Robert McLean, the depot's public affairs officer,
said Monday.
   ``Although not charged under the Uniform Code of Military
Justice, the two were administratively discharged by reason of
homosexuality as provided for in accordance with Department of
Defense policy,'' said McLean, who said he didn't know how long
they had been in the Corps.
   ``Under the circumstances in their case, their conduct in the
opinion of the command did not warrant judicial action. However,
their conduct was contradictory to established standards of conduct
and specifically violated DOD policy on homosexuality,'' McLean
said.
   The Department of Defense operates under a policy that
``homosexuality is incompatible with military service,'' and the
uniform code makes homosexuality a crime.
   The women, discharged Friday, were the first released as a
result of the investigation, which started in December and
primarily involves the Fourth Recruit Training Battalion, where all
female recruits are trained.
   Five other women have been charged with indecent acts and are
involved in criminal proceedings.
   A hearing for one of those women, Cpl. Barbara J. Baum,
concluded Monday when a Beaufort County sheriff's deputy testified
he found his former girlfriend, a Marine, in bed with Ms. Baum.
   Ms. Baum, 23, of Mishawaka, Ind., has been charged with indecent
acts with women, sodomy and obstruction of justice. She has been
suspended from her military police duties at the depot.
   After reviewing testimony from the two-day hearing, the hearing
officer will make a non-binding recommendation of action to Ms.
Baum's commanding officer. Recommendations could range from a
court-martial to no action.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
