<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Nail-Gun Suicide, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0564,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Stabs Estranged Wife, Kills Self With Nail Gun</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to UPDATE with woman's condition</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MERRIMACK, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 33-year-old man stabbed his estranged
wife with a hunting knife early today, then killed himself with a
shot to the head from a high-powered nail gun, police said.
   Patricia Lecam, 28, survived and fled through her bedroom window
to a neighbor's house with her three young children, police said.
She was in fair condition at a hospital this morning, officials
said.
   Deputy Chief William Mulligan said police heard what sounded
like a single gunshot when they arrived at the home in response to
a report of a burglary in progress at 1:08 a.m.
   A search turned up William Lecam's body lying in the woods about
150 yards behind the house, Mulligan said. He had shot himself in
the head with a nail gun, Mulligan said.
   Nail guns are used in construction to save time. Most are driven
by compressed air fed through hoses, but Mulligan said this one
apparently used cartridges containing a small explosive charge.
   Lecam had been arrested in February on charges of assaulting his
wife, Mulligan said.
</TEXT>
