<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 1120EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-BillCollection     04-19 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Bill Collection,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Makes it Easier to Recover Debts Owed by Dead People in
Oklahoma Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today made it easier for
creditors to recover debts owed by dead people.
   The justices, voting 8-1, revived a claim by an Oklahoma bill
collection agency that said it unfairly was denied the chance to
recover part of a hospital bill owed by a former patient who died.
   The agency, Tulsa Professional Collection Services Inc., is
seeking to collect $14,657 from the family of the late H. Everett
Pope Jr.
   Pope ran up a $142,000 bill at St. John Medical Center in Tulsa
from Nov. 23, 1978, until he died the following April 2. Insurance
covered all but the amount sought by the bill collector.
   Pope's family published a newspaper notice to creditors after
his will was admitted to probate in July 1979.
   Oklahoma law requires that any creditor claiming money from an
estate file such a claim within two months of the probate notice.
   Tulsa Professional Collection Services, which missed the
deadline, said it was denied due process because it was not
notified directly of the probate proceedings.
   The Supreme Court today said the agency has a legitimate case.
   Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, in her opinion for the court, said
if the Pope family knew about the collection agency or could have
determined its identity by a reasonable effort it was required to
notify the creditor directly _ by mail, for example _ about the
probate proceedings.
   The court set aside a decision by the Oklahoma Supreme Court in
favor of the Pope family and ordered further lower court
proceedings to determine whether the Pope family knew the
collection agency was owed money or whether the agency's identity
was ``reasonably ascertainable.''
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist dissented.
   The case is Tulsa Professional Collection Services vs. Pope,
86-1961.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
