<1ST_LINE>r i PM-People-Margaret     04-19 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Margaret,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug Charge Dropped Against Prime Minister's Ex-Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors today dismissed charges of marijuana
possession against Margaret Kemper, the ex-wife of former Prime
Minister Pierre Elliott Trudeau.
   Ms. Kemper had been charged March 17 after Royal Canadian
Mounted Police used a search warrant to seize a package at her home.
   Federal prosecutor Keith Ward said a defect in the warrant would
have made successful prosecution impossible.
   A copy of the search warrant used at Ms. Kemper's home said an
informer in British Columbia told police Ms. Kemper would be
receiving a pound of marijuana through the mail in eight separate
packages.
   Ward said the problem with the warrant was that the marijuana
was not delivered until sometime after the warrant was signed. He
said the pollice officer who requested the warrant had told the
court that the marijuana had been received.
   Ward said he had decided to drop the charge.
   ``I am the prosecutor, the one who received the case,'' Ward
said. ``This was my decision.''
   He denied any suggestion that Ms. Kemper received special
treatment.
   ``It has been treated like any other three-dash-one (possession
charge) as far as is possible,'' Ward said. ``I've never seen so
much press interest in a three-dash-one.''
   Ms. Kemper, 39, did not have to appear in court on the charge. A
conviction could have carried a maximum fine of $1,000 or six
months in jail or both, although lesser penalties are usually
imposed.
   Trudeau and his wife were divorced in 1983. She married Ottawa
real estate developer Fried Kemper the following year, with whom
she has one son.
</TEXT>
