<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GamblingIndictments     04-19 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gambling Indictments,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor of Chicago Suburb, Two Others, Indicted in Alleged Gambling
Ring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suburban police chief's undercover activity for
the FBI has resulted in federal gambling indictments of the mayor
and two other men, prosecutors say.
   ``I've taken an oath to follow the law,'' Police Chief Anton
Graff said on Monday, ``and I feel nobody is above the law, even
the mayor.''
   Mayor Kenneth Fisher of Dixmoor was charged Monday with
conspiracy to commit racketeering, racketeering, lying to a federal
agent and obstruction of justice, said Assistant U.S. Attorney
Steven Miller.
   The mayor was accused of taking bribes to allow a gambling
operation in the town for five years, Miller said.
   Benjamin Laster of Downers Grove and Samuel Perry of Calumet
City were indicted on charges of racketeering and conspiracy,
prosecutors said.
   Miller would not comment on the nature of the alleged gambling
operation, but Graff said it was primarily bookmaking on horse
races.
   The indictment said the operation was based at two taverns, one
of them owned by Laster.
   Valukas called Graff the hero of the operation, saying the
police chief was offered bribes by Laster to protect the gambling
operation, but notified the FBI of the bribe attempt.
   Graff began secretly working for the FBI in March 1986,
officials said.
</TEXT>
