<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Harris-Education     04-19 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Harris-Education,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harris Asks Bennett To Stop `Wall Chart' Comparisons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Joe Frank Harris says a federal ranking of
state education efforts is unfair and incomplete, and he wants the
Education Department to stop its annual ``wall chart'' comparing
state-by-state improvements.
   The report ``fails to acknowledge the diminished role of the
federal government in improving education, while holding individual
states up to public criticism for failure to meet unspecified
federal expectations,'' Harris said in a letter to Education
Secretary William Bennett.
   ``Premature reporting on education programs, improvements and
achievements is discouraging to those who are implementing major
reforms in public education. ... Such improvements can only be
reached by long-term committment,'' Harris said in the letter,
mailed Friday and distributed to reporters Monday.
   Bennett has been using the wall chart for five years to show the
educational performance of each state.
   In the latest chart, released in February, Georgia was 20th in
combined Scholastic Aptitude Test scores, 48th in graduation rates,
44th in per-pupil expenditure, 40th in student-teacher ratios and
27th in average teacher salaries.
   Harris' letter, which was drafted by state education officials,
complained that the Education Department's statistics are wrong. It
repeated complaints about using SAT scores, saying the test is
weighted more as a college admissions test in some states than
others.
   It said the teacher salary comparisons do not take into account
each state's cost of living, and it noted that some states include
general equivalency diploma holders as high school graduates.
   Valena Plisko, director of elementary and secondary planning at
the U.S. Education Department, defended the chart, saying it ``has
been effective in prodding the states to improve their
performance.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
