<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites SUB a0426 04-19 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites, SUB, a0426,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st item, CORRECTING 1st name to James, sted Charles, in
3rd graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Band leader Glenn Miller's career
might not have been quite as successful had the founders of this
Tennessee River city picked a different name 150 years ago.
   After all, ``Pardon me, boy, is that the Montevideo choo choo?''
doesn't really sing, does it?
   Montevideo was one of several possibilities considered by land
commissioners when they were naming the new town at Ross's Landing
in 1838, says James Livingood, a Hamilton County historian.
   Other nominees were Lookout City, Albion and the eventual
winner, the Cherokee Indian word for ``rock coming to a point,'' a
reference to Lookout Mountain.
   ``There was spirited debate,'' Livingood said Sunday during a
program marking Chattanooga's 150th birthday.
   The commissioners settled on Chattanooga, Livingood said,
because one observer noted that although the sound of the name was
perhaps outlandish, the city's success would make the name
``pleasant and familiar, and, besides, there will be not another
like it anywhere in the world.''
   That prediction didn't exactly pan out _ there is a town in
Oklahoma with the same name _ but Chattanooga has come a long way
in the last century and a half, say those who have governed it in
recent years.
</TEXT>
