<1ST_LINE>u a PM-AbandonedChild 1stLd-Writethru a0484 04-19 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abandoned Child, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0484,0607</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Darlwin Carlisle To Leave Hospital</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to update with girl leaving hospital,
picking up at the 8th graf previous, beginning ``Darlwin lived.''
Darlwin for child and mother is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 9-year-old girl whose frostbitten lower legs
were amputated after she was abandoned in an unheated building
walked out of a hospital today, and doctors said she had most of
the abilities and all the energy of a cheerful youngster.
   Darlwin Carlisle, who has been fitted with artificial limbs,
limped very slightly but smiled and held two dolls when she walked
down the front steps of La Rabida Children's Hospital.
   She was accompanied by her great-grandmother, Katie Carlisle,
her aunt, Sallie Carlisle, and a cousin, Crystal Carlisle. Darlwin
will live with her great-grandmother in Gary, Ind., where she was
found three months ago.
   ``She's in very good spirits,'' said Roberta O'Shea, her
physical therapist. ``She's very excited to be going home. She
won't need physical therapy anymore. As you can see, she walked out
fine.''
   ``She's been doing wonderfully,'' said Dr. Paula Jaudes,
Darlwin's physician at La Rabida. ``She can ride a bicycle, she can
roller skate. We took her to a ballgame over the weekend.''
   Darlwin's father, James Carlisle of Fort Wayne, Ind., said he
had hoped to regain custody of his daughter but decided he had
little chance of convincing the courts because he and his wife,
Alice, already have two small children.
   Darlwin lived with her mother, Darlwin Britt, in Gary, before
being found Jan. 17 by a construction worker in the family's
unheated home in a padlocked apartment building. Authorities said
the girl apparently had been locked inside the freezing attic
several days earlier by her mother, who allegedly abandoned the
girl.
   Britt, 25, has pleaded innocent to charges of felony child
neglect.
   Doctors at the University of Chicago's Wyler Children's Hospital
determined they could not save Darlwin's lower legs from
frostbite-caused gangrene, and amputated them 6 inches below the
knees Jan. 23.
   The girl was transferred to La Rabida, also a University of
Chicago hospital, on Jan. 29 to be fitted with artificial limbs and
be trained how to use them.
   La Rabida staff members say they will miss Darlwin _ even though
she had an urge once in a while to roller skate in the halls.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``She has her permanent legs now and puts them on and off by
herself,'' Jaudes said. ``She also puts on and takes off her own
socks. She'll have a counselor in Indiana, but the physical
problems are gone.''
   The physician said Darlwin will be attending a regular
elementary school in Indiana, not a special school for the
handicapped.
   ``You can't consider her handicapped,'' said Jaudes.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Before she was abandoned, Darlwin had been a third-grader at
Gary's Daniel Webster School, where a fund has been set up for her.
   Because of the intense public interest and support Darlwin
received after she was found, La Rabida authorities said they
planned to bar reporters from interviewing her or her family.
   While she was being treated at Wyler, Darlwin received a bag of
mail a day on average from well-wishers, hospital officials said.
More importantly, the public contributed more than $120,000 to pay
for Darlwin's medical treatment and future welfare.
   The bill at Wyler alone was $27,020. The bill at La Rabida was
$18,000 in early March, and was then growing at the rate of about
$600 a day. A current figure was not available.
</TEXT>
