<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 1155EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Tunisia-Israel     04-19 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Tunisia-Israel,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tunisian Envoy Says Evidence Points to Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tunisian Ambassador Habib Ben Yahia said today
his country has evidence that Israel carried out last weekend's
assassination of a Palestinian leader in Tunisia.
   Ben Yahia said the most conclusive piece of evidence was the
presence of a Boeing 707 aircraft with Israeli markings off the
Tunisian coast at the time of the assassination.
   The plane, carrying sophisticated electronic equipment, was used
to jam telecommunications around the town where Khalil al-Wazir
lived, he said. The plane's registration number was 4X977, he said.
Israel's international aircraft designation code is ``4X.''
   Ben Yahia said the government-appointed inquiry panel had found
that the commandos used 9mm Israeli-made Uzi submachine guns to
kill al-Wazir, one of the top leaders of the Palestine Liberation
Organization, two bodyguards and a Tunisian gardner. Reports from
Tunisia said the attack was carried out by seven people.
   He said the team used false Lebanese passports to enter Tunisia,
driving two Volkswagen minibuses and a Peugeot car rented from a
Tunis car rental agency to reach al-Wazir's home. The cars were
later found abandoned on a beach 10 miles from the scene of the
attack, he said.
   The inquiry panel is still investigating whether the commandos
got away by boat, he said.
   In all, Ben Yahia said, the preliminary investigation had
determined the ``unequivocable responsibility of the Israeli
government'' for Saturday's assassination of al-Wazir by a commando
team.
   Unconfirmed reports from Israel say the operation was carried
out by navy frogmen, commandos and the Mossad intelligence agency.
Israel has refused to confirm or deny allegations of its
involvement.
</TEXT>
