<HEAD>Americans Set Up Base Camp on World's Third Highest Peak</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American team scaling 28,162-foot
Mount Kanchenjunga, the third-highest peak in the world, has
established a base camp half way up, it was reported Tuesday.
   The expedition set up its camp 16,334 feet up the Himalayan
mountain's flank at Pangpema on April 3, according to reports
reaching Katmandu on Tuesday. The Americans are trying to climb the
peak from its northern side.
   The 14-member team is led by Carlos P. Buhler, 34, a
mountaineering teacher from Bellingham, Wash.
   The peak ranks as the third highest mountain in the world after
29,064-foot K2 and 29,028-foot Mount Everest, also in the Himalayas.
</TEXT>
