<1ST_LINE>r p BC-NewYorkAt-A-Glance     04-19 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-New York At-A-Glance,250</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are the methods for picking
delegates from New York to attend the 1988 Democratic and
Republican national conventions this summer.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DEMOCRATS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Method: Primary
   Date: Tuesday, April 19
   Presidential filing deadline: Thursday, March 3, 1988
   Pledged delegates:255 Super delegates: 20 TOTAL: 275
   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, April 19
   Selection of delegates: Dates not yet determined.
   
   New York Democrats hold a direct-election primary to pick 167
pledged national convention delegates from congressional districts.
   The state's remaining 88 pledged national convention delegates
will be allocated among presidential candidates in proportion to
the results of the April 19 primary.
   Those delegates would be picked by the state committee at a
meeting to be held between May 15 and June 14. Candidates for those
slots have to file a statement of candidacy no later than five days
before the state committee meeting.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>REPUBLICANS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Method: Primary
   Date: Tuesday, April 19
   Presidential filing deadline: Thursday, March 3, 1988
   Delegates: 136
   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, April 19 and a date not yet
determined.
   Selection of delegates: Dates not yet determined.
   
   New York Republicans elect 102 of their national convention
delegates directly from the April 19 primary ballot. These
delegates, three of whom are elected from each of 34 congressional
districts, are pledged to a presidential candidate or they run
uncommitted.
   The remaining 34 delegates from New York serve at large and are
picked by the Republican State Committee. The date has not yet been
determined.
</TEXT>
