<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brian Holland, Lamont Dozier and Eddie Holland
found out how sweet it was to be loved as they were inducted into
the Songwriters Hall of Fame.
   The three performed their songs ``How Sweet It Is To Be Loved by
You'' and ``Baby I Need Your Love'' at the awards banquet Monday
night. They shared the spotlight with Mary Wilson, who was a
Supreme when that trio became famous singing Holland-Dozier-Holland
songs.
   Film clips accompanied the induction of the late Sir Noel
Coward, who was seen singing his ``Mad Dogs and Englishmen,'' and
Leroy Anderson, shown playing his ``Syncopated Clock'' on the piano.
   The National Academy of Popular Music, which sponsored the 19th
annual awards banquet, gave its lifetime achievement award to
television perennial Dick Clark, who said he never wrote a song.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spanish balladeer Julio Iglesias went
ahead with a performance despite complaints by Filipino musicians
and a court order.
   The Philippine Federation of Musicians Inc. asked a court to
block the concerts, arguing they violated the Filipino musicians'
code of ethics and were an insult to local performers who were
excluded.
   The court issued an order banning Monday's performance, but
Iglesias went ahead with his third of four scheduled performances.
About 1,000 people paid the equivalent of $150 apiece for the
dinner show.
   Iglesias, who was once married to Filipino socialite Isabel
Preysler, arrived Thursday with his own 40-member band.
   ``I fly all over the world with my band,'' he said. ``You could
say it is my wife. Would you change your wife for a new one? No
way.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PERTH, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Queen Elizabeth II on Tuesday began her
11th visit since her coronation, this time to help celebrate the
country's bicentennial, marking the arrival of the British convicts
who settled Australia.
   Two thousand people welcomed the queen and her husband, and
Prime Minister Bob Hawke flew from Sydney to greet them.
   The queen will spend 22 days, traveling 30,175 miles through
five states. During her stay, she will open a new parliament house
in Canberra, Expo '88 in Brisbane and a stockman's hall of fame in
the Outback.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talent _ and a few strategic chocolate chip
cookies _ were just the ticket for actress Allyce Beasely to land
her first meaningful television role.
   ``I don't think I ever met an Italian who went to see her
parents without food,'' Ms. Beasely, who now plays Agnes Dipesto on
``Moonlighting,'' says in the April 23 issue of TV Guide. ``So I
baked chocolate chip cookies and arranged them on a paper plate and
brought them into the audition.''
   She got the part as an Italian daughter of the coach on NBC's
``Cheers.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AZUSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Los Angeles Dodgers infielder Jeff
Hamilton, awakened by a loud bang two days after moving into his
new home, found his car in a hole created when his carport floor
collapsed, officials said.
   Hamilton found his 1987 Camaro in shambles Monday morning.
   Fire Capt. Raymond Stone said the department responded to a
report of a gas leak and found the collapsed floor had severed a
gas line.
   Hamilton's home was not damaged, Stone said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Author Norman Mailer, singer Beverly Sills and
Donald and Ivana Trump were among the guests at a marriage that has
joined two billionaire families.
   Laura S. Steinberg, 25, and Jonathan M. Tisch, 34, were married
Monday at the Central Synagogue. The reception was held in Great
Hall of the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
   Mrs. Tisch's parents are Barbara and Saul P. Steinberg, chairman
and chief executive of Reliance Group Holdings Inc.
   Tisch, president of Loews Hotels, is the son of Joan and Preston
Robert Tisch, president and co-chief executive officer of the Loews
Corp. and former U.S. postmaster general.
   The bridegroom's uncle, Laurence A. Tisch, is chairman of CBS.
   At the couple's engagement party last year, a member of the
Tisch family joked: ``If they get married, it will have to be
cleared by the SEC.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anthony Perkins, the evil anti-hero of the
Hitchcock thriller ``Psycho,'' will play two roles, actually
different sides of the same person, in his next film, officials
said Tuesday.
   Perkins will play both star characters in a film of Robert Louis
Stevenson's 1886 tale ``The Strange Case of Dr. Jekyll and Mr.
Hyde,'' the story of a doctor who led a second life in the form of
villain Edward Hyde.
   Perkins, 52, said he will try to play the characters without
special makeup because that ``would have given him too much of a
monstrous effect.''
   ``Dr. Jekyll had problems and turned into Mr. Hyde after
experimenting with drugs,'' said the actor, adding that he did not
dabble in drugs himself.
   Perkins' co-star will be Glynis Barber, star of a popular
British television detective series, ``Dempsey and Makepeace.''
Officals said they will begin shooting at an undecided date on
location in London and Budapest, Hungary.
</TEXT>
