<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brown-MTV     04-19 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brown-MTV,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brown University, Protecting Image, Rejects MTV Coverage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brown University has rejected plans by
the cable television station MTV to cover its spring celebration
for fear of being portrayed as a party school, an official said
Tuesday.
   Student organizers turned down MTV's request to cover the
four-day series of concerts and parties after Robert Reichley, the
school's vice president for university relations, expressed strong
disapproval.
   Reichley said he was disturbed by last year's MTV coverage,
which featured spring parties at the University of Connecticut,
Syracuse University, Indiana University and San Diego State.
   ``It was very clear to us that they emphasized all of the party,
social and drinking side of the thing,'' Reichley said. ``I just
don't think we have any desire to fall on our own spear and expose
ourselves to that kind of thing.''
   Eric Broudy, director of the Brown news bureau, also watched the
tape.
   ``People were seeming out of control,'' Broudy said. ``What we
didn't want was to have Brown portrayed as a big party.''
   Doug Herzog, MTV's senior vice president of programs, disagreed
with Brown's interpretation of the tapes.
   ``When we go to any campus, we try to represent more than just
one aspect of a school,'' Herzog said Tuesday through a
spokeswoman. ``Although most schools welcome our presence, we
understand Brown's position.''
   The spokeswoman, Tina Exarhos, said this year's program would
feature San Diego State, Indiana, Tulane University and the
University of Missouri.
   Brown has been in an unflattering spotlight several times in the
last few years, including the highly publicized December trial in
which an insurance executive was acquitted of charges that he
organized a prostitution ring involving Brown students.
   Keith Wexelblatt, co-chairman of the Spring Weekend planning
committee, said he was disappointed but agreed with the
administrators' decision.
</TEXT>
