<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--InterpolAttack     04-19 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Interpol Attack,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Charged in 1986 Attack on Interpol</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man believed to be a member of the leftist
terrorist group Direct Action was charged Tuesday in the 1986
bombing of the international police agency Interpol.
   Georges Cipriana was charged by investigating magistrate
Jean-Louis Brugiere with complicity in attempted homicide and
destruction of property with explosives, according to court sources
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Two powerful explosions on May 16, 1986, injured a police guard
and extensively damaged Interpol headquarters, located in the Paris
suburb of St. Cloud.
   At least two men were in a nearby car while two other men
planted the bombs, police said. A fifth man may have driven a
getaway car, police said.
   On Monday, Jean-Marc Rouillan, who police say was one of the
founders of Direct Action, was charged in the bombing.
   In 1985, Direct Action claimed 16 bomb attacks in the Paris
area. In 1986, about a dozen bombings were claimed by the terrorist
group, which has since been virtually dismantled and its leaders
arrested and tried.
   Interpol is the central information agency for the police in 138
member countries.
</TEXT>
