<HEAD>Students Who Skipped Class Friday Face Punishment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All 3,000 students who stayed away from
classes for a ``skip day'' that ended in gang violence face
punishment from school authorities.
   The party in a park ended Friday when gang members opened fire
and wounded five in a crowd of 300 high school students who had
taken the day off.
   Superintendent Robert Fortenberry said Monday that those who
skipped without a valid excuse will receive a ``zero'' for that
day's grades and assignments.
   The punishment will be more severe for students taking part in
the shootings and those who already have chalked up a high number
of absences, Deputy Superintendent Dan Merritt said.
   Many parents are calling Fortenberry's office complaining that
he's being too hard on the students about the traditional ``skip
day.''
   Six people have been arrested and charged so far in the
shootings. Disciplinary hearings will be held for students and gang
members who carried guns at the park or broke other laws,
Fortenberry said.
   ``If they had weapons, I'll recommend to the Jackson School
Board that they be expelled,'' Fortenberry said.
</TEXT>
