<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Protest     04-19 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Protest,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jews Protest Peacefully for Right to Emigrate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 35 Soviet Jews seeking to draw attention to
their demand to emigrate prior to the visit of U.S. Secretary of
State George P. Shultz demonstrated peacefully Tuesday at the
Moscow visa office.
   Scores of Soviets stopped to watch the demonstrators display
banners saying ``End Lawlessness,'' ``Let Us Go to Our Children and
Grandchildren,'' and other slogans.
   About a dozen uniformed police were on hand, and after about
five minutes one of them approached the protesters and asked them
to take down their signs. They complied, and there were no arrests.
   One of the protesters, Yuli Kosharovsky, said the protesters
support the meetings between top U.S. and Soviet officials leading
up to the May 29-June 2 summit meeting.
   ``We want the dialogue between the Soviet Union and America to
continue, and continue productively,'' Kosharovsky said. ``But we
want to stress that our destiny here is terrible.''
   Kosharovsky said he has been refused permission to emigrate to
Israel for 17 years because of ``unlawful decisions by anonymous
bureaucrats.'' He said officials have said he had access to state
secrets while working in a factory in the Ural Mountain city of
Sverdlov.
   Shultz is to arrive in Moscow on Thursday for the latest in a
series of monthly contacts leading up to the summit meeting. Both
sides are trying to work out an agreement to cut long-range nuclear
missiles by 30 percent to 50 percent.
   But Shultz also has brought up human rights issues in the
meetings with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze,
Mikhail S. Gorbachev and other top officials.
   Shultz plans to meet with refuseniks at the home of a U.S.
diplomat during his visit to Moscow this week.
   Another refusenik in the crowd, Tanya Zeman, said those who have
not received permission to leave the Soviet Union are getting
desperate.
   More than 8,000 Jews were allowed to emigrate in 1987, including
such well-known figures as Josef Begun, Vladimir Slepak, and Ida
Nudel. The 1987 total was higher than recent years but still far
below the 1979 total of more than 51,000.
   The Geneva-based intergovernmental Agency for Migration said 944
Jews were allowed to emigrate in March, the highest monthly total
since July 1981.
</TEXT>
