<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NursingHomeInsurance     04-19 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nursing Home Insurance,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consumer Reports: Nursing Home Insurance Not a Good Buy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Insurance to cover the costs of nursing home
care has been promoted increasingly in the last few years, but
probably isn't a good buy for most Americans, a national consumer
group said Tuesday.
   And anyone considering such coverage should study the policy
carefully, Consumers Union warned. Even insurance sales
representatives are confused about what coverage is being offered,
officials of the group said at a news conference.
   Consumers Union rates more than 50 long-term care policies in
the May edition of its magazine, Consumer Reports, and finds some
fault with every one of them.
   ``The private insurance system cannot spread its costs over a
large enough number of people to make coverage affordable to the
millions who need it,'' Consumers Union President Rhoda Karpatkin
said.
   Only the federal government can do that, she said, calling for
congressional action to provide long-term care protection.
   Gail Shearer of the consumers group said policies providing
long-term care are quite expensive and are not recommended for
people of moderate income. Prices can range as high as $100 a month
to $260 a month.
   And people under 60 shouldn't buy such policies unless there is
some guarantee that benefits will rise to keep pace with inflation,
Ms. Shearer added.
   Nonetheless, many policies are being offered and some people may
be tempted to buy them, she said.
   Problems to watch out for include:
   _Protection may not be available to people who need it most _
those with health problems already. Check policies for exclusions
that disallow coverage for pre-existing conditions.
   _Some policies were found to cover only certain types of care,
but not custodial care, potentially the longest and most costly
type.
   _More than half of all nursing home patients are admitted
without having been hospitalized first, but a majority of the
long-term care policies checked required prior hospitalization
before benefits could be provided.
   _Alzheimer's disease accounts for half of all nursing home
patients, yet a majority of the policies did not specifically state
that it was covered.
   A company flooded with claims could decide to use the vague
language of its policies to exclude Alzheimer's coverage, Consumers
Union warned.
   In addition, the group noted that some policies require a
confirmed diagnosis to provide coverage, and Alzheimer's cannot
always be confirmed except by autopsy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
