<HEAD>Cloud of Gas Engulfs Railroad Work Crew</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf to CORRECT name of company to ICI, sted ICA</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOUNT VERNON, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cloud of chlorine gas engulfed a
rural south railroad work crew of 55 men, sending 13 to hospitals
for treatment, officials said today.
   Hospital officials said only two of the Norfolk Southern
Railroad workers needed to be admitted overnight after the Monday
afternoon accident, and they were released this morning from South
Alabama Medical Center at Mobile.
   The others were treated for chemical inhalation and released.
   Janice Whatley, a member of the Mount Vernon rescue squad, said
the crew was working on Norfolk Southern tracks just south of
Alabama Power Co.'s Barry Electric Generating Plant.
   The cloud leaked from a gas line at a nearby chemical plant,
Rick Harris, a railroad spokesman in Atlanta said today.
   Harris said the accident closed the tracks for six hours. He
said the crew had symptoms that included swollen eyes, nausea and
breathing problems.
   The leak occurred in a chlorine line at an ICI Americas Inc.
plant that manufactures agricultural chemicals, plant manager Steve
Ledoux said today. He said the leak was capped immediately and the
cause was being investigated.
