<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Kenya-Editor     04-19 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Kenya-Editor,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Editor of Kenyan Law Magazine Charged in Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The editor of a magazine critical of the
government denied in court Tuesday that he violated publication
regulations.
   Gitobu Imanyara, a lawyer and editor in chief of The Nairobi Law
Monthly, was charged under the country's Books and Newspapers Act.
   His magazine has published articles criticizing political
detentions without trial, including those of lawyers who since have
been released. The publication has also challenged alleged
government interference in the courts and a new procedure approved
by the Kenya African National Union, the sole legal political
party, using head counts to tally votes in preliminary elections.
   The editor was accused of failing to deliver magazine copies to
a government registrar and of not making annual returns stating how
many magazines were published and at what prices they sold.
   Imanyara was freed on bail pending trial at a date still to be
set.
   The editor of a recently banned church magazine will appear in
court on similar charges April 26.
</TEXT>
