<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pope-Ukraine     04-19 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Ukraine,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Urges Religious Freedom for Ukrainian Catholics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Tuesday called for
religious freedom for Ukrainian Catholics in a letter marking the
1,000 anniversary of Christianity in what is now the Soviet Union.
   ``No one ought to consider membership in the Catholic Church as
incompatible with the good of the homeland and with the heritage of
Saint Vladmir,'' the pope said in a letter to Ukrainian Catholics
around the world.
   Prince Vladimir introduced Christianity in Kievan Rus', the
ancient name of the Soviet Ukraine, with a mass baptism on the
banks of the Dnieper River in 988.
   The Ukrainian church was suppressed in 1946 by Soviet dictator
Josef Stalin, who ordered it absorbed into the Russian Orthodox
church. Ukrainian priests who refused to accept the state-dominated
Orthodox church were shot or imprisoned, according to church
historians.
   Today, Eastern Rite Ukrainian Catholics make up the largest
underground church in the officially atheist Soviet Union.
Ukrainian clerics say there are up to 4 million Ukrainian Catholics
in the Soviet Union, including 10 secret bishops and more than 100
priests. Another 1.5 million Ukrainian Catholics live abroad.
   The pope, who has often expressed his desire to visit the Soviet
Union but has not been invited, said he would instead make a
``spiritual pilgrimage'' to the Ukraine for the millennium.
   The pope's letter was addressed to Cardinal Myroslav Ivan
Lubachivsky, the Rome-based leader of Ukrainian Catholics,
Ukrainian bishops and ``all the Ukrainian priests, religious and
faithful.''
   John Paul said the Ukrainian church ``has been tried by such
great adversity in recent decades.''
   ``May your great numbers of faithful enjoy true freedom of
conscience and respect for their religious right to give public
worship to God,'' the pontiff wrote.
   He said the main celebrations for the millennium would be held
in Rome. Vatican Radio has said the observance will include a Mass
celebrated by the pope and Ukrainian bishops in St. Peter's
Basilica on July 10.
   Last month, the Vatican announced the Russian Orthodox Church
had invited the pope to send a Vatican delegation to attend the
official millennium celebrations in the Soviet Union. It said the
pope would appoint the delegation for the trip to Moscow in June.
   The pope has said he would visit the Soviet Union only if he is
allowed to visit Catholics throughout the country, including the
Ukraine and Lithuania.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
