<1ST_LINE>u a PM-AutoTalks 2ndLd-Writethru a0529-a0508 04-19 0722</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Talks, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0529-a0508,0740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler Negotiators Want To Organize Plant Workers In Teams</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs, UPDATING with Chrysler demands today;
picks up 3rd graf pvs, ``Chrysler workers xxx; Version moved on
business wire</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. negotiators asked the United Auto
Workers today to support the automaker's efforts to organize plant
workers into teams and help avoid increased assembly costs.
   The team plan would allow Chrysler greater flexibility in using
different workers for different jobs, Vice President Anthony St.
John said after a second morning of meetings with the UAW on a new
contract.
   St. John said Chrysler, the nation's No. 3 automaker, wants
modifications to a pattern contract adopted last year at Ford Motor
Co. and General Motors Corp. to help avoid cost increases.
   Chrysler wants to set a minimum retirement age to keep more
workers active in their prime and increase the ratio of active
workers to retirees. St. John said Chrysler workers now retire as
early as age 48.
   Adopting a minimum retirement age, as well as encouraging
workers to join prepaid health care plans, would help keep
Chrysler's per-car production cost from going as much as $3.50
above GM's, St. John said.
   UAW spokesman Bob Barbee said the union had no immediate comment
on Chrysler's proposals.
   On Monday, St. John said Chrysler's senior executives will forgo
bonuses in years when the No. 3 automaker earns too little to share
profits with workers.
   The announcement came as the sides opened early talks on a
contract covering 66,000 workers in 15 states.
   Chrysler workers have no profit-sharing formula under the
current contract, which expires Sept. 14. But union and company
officials agree they will adopt an industry-pattern agreement
established last fall at GM and Ford Motor Co. that contains
profit-sharing.
   Union officials will study St. John's announcement before
commenting, UAW spokesman Peter Laarman said, calling it ``a free
gift, the kind you have to look at real close.''
   UAW leaders have blasted General Motors Corp., the nation's
largest automaker, for paying millions of dollars in cash bonuses
or stock awards to executives in the past two years while saying
its earnings were insufficient to distribute profits to workers.
   ``There is a public perception that it is unfair _ and we tend
to agree with that,'' St. John said.
   ``In any year where profit-sharing payments are not made to UAW
employees, the annual senior executive bonuses will also not be
paid. We intend to work through that issue in a commitment form
with the UAW,'' he said.
   St. John and UAW President Owen Bieber said they hope to reach a
contract settlement in two to three weeks. Union bargainers
presented their demands Monday.
   Company negotiators were scheduled to present proposals today
before the release of a company proxy statement likely to show that
Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca again exercised stock options granted
in the early 1980s, when Chrysler's stock was worth a fraction of
its present value.
   In 1986, Iacocca earned more than $20 million in salary,
benefits and exercised stock options.
   The pattern contract's profit-sharing formula resulted in a
record $636 million distributed among 156,000 Ford workers last
year. Ford profit-sharing checks averaged about $4,000 per worker.
   Bieber said pattern bargaining ``has always served our
membership very well. It has been a stabilizing force within the
companies and between them.''
   St. John also said Chrysler wants to set up a committee of union
and company officials and outside participants to track the new
contract's ability to protect jobs and increase efficiency and
quality at Chrysler plants.
   The committee's findings would be used in drawing up a new
contract in 1990, St. John said, apparently indicating Chrysler
will agree to the union's demand for a two-year contract.
   Bieber and UAW Vice President Marc Stepp said they want to put
Chrysler's contract expiration back in synch with the GM and Ford
pacts so that in 1990, all three will expire together for the first
time in a decade.
   The talks, which normally would begin in mid-July, cover wages,
benefits and working conditions.
   Chrysler's UAW contract covers 51,600 hourly, 5,600 salaried and
6,000 laid-off workers at factories, parts depots and offices in
Michigan, Ohio, Illinois, Massachusetts, Colorado, Alabama,
Indiana, California, Tennessee, Minnesota, Delaware, New York,
Oregon, Florida and Missouri.
</TEXT>
