<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Congress-Primary 1st-LdWritethru a0613 04-19 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Congress-Primary, 1st-Ld Writethru, a0613,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Leads in Senate ``Super Delegate'' Balloting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with vote</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis led the
balloting in the first round of the Capitol Hill ``primary'' today,
when Senate Democrats named 43 members as ``super delegates'' to
this summer's convention.
   The presidential candidates focused their attention on the New
York primary, where 255 delegates were at stake, but nearly as many
convention seats were to be decided by Senate and House Democrats
in sessions today and Wednesday.
   Dukakis won the backing of 13 of those selected, while most of
the professional politicians _ 21 _ remained uncommitted.
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr., whose campaign was dependent on a good
showing in today's New York primary, was second to Dukakis, gaining
the support of six of his Senate colleagues. He was named as a
delegate as well.
   Sen. Paul Simon, whose campaign is on hold, managed to win only
a seat for himself and the backing of fellow Illinois Sen. Alan
Dixon.
   Jesse Jackson, Dukakis' closest challenger, was shut out.
   The Senate's choices kept Dukakis' overall delegate lead intact.
   According to the AP count, Dukakis had 881 delegates to 745 for
Jackson. Gore had 419 and Simon 183. Uncommitted delegates totaled
622.
   Today's choices came in a quick public vote by the Senate
Democratic Conference, following weeks of secret jockeying for the
spots at the convention in Atlanta in July.
   Senate Democratic Leader Robert C. Byrd said that the selection
process was relatively painless.
   ``We were pleased that we were able to accommodate almost every
Democratic member who requested to be an unpledged delegate,'' the
West Virginia Democrat said.
   He did not name the two who lost out because of seniority.
   The House Democratic Caucus makes its official choices for 210
``super delegate'' slots on Wednesday, and Dukakis is ahead among
those already nominated for those positions as well.
   The results from the Senate caucus were not a surprise, although
32 of the 43 were nominated last week in secret. The other 11 were
nominated and put on the list over the weekend.
   The Associated Press obtained a list of those nominees.
   Among the first 32, Dukakis had nine, Gore five, Simon two and
16 were uncommitted.
   The 11 additional delegates named today added four delegate
votes for Dukakis, two for Gore and six to uncommitted.
   A total of 646 of the 4,162 votes to be cast at the Atlanta
convention will come from super delegates.
   In addition to the 253 congressional slots, 362 votes will be
cast by members of the Democratic National Committee and 26 by
Democratic governors. Five former party leaders also have automatic
seats at the convention.
   The 11 senators added to the delegate list today were: Quentin
Burdick of North Dakota, J. Bennett Johnston of Louisiana, Bill
Bradley of New Jersey, Christopher Dodd of Connecticut, Jeff
Bingaman of New Mexico, Jay Rockefeller of West Virginia, Brock
Adams of Washington, Tim Wirth of Colorado, Wyche Fowler of
Georgia, Tom Daschle of South Dakota and Harry Reid of Nevada.
</TEXT>
