<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Eastern-Lorenzo     04-19 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern-Lorenzo,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern Airlines, Texas Air Corp. Lash Out at Unions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The executives of Eastern Airlines and its
parent Texas Air Corp., lashed out at the unions today for a
``slanderous safety campaign'' and ``misinformation'' that they say
has led to the government investigation into the airline company.
   ``Eastern today is the most watched airline in the business,''
Texas Air chairman Frank Lorenzo told a news conference, adding
that he welcomed the government probes into Eastern and Continental
Airlines, also part of his airline empire.
   ``The ramp inspections (ordered by the Federal Aviation
Administration) will demonstrate once and for all that Continental
and Eastern are as safe as any major airline,'' said Lorenzo.
   ``What is at issue is how far a union is permitted to go by
weakening a company through harassament .. (and) misinformation ...
in part (in an attempt) to take over the company,'' said Lorenzo,
who vowed to keep Eastern.
   ``The company is not for sale,'' Lorenzo said, adding that while
he is aware of interests by some union leaders to launch a hostile
takeover he has no concerete evidence of such a move.
   Officials from the unions representing Eastern's mechanics and
pilots could not be reached immediately for comment on the charges.
They have said in the past that they are only trying to highlight
efforts by Lorenzo to weaken Eastern.
   The airline and the mechanics' union are negotiating a contract
in which the union has been resisting demands by management that it
take significant wage concessions.
   Philip Bakes, president of Eastern, said that he is confident
the federal investigation of Eastern will conclude the airline is
being operated safely. He said federal inspectors have examined all
of Eastern's jets at least once since the probe was announced last
week and some planes have been examined five or six times as they
operate in and out of different airports.
   Bakes accused the unions of a ``slanderous safety campaign''
which he said has been a ``major factor'' in recent financial
losses by the airline.
   While some Eastern jets have been taken out of service after the
inspections, he characterized such actions as routine and ``proof
that the system is working.''
   ``Everyday planes are being taken out of service'' briefly as
part of the airline's normal operations when they have mechanical
or other problems.
   Texas Air, the country's largest airline company, has been
reeling from a series of inspections announced last week by the FAA
and the Transportation Department into safety at the two airlines
and the parent holding company's management and finances.
   The news conference also was attended by two members of
Eastern's board of directors and by Frank Borman, who was Eastern's
chairman before the airline was sold to Texas Air in 1986 and now
remains on Texas Air's board of directors.
   All of the executives blamed the labor turmoil at Eastern for
creating ``an atmosphere'' which prompted the unusual scrutiny of
both the FAA and its parent Transportation Department.
   Bakes said Eastern is ``clearly being hurt by operating in an
atmosphere of many myths'' but that the various federal
investigations of Eastern and Texas Air so far have had only a
small impact on flight bookings at the airline.
   ``Obviously this isn't helping our business,'' he said.
   Eastern, meanwhile, said it was launching an advertising
campaign aimed at countering the attack on its image. The aim of
the ads as well as Tuesday's news conference is ``to clear the
air'' and ``set the record straight,'' said Clark Onstad, a Texas
Air vice president.
</TEXT>
