<HEAD>Bomb Explodes Near Parliament</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb blew up today at an office
building near Parliament, shattering the entrance and spraying
glass fragments into the street.
   The blast reportedly caused no injuries, but ambulances and fire
engines were called in and the area was cordoned off. Residents of
a nearby apartment complex were evacuated as a precaution.
   The explosion occurred at 6:18 p.m. at the Santam building,
about 100 yards from Parliament. Parliament was in session at the
time of the blast.
   Police had no immediate comment on the type of explosive
involved or who might have been responsible.
   There have been several bombings in South Africa in the past
week, including one that damaged Johannesburg's city hall and
another that killed a man and injured a woman outside a cinema
complex in Pretoria.
   Authorities have blamed the blasts on guerrillas of the outlawed
African National Congress, the main guerrilla group fighting to
overthrow the government and end apartheid.
   Police Commissioner Hennie De Witt said today that the man
killed by the blast Friday in Pretoria had been identified as a
``trained African National Congress terrorist.'' De Witt said the
man, whose name was not made public, was carrying a Soviet-made
limpet mine when it exploded accidentally.
</TEXT>
