<1ST_LINE>u a AM-AbandonedChild Bjt   04-19 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abandoned Child, Bjt,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Abandoned Child Leaves Hospital for New Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nine-year-old Darlwin Carlisle, whose frostbitten
legs were amputated after she was abandoned in an unheated
apartment this winter, walked out of a hospital Tuesday on
artificial legs, smiling and waving.
   ``She's very motivated, very courageous,'' said Roberta O'Shea,
the girl's physical therapist at La Rabida Children's Hospital.
``She runs and she jumps and she can skip. She can do just about
everything.
   ``The only thing she can't do is double-Dutch jump rope because
I don't know how,'' and so she couldn't teach her.
   Darlwin's ordeal touched hearts nationwide after she was found
locked in a Gary, Ind., apartment Jan. 17 by a construction worker
who said he heard a child's voice plead, ``Please don't board me
up.''
   Hundreds of presents, thousands of letters and donations
totaling $125,000 poured in to cheer her up and pay her hospital
bills after her legs were amputated just below the knee.
   Before Darlwin left the hospital Tuesday, her relatives packed
up four boxes with toys and other presents she received.
   Under a sunny blue sky, Darlwin walked down the front steps of
La Rabida, holding two dolls and wearing a pink and white lace
dress with pink bows in her hair.
   She limped very slightly as she walked to a waiting car,
accompanied by her great-grandmother, Katie Carlisle, her aunt,
Sallie Carlisle, and a cousin, Crystal Carlisle. Darlwin will live
with her great-grandmother in Gary, Ind.
   One of Darlwin's nurses kissed her while Ms. O'Shea made sure
her seat belt was fastened.
   ``She's in very good spirits,'' Ms. O'Shea told reporters.
``She's very excited to be going home. She won't need physical
therapy anymore. As you can see, she walked out fine.''
   While at La Rabida, Darlwin learned to ride a bicycle _ falling
only once _ and how to roller skate without using canes, Ms. O'Shea
said.
   ``She's been doing wonderfully,'' said Paula Jaudes, Darlwin's
physician at La Rabida. ``You can't consider her handicapped.''
   Darlwin lived with her mother, Darlwin Britt, in Gary, before
being found by construction worker Jeff Griffin who had been sent
to board up an unheated brick home after a mortgage foreclosure.
   Griffin said at the time that he heard a child pleading for
help, removed a six-foot refrigerator from the top of the stairway
and kicked open a padlocked door to rescue the girl.
   Doctors said later the severity of her injuries indicated she
had been in the extreme cold for at least five days.
   Doctors at the University of Chicago's Wyler Children's Hospital
determined they could not save Darlwin's lower legs from gangrene,
and amputated them Jan. 23.
   Her 25-year-old mother has pleaded innocent to three counts of
felony child neglect and remains in the Lake County Jail in Crown
Point, Ind., in lieu of $50,000 bail, said Diane McDowell, a
spokeswoman for the county prosecutor's office. Her trial is
scheduled June 20. She faces up to 60 years in prison, if convicted
on all three counts, Ms. McDowell said.
   The girl was transferred to La Rabida, also a University of
Chicago hospital, on Jan. 29 to be fitted with artificial limbs.
   Her bill at Wyler reached $27,020 and at La Rabida it was
averaging about $500 a day, La Rabida's development director,
Phyllis Monjar, said, which would have brought it to about $39,500
through Monday. Donated money not used for medical bills will be
used to provide for Darlwin's future education and care.
   In Gary, Darlwin will return soon to a regular elementary
school, probably as a fourth-grader, Ms. Monjar said.
</TEXT>
