<HEAD>Chlorine Leak Sends 13 Railroad Workers to Hospitals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNT VERNON, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A chlorine gas leak at a chemical
plant formed a toxic cloud that engulfed a railroad work crew of 55
people, sending 13 to hospitals, officials said Tuesday.
   Two of the Norfolk Southern Railroad workers were hospitalized
overnight and released Tuesday from South Alabama Medical Center at
Mobile, officials said. The others were treated Monday for chemical
inhalation.
   Janice Whatley, a member of the Mount Vernon rescue squad, said
the crew was working on Norfolk Southern tracks.
   The gas leaked from a line at ICI Americas Inc., said Rick
Harris, a railroad spokesman in Atlanta. The cause was not known.
The company makes agricultural chemicals.
   The tracks were closed for six hours.
