<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Patrol-Thefts     04-19 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Patrol-Thefts,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Diary Details Theft By Student Patrol Members</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twelve University of Illinois students
have been dropped from the student campus patrol and two of them
face criminal charges of stealing from the offices they were
assigned to protect.
   Not all 12 were involved in crimes, but some knew and did not
inform supervisors, said university Police Chief Paul Dollins.
   Dollins said he won't abolish the 4-year-old program, in which
about 60 students are paid $3.50 an hour to patrol the campus.
   ``When we first started, the students were motivated out of a
desire to provide public safety on campus,'' said Dollins. ``We
need to get students with qualities of courage and integrity on
board.''
   One of the 12 student patrol members, John Boch, gave police his
diary detailing some of the incidents.
   ``I discover that Turner Plant Sciences building is easy-open
city with my trusty ... pocketknife,'' Boch wrote in the diary.
``God, this job is just practice breaking and entering.''
   Boch and the other 11 face possible university disciplinary
action.
   Boch said ``it was sort of a game'' to get into offices, where
he allegedly took small items such as stationery and pens.
   However, Boch said that when he discovered another patrol member
was stealing more valuable items, he told the student patrol
coordinator and handed over his diary.
   Champaign County State's Attorney Tom Difanis later charged two
patrol members, one with burglary, felony theft and misdemeanor
theft and the other with misdemeanor theft.
   Boch will not face criminal charges, said Difanis.
   ``It's silly little things,'' Boch's diary said. ``You can call
it burglary and theft if you want, but we didn't see it as crime
per se.''
   He added: ``I see in hindsight I shouldn't have kept a diary.''
</TEXT>
