<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ShuttleTest     04-19 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle Test,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thiokol, NASA Enter Final Test Phase Before Shuttle Flights Resume</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIGHAM CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The third full-scale firing of a
redesigned solid fuel booster rocket for the space shuttle was
scheduled for Wednesday with deliberate flaws built in to test
safety features.
   The two-minute firing of the 126-foot-long, 1.2 million-pound
booster was scheduled for 3 p.m. EDT at Morton Thiokol's Wasatch
Operations plant 25 miles west of Brigham City.
   ``This is a really important milestone in the resumption of
flight,'' said company spokesman Rocky Raab. ``In a sense, it's the
culmination of the redesign effort of two years. If all three of
the (final) tests proceed satisfactorily, the launch preparations
proceed.''
   The horizontal test is designed to reveal any weaknesses in
booster, which was redesigned after the Jan. 28, 1986, explosion of
the shuttle Challenger.
   The disaster, which killed Challenger's seven-member crew, was
blamed on a flawed booster rocket seal that allowed blazing exhaust
to escape through a joint in the side and ignite the shuttle's
external liquid fuel tank.
   Wednesday's test is the first in the last series of firings
planned by Morton Thiokol and NASA before the shuttle's first
post-Challenger launch, scheduled for mid-August. Other full-scale
tests are scheduled for June and July.
   The rocket for Wednesday's test was assembled with deliberate
flaws in sealing material in the joints between segments of the
booster. Flawed seals have been tested previously in short-duration
tests, but never in a full-scale firing, Raab said.
   In one joint, a defect was cut into the surface of a J-shaped
seal where sections of insulation meet inside the rocket casing.
The defect could let hot gas penetrate the insulation and hit the
innermost of three O-rings. In the short-duration tests, the defect
sealed itself during firing and gas did not reach the O-ring.
   In another joint a small ``blowhole'' was created in the
adhesive that binds the insulation to the rocket casing. In
short-duration tests, hot gases have followed the blowhole to a new
O-ring, but have not gone beyond it.
   The test comes at a critical time for Morton Thiokol. The
company is NASA's sole supplier of booster rockets, and views a
successful launch as a sign the stigma of the Challenger tragedy
can be set aside.
   While praising Morton Thiokol's work in the redesign effort,
NASA also has asked Congress for a $1.2 million government plant to
build its own boosters.
   Though not related to the shuttle program, the company's image
also was tarnished by the deaths of five employees in a Dec. 29
fire that destroyed a first-stage MX missile rocket motor.
   State safety inspectors cited Morton Thiokol for alleged safety
violations, which are being contested by the company.
   But both Air Force and Morton Thiokol investigators concluded
the workers violated company safety rules by being in the building
during a critical stage of the fueling process that normally is
carried out by remote control.
   Raab said confidence at the company remains high.
   ``The morale here is extremely good as far as the redesign and
success we've had to date,'' Raab said. ``What most people don't
realize is this redesign effort is about three times as intricate
as the original design process, and is being completed in half the
time.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
