<HEAD>Explosion Injures 6 At American Center in San Jose</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion at the American-Costa
Rican Cultural Center injured six people on Tuesday, police and
U.S. Embassy spokesmen said.
   At least two of the injured were seriously hurt, officials said.
   First police reports said it appeared that a ``bomb or grenade''
had been thrown against the center, but there were later reports
the blast occurred in an electric transformer.
   The force of the explosion broke windows in nearby cars.
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Mark Krischick said, ``Preliminary
information available to us, is that it was not a bomb but a
malfunction of electrical equipment on a power line.''
   He said he based that conclusion on statements from police,
embassy workers and witnesses and on the types of injuries
sustained.
   The cultural center is sponsored by the U.S. Embassy.
