<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 1425EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Reagan-FECAudit     04-19 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-FEC Audit,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan's 1984 Campaign Fined</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Election Commission fined
President Reagan's campaign committee $10,000 for accepting
excessive contributions in the 1984 primary election, newly
released records show.
   The commission is winding up its work on the 1984 election, and
documents released Monday include a Jan. 26 settlement signed by
the Reagan committee.
   An audit by the FEC found that Reagan accepted more than the
$1,000 maximum from 285 individuals, for a total of $193,674 in
excess receipts.
   Of that, the campaign transferred $172,624 into a fund used to
comply with various FEC regulations in the general election. But
such a transfer is legal only if the donors give written
permission, which was not obtained in the case of Reagan's
campaign, the commission report said.
   Most of the rest of the money was refunded to the donors,
``although not within a reasonable time,'' according to the
settlement agreement signed by the FEC and the Reagan committee
treasurer, Angela Buchanan Jackson.
   Five thousand dollars was later listed in the names of spouses
of original donors, but that procedure, too, requires written
authorization from the contributors and spouses, and the
authorization was not given.
   Spending and contribution limits apply to all candidates who
receive federal matching funds for their presidential campaigns.
   The two party nominees for the general election receive all
their campaign funds from the federal pot and do not have to raise
any money on their own. In the primary elections, however, they
must raise money privately that can be matched from the federal
fund.
   The fund is supported by the voluntary $1 checkoff on income tax
returns.
   This year, the FEC will give the Democratic and Republican
nominees $27 million each for the general election campaign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
