<1ST_LINE>u a PM-KennedyFiles 3rdLd-Writethru a0652 04-19 0901</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kennedy Files, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0652,0925</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Offer Evidence In RFK Assassination</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Leads with 6 grafs to update with formal release of material,
picking up 6th graf pvs, ``Among the xxx</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A polka dot dress, bullets taken from
victims and a hand-scrawled notation that ``RFK must die'' were
among pieces of evidence put on display today as officials opened
secret records on the assassination of Robert F. Kennedy.
   The exhibits mounted on boards and in glass cases were samples
of the voluminous files examined by state archivists and were put
on display to illustrate key points in the investigation as
authorities released the material.
   The police files on Kennedy's shooting could shed new light on
persistent questions about whether Sirhan Bishara Sirhan was the
only gunman in the shooting.
   Was Kennedy shot from in front or behind? Were there eight shots
or more in the pantry of the Ambassador Hotel? And how close was
the gunman whose bullet found its fatal path into Kennedy's brain?
   Those questions and others raised by conspiracy theorists and
scholars may be addressed in some 50,000 pages of documents,
interviews with 4,000 witnesses, and 2,500 photographs being
released today by California Secretary of State March Fong Eu.
   ``It has been almost 20 years since that awful night at the
Ambassador (Hotel), a night which ended one life and changed so
many others,'' Eu said as she formally ordered the materials made
public.
   Among the disputed facts verified by the documents was an
admission by police that they destroyed key evidence in the case,
including ceiling tiles, a door jamb and thousands of photographs
taken in the Ambassador Hotel kitchen where Kennedy was shot on
June 5, 1968.
   An official record in the evidence showed that 2,410 photographs
were burned on Aug. 21, 1968. It gives no reason for their burning.
   The polka dot dress was one of many purchased by police in an
effort to jog the memories of witnesses on a point of contention _
whether a girl in a polka dot dress was seen running from the
Ambassador Hotel shouting, ``We shot him.'' That report was never
verified.
   One entire case of evidence contained items from Sirhan's
Pasadena home. Among the items was the now-famous diary in which
Sirhan scrawled in pencil his plans to kill the New York senator.
   ``My determination to eliminate RFK is becoming more the more of
an unshakeable obsession,'' he wrote. Under a series of doodles was
the statement, ``RFK must die.''
   Also included was sign-in sheet from a San Gabriel Valley gun
club which showed that Sirhan visited there on June 4, 1968.
   The key question is whether Sirhan, a Jordanian immigrant
serving a life sentence for the crime, was the lone assassin of the
Democratic presidential hopeful.
   On the eve of the release of the files, Sirhan's attorney, Luke
McKissack, said Sirhan expects nothing to contradict his
frequently-stated claim that he was a lone gunman.
   McKissack said that although Sirhan maintains he doesn't
remember shooting Kennedy, Sirhan believes he was motivated by
anger over the Arab loss in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war.
   McKissack said that Sirhan, who is serving his sentence at
Soledad Prison, has given up hope that he will ever be paroled.
   Eu and California Archivist John Burns say they hope the release
of the Los Angeles Police Department investigative file will
satisfy the public's right to know everything about the event.
   ``There should no longer be any speculation about what the
police found,'' Burns said.
   The release follows years of demands for public access to the
information.
   ``This is a kind of vindication of citizens' efforts to force
this material out,'' said Gregory Stone, a political scientist on
leave from the University of Wisconsin who has devoted himself to
studying Kennedy's killing.
   Stone equated its importance with the 1964 publication of the
Warren Commission's investigation of the assassination of President
John F. Kennedy, Robert Kennedy's brother.
   The only things withheld from disclosure, Eu said, were autopsy
photos, criminal ``rap sheets'' and fingerprint cards, juvenile
case records, internal police personnel records and records that
originated with the FBI or police departments outside Los Angeles'.
   Burns said the FBI would release its own file at an unspecified
time.
   Eu's spokeswoman, Melissa Warren, said her office had been
inundated with calls since announcing the impending release,
including many from Massachusetts, Kennedy's home state, and New
York, which he represented as a U.S. senator.
   A summary of Los Angeles Police Department files released in
1986 contained a police conclusion tht Sirhan was the lone
assassin. It found no evidence of a second gunman or a conspiracy.
   Sirhan admitted the killing at his 1969 trial but has claimed he
has no memory of the actual shooting. He blames his memory loss on
alcohol.
   Names and details considered sensitive at the time were deleted
from the 1986 summary. It did not fully address questions raised
about forensic evidence involving the gun, autopsy reports and
witness recollections.
   Witnesses told of seeing Sirhan step from behind a steam table
into Kennedy's path as the senator walked toward him. But Los
Angeles County Coroner Thomas Noguchi testified at Sirhan's trial
that Kennedy was killed by a shot fired behind his right ear.
   Conspiracy theorists suggested that a second gunman fired at
Kennedy from behind while Sirhan stood in front of him.
</TEXT>
