<DOCNO> AP880419-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 1530EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FarmTrade     04-19 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farm Trade,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lyng No Direct Link Between Reagan Veto, Canadian Trade Accord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan might veto a massive trade
bill now before Congress, but that action wouldn't directly affect
the free-trade agreement between the United States and Canada,
Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng said Tuesday.
   ``There's nothing that tells me that they're connected,'' Lyng
said. If there is a veto of the sweeping trade bill, Reagan's veto
message would ``describe some reasons that have nothing whatsoever
to do with the free trade agreement with Canada, as far as I can
see.''
   Lawmakers are near final action on the 1,000-page trade bill,
but there have been veto threats over parts the administration find
objectionable, including a provision that would require 60-day
notice of plant closings and large-scale layoffs.
   The U.S.-Canada trade pact was signed Jan. 2 but still requires
approval by the Canadian parliament and the U.S. Congress. If
approved, the treaty will take effect Jan. 1, 1989, and will
gradually eliminate all tariffs between the two countries and
address non-tariff barriers.
   According to the Agriculture Department, U.S-Canada trade was
about $124 billion in 1986, of which $4.6 billion was agricultural.
   Lyng appeared at a news conference with Canadian minister of
agriculture, John Wise, following private discussions. Wise said he
was pleased by Lyng's view of the trade bill and said there is
``the absolute need and the absolute necessity for us to join
forces'' in ongoing global talks under the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade, or GATT.
   ``In fact, I think, were it not for the leadership taken by
Canada and the United States ... we probably wouldn't be at the
stage that we are now in the Uruguay Round of multinational trade
negotiations,'' Wise said.
   Both he and Lyng said the U.S.-Canada free-trade agreement would
help push the cause of global reform.
   ``It would be extremely helpful, I think, to both of us, in
sending a very legitimate and a very concrete message to our other
trading partners, particularly at GATT,'' Wise said.
   In a joint statement later, the two agricultural leaders pledged
to work together ``to ensure that the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development ministerial meeting in May and the
Toronto economic summit in June provide the necessary political
impetus'' for a midterm review of the Uruguay Round next December
in Montreal.
</TEXT>
