<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Zimbabwe-Amnesty     04-19 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Zimbabwe-Amnesty ,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amnesty Declared for Zimbabwe Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Robert Mugabe on Tuesday
announced a general amnesty for armed rebels and political
opponents, saying it was made possible by his recent accord with
longtime rival Joshua Nkomo.
   Mugabe, speaking at a ceremony marking his country's Defense
Forces Day, credited the amnesty to the unity pact signed Dec. 22
with Nkomo, a former opposition leader.
   The unity agreement aims to merge Mugabe's governing Zimbabwe
African National Union with Nkomo's Zimbabwe African People's Union
by year's end.
   Mugabe and Nkomo led allied rebel armies fighting white rule
when Zimbabwe was a British colony known as Rhodesia. When
independence was declared in 1980 and Mugabe became president, some
Nkomo supporters took to the countryside to fight the new black
government.
   On Monday, the eighth anniversary of independence, Mugabe asked
those rebels in western Zimbabwe to surrender. He said about 100
rebels remained at large in Matabeleland, Nkomo's traditional
tribal stronghold.
   Mugabe did not say how many people will be affected by the
amnesty, the first he has offered to opponents. He said it would
also cover political exiles and certain people convicted of minor
crimes.
</TEXT>
