<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Gulf-Helicopter 4thLd-Writethru a0637 04-19 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Helicopter, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0637,450</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs graf 7, Pentagon spokesman, to include ages.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci refused to
specutlate today on the fate of a Marine helicopter and its two-man
crew missing since American encounters Monday with Iranian forces
in the Persian Gulf.
   Nor would he comment on Iran's claims that its forces had
brought the craft down.
   Carlucci, asked as he left a memorial service for police
officers and others killed enforcing drug laws whether the copter
was considered lost, answered:
   ``I'm not going to speculate. We're continuing to look, and I'm
certainly hopeful.''
   Asked about Iranian claims that its forces had shot the
helicopter down, Carlucci replied, ``I'm not going to get into the
details.''
   The Marine Corps, meanwhile, changed the status of the
helicopter's two crewmen to missing.
   Pentagon Spokesman Dan Howard identified them as Capt. Stephen
C. Leslie, 30, and Capt. Kenneth W. Hill, 33, assigned to Squadron
HMLA-167 based at the New River, N.C., Marine Corps Air Station.
   Leslie claims a home of record of New Bern and Hill a home of
record of Thomasville, N.C., the Pentagon said.
   Howard repeated statements of Monday that the Cobra had been
sent out on a ``standard patrol sweep'' and that there was no
evidence to suggest the copter had ever come under fire.
   As he commented, U.S. Navy ships and planes continued to search
for the Marine Cobra attack helicopter over the central gulf.
   The helicopter did not return to the USS Wainwright Monday after
what Pentagon officials called a ``routine reconnaissance mission.''
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency reported Monday
night that Iranian warships, ``in a heroic clash with the aggressor
American helicopters in the Persian Gulf shot down one of them
Monday afternoon.''
   Addressing the search, a Pentagon spokesman, Maj. Charles Boyd,
said today:
   ``There is a very extensive search underway. Numerous ships and
helicopters are involved. The airborne search stopped during the
night and resumed at daylight, but numerous surface ships kept
searching during the night.''
   The helicopter was in the lower central portion of the gulf,
near the area of Monday's heaviest fighting, when it disappeared,
according to the Pentagon, which was not releasing the names of the
two crewmen.
   Another Pentagon spokesman, Lt. Col., Arnold Williams, said the
helicopter was assigned to the USS Trenton as part of the Marine
task force protecting Kuwaiti oil tankers in the Persian Gulf. The
helicopter was operating temporarily from the Wainwright, a
cruiser, he said.
   Williams said he did not know what radio contact there had been
with the helicopter.
   No American casualties were reported in the initial attacks on
Iranian positions and the later return fire from Iranian speed
boats and land-based missiles.
</TEXT>
