<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-Reax     04-19 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Reax,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>European Leaders Denounce Mine-Laying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   European leaders Tuesday denounced mine-laying in
the Persian Gulf, while Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of Britain
went further and delivered a strong defense of U.S. retaliatory
action against Iran.
   ``I'm in favor of action against those who lay mines against
shipping in the gulf ... and not letting people get away with
constantly causing extra trouble on what should be a free
international seaway,'' Mrs. Thatcher told Parliament, adding:
   ``I fully support the action which the United States took.''
   A French government spokesman said Paris ``is concerned by the
sudden renewal of tension in the gulf.''
   Speaking on condition of anonymity, he said: ``We reaffirm our
commitment to freedom of navigation in the gulf and demand that the
mining stop'' along with ``all other acts hostile to navigation in
international waters.''
   In reply to a question, he said attacks on merchant shipping
``can only lead to measures of self-defense.''
   Italian Foreign Minister Giulio Andreotti said: ``Laying mines
is an illegal act, which puts navigation at risk.'' He said the
U.S. attack on an Iranian oil platform and an Iranian
counterattack, ``correspond with the hard logic of military action
and reaction.''
   An Iranian diplomat said the accusation that his country planted
the mines was ``such an absurd thing that one does not have to deny
it.'' He implied Iraq was the culprit, because disruption of gulf
shipping served Iraqi interests.
   ``It was Iraq that attacked the shipping in the Persian Gulf
(and) invited foreign forces to the area ... in order to divert the
attention from the main problem on the battleground,'' said
Akhunzadeh Basti, the Iranian charge d'affaires in London, in a
British Broadcasting Corp. radio interview.
   Asked whether Iran would attack U.S. targets again, he replied:
``By these actions, they (America) openly committed themselves, or
they made an alliance with the Iraqis. So we see now the Americans
are directly supporting Iraq in a defeated war and if that is their
position, of course there will be countermeasures.''
   Basti was summoned to by British Foreign Office official Alan
Munro who protested about the mining and Iran's attack on the York
Marine a British-owned tanker on lease to a U.S. company.
   In West Germany, the left-leaning Frankfurter Rundschau
newspaper said that militarily, Washington ``can be satisfied with
the results of the attacks against two Iranian oil platforms in the
gulf.''
   However, it said, ``in another way the attack did not work as
planned in Washington'' because Iran responded to the action by
attacking the York Marine.
   ``This means a dangerous escalation of the already tense
situation between the United States and Iran in the gulf, and
confirms the fears of Congress that the United States could be
drawn into a broad military conflict in the gulf,'' the paper said.
</TEXT>
