<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Incest     04-19 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Incest,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Says Incest to Blame for High Infant Mortality in
Turkmenia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet newspaper on Tuesday blamed high infant
mortality in the Central Asian republic of Turkmenia on widespread
incest among rural residents who intermarry to avoid paying huge
dowries demanded by tradition.
   The youth newspaper Komsomolskaya Pravda quoted a doctor in the
village of Yagtylyk as saying that at one nearby collective farm,
there are 90 families in which the parents are close relatives, and
71 of them had borne children who died within a year.
   The newspaper did not make clear how much of the republic's high
incidence of infant mortality was attributable to incest, but said
it was ``a high percentage.''
   A Soviet sociology journal last year reported that the infant
mortality rate in Turkmenia is more than twice the Soviet national
average, which itself ranks 50th in the world, behind most
developed countries.
   The journal, Sociological Research, said 58.2 of every 1,000
children born in the Central Asian republic die within a year. The
national infant mortality rate in the Soviet Union in 1986 was 25.4
per 1,000. Infant mortality in the United States that year was 10.4
per 1,000 births.
   ``They knock us doctors for the high infant mortality rate,''
Khodzhamurad Makhemov, a pediatric specialist in Turkmenia's
Takhtinsky region told the newspaper. ``Yet we are powerless in the
case of the death of a child of related parents.''
   The report referred to the case of a 30-year-old woman in the
region who married her first cousin and gave birth to eight
children. Five of them died before reaching age one.
   Komsomolskaya Pravda said 164 cases of infant mortality
attributable to incest had been found in the one village, Yagtylyk,
the population of which was not given and is too small to be
included in the annual national economic report. The article
speculated, however, that a similar situation existed throughout
the rural regions of the republic of about 3.3 million people.
   Intermarriage in the republic has not fallen off in recent
years, the newspaper said, blaming the practice on ``those who
support dowry ransoms, the buying and selling of Turkmenian girls.''
   Rural families that cannot afford to pay thousands of rubles to
an outside family encourage their children to marry within, the
newspaper said.
   The article quoted local marriage office workers as saying they
are powerless to prevent intermarriage, and called for changes in
the republic's legal code to deter close relatives from marrying.
   It noted, however, that traditions in rural regions are not so
easily broken, and that many of the related couples who arrive at
public offices to register their weddings do so only after they
``in fact have already become husband and wife.''
   Turkmenia, like most of Central Asia, is populated mostly by
Moslems, who marry in religious ceremonies and register with Soviet
authorities as a formality.
   The article, titled ``Marrying ... a Brother,'' also called on
teachers and health care workers to inform rural residents of the
genetic dangers involved in bearing children with a close relative.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
