<1ST_LINE>u i AM-PLOSlaying     04-19 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO Slaying,0627</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Body of Slain Palestinian Guerrilla Leader Arrives In Syria</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The body of Khalil al-Wazir, the PLO
military commander assassinated in Tunis last week, was met in
Syria on Tuesday by grieving relatives and competing factions of
the PLO.
   The PLO-chartered plane carrying the body of al-Wazir, his wife,
five children and PLO officials touched down at Damascus airport at
2:45 p.m.
   Palestine Liberation Organization Chairman Yasser Arafat was not
aboard the plane. Arafat saw the body off at Tunis airport in
Tunisia but stayed behind, apparently because of his feud with
President Hafez Assad of Syria.
   Al-Wazir, 52, also known as Abu Jihad, was killed Saturday by
armed commandos who burst into his home in suburban Tunis. The
funeral was set for Wednesday.
   Israeli sources have said Israeli security forces carried out
the attack but the Israeli government has refused to confirm this.
   The PLO and Tunisia have blamed Israel for the assassination.
Tunisia on Tuesday requested a special session of the United
Nations Security Council to condemn the slaying.
   Al-Wazir's mother, Fawzieh, hugged and kissed his wife, Intisar,
as she stepped from the plane. Al-Wazir's sick father could not
make it to the airport.
   Among those aboard the plane were five members of the PLO
Central Committee, all members of Fatah, the backbone of the PLO.
   Also aboard were members of the Marxist Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine and the Moscow-oriented Democratic Front
for the Liberation of Palestine.
   The popular front and the democratic front are the main factions
making up the PLO after Fatah.
   Arafat and al-Wazir were expelled from Damascus in June 1983
after a Syrian-backed mutiny in PLO ranks.
   Al-Wazir was born in Ramle, which is now in Israel, and had
asked to be buried close to Palestine. His mother and father live
in Damascus.
   Palestinian delegations at the airport rushed to embrace the PLO
officials as they stepped from the plane. George Habash, who leads
the popular front, took Mrs. al-Wazir in his arms.
   Mrs. al-Wazir, wearing a black dress and a Palestinian flag
scarf, emerged from the plane carrying a poster of her husband in
one hand and flashing ``V'' for victory in the other.
   ``In soul, in blood we shall continue the march to Palestine,''
vowed Mrs. al-Wazir, flanked by her children, all wearing olive
green military fatigues.
   About 30 Palestinian girl and boy scouts, some clad in PLO flags
and others in traditional Palestinian costumes, repeated Mrs.
Wazir's words, adding: ``There is no God but God. God loved Abu
Jihad.''
   The boy scouts, standing near the plane and carrying four
wreaths including one from Arafat, sang Palestinian revolutionary
songs. Al-Wazir's 21-year-old son, Bassil, vowed to avenge the loss
of his father.
   ``My father's martyrdom means a new beginning, a new start,
readiness and will to fight for the freedom of Palestine,'' Bassil
told reporters in English.
   Representatives of Assad's government and the Jordanian
government of King Hussein also were at the airport.
   Dozens of Palestinian men carried al-Wazir's coffin, draped in a
red, white, green and black Palestinian flag, out of the plane into
a waiting ambulance an hour after its arrival.
   A Tunisian commission investigating the assassination has
concluded that the operation was conducted by Israel commandos.
   The Tunisian ambassador to Washington said Tuesday the most
conclusive piece of evidence was the presence of a Boeing 707
aircraft with Israeli markings off the Tunisian coast at the time
of the assassination.
   The plane used sophisticated electronic equipment to jam
telecommunications around the town where al-Wazir lived, he said.
</TEXT>
