<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Moonwalk 1stLd-Writethru a0716 04-19 0832</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Moonwalk, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0716,0849</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Life Is a Lonely Moonwalk for Michael Jackson</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs lead to CORRECT proper name to Doh, sted Dough. Inserts
1 graf after 15th, `Areheart, who...' to add quote that editors
didn't pressure Jackson on subjects.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Jackson pranced, danced and rocked at an
age when most kids are still molding Play Doh. An international
star and millionaire by adolescence, his life has remained
shrouded. His new autobiography, ``Moonwalk,'' hopes to rip through
that cloak.
   It doesn't. What we have here is a failure to titillate.
   The 283-page book, to be released this week by Doubleday, does
not name lovers, explain the megastar's affection for the Elephant
Man, detail massive plastic surgery and skin whitening, talk about
the oxygen pressure chamber he purportedly wanted to prolong his
life, or serve up any other delicious show biz dish.
   Rather, ``Moonwalk'' is a gentle excursion into the 24 years
Jackson has spent as a performer. The title refers to the sliding
dance step he popularized.
   ``I was interested in being able to talk about how I feel in a
book that would be mine _ my words and my voice,'' the 29-year-old
star says. ``I hope it will clear up some misconceptions.''
   Misconceptions are as plentiful in Jackson's life as screaming
teen-agers at his concerts. The media, it seems, has not been kind
to little Michael.
   ``I don't understand why they feel the need to make up things
about me,'' he writes. ``I take some small pride in thinking that
I've come out pretty well, all things considered. ... It's a
difficult life. Very few manage any semblance of a normal
childhood.''
   He admits to having two nose jobs and a chin cleft. However, he
said he has not had his cheeks or eyes altered or a skin peel.
   He acknowledges long-standing friendships with Tatum O'Neal,
Brooke Shields, Liza Minnelli, Elizabeth Taylor and Diana Ross _
but there is no kiss and tell.
   The closest he gets is a passage about a date with O'Neal. They
went to a club in Los Angeles called On the Rox, and the young
actress grabbed his hand.
   ``This probably wouldn't mean a lot to other people, but it was
serious stuff to me. She touched me,'' he says in the book.
   Jackson was asked to do the book in 1984 by two Doubleday
editors _ Jacqueline Onassis, who wrote the dedication page, and
Shaye Areheart, who worked closely with the reclusive star and
helped him write.
   ``He was someone we admired and thought was a real musical
genius, and he had had a long and fascinating career, considering
his age,'' Areheart said in an interview. ``I think the book
reflects the Michael Jackson I've come to know. He's very
sensitive, very loyal, very kind.
   ``He's every inch a professional; he's that way in every aspect
of his life. He's very articulate, very intelligent, very creative,
very lovely.''
   Areheart, who has been a Doubleday editor for nine years, said
both she and Jackson were satisfied with the result.
   ``I didn't put any pressure on him about subjects he wanted to
discuss in the book,'' she said. ``I wanted him to write a book
that reflected things he wanted to share with people. I thought he
was amazingly candid and warm and did an excellent job.''
   Jackson's honesty is illuminated in his feelings about his
loneliness, his family, how his career was managed and his missed
childhood.
   He started performing when he was 5 and recalled coming home
from school, dropping his books, going to the studio, returning
home around midnight and sometimes never even having time for a
snack. There was a park across the street from the Motown studio,
and he used to watch other youngsters at play.
   ``I'd just stare at them in wonder _ I couldn't imagine such
freedom, such a carefree life _ and wish more than anything that I
had that kind of freedom, that I could walk away and be like them.
So there were sad moments in my childhood,'' he said.
   Michael Jackson is the seventh of nine children born to Joseph
and Katherine Jackson in Gary, Ind. He performed as lead singer
with his older brothers as the Jackson 5. They released 26 albums
for Motown and Epic.
   Their father, a steel mill worker who played with a local rhythm
and blues band, was extremely strict with the young performers.
   ``We'd perform for him and he'd critique us,'' Jackson writes.
``If you messed up, you got hit, sometimes with a belt, sometimes
with a switch. ... Dad would make me so mad and hurt that I'd try
to get back at him and get beaten all the more.''
   When he turned 21, his father's management contract expired, and
Michael, dissatisfied with how his career was going, especially
with Motown's refusal to allow the Jacksons to write and produce,
fired him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
