<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Meese-Probe     04-19 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese-Probe,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Says He was Unaware of Benders' Involvement In Lease</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III said Tuesday
he didn't know until last week that the real estate family
contributing money for his wife's salary was leasing office space
to the Justice Department.
   In his first comments to reporters on the subject, Meese said
``there's absolutely no connection'' between his wife's
$40,000-a-year salary donated to a charity by the Bender family
foundation and a subsequent $50 million Justice Department lease
with a partnership headed by Howard M. Bender.
   Meese also said that as attorney general he ``never participated
in any matter pertaining to the Benders.''
   After meeting with several Republican congressmen on Capitol
Hill to discuss his trip earlier this month to South America, Meese
was asked whether it would have been better not to accept money
that was coming from a family that was renting offices to the
Justice Department.
   ``I think at the time nobody knew that they (the Benders) were
renting buildings to the Justice Department,'' he replied. ``As a
matter of fact, I didn't know that until I saw it in the news media
last week.''
   The Associated Press reported last Wednesday that a partnership
headed by Bender won a $50 million lease renewal on a Justice
Department building housing offices of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, a Justice Department agency.
   Thirteen days after obtaining the new lease, real estate
developer Bender and his partners sold the building for $22.6
million more than they had paid for it two years earlier, earning a
60 percent profit.
   ``Let me just say there's absolutely no connection between the
two things (his wife's salary and the Bender's business with the
Justice Department) and I think that will be made plain ultimately
when all the facts are out,'' Meese said.
   The attorney general was referring to the criminal investigation
of his activities being conducted by independent counsel James
McKay.
   McKay is looking into the involvement of longtime Meese friend
E. Robert Wallach in Ursula Meese taking her position with the
Multiple Sclerosis Society, to which the Bender Foundation
contributed the money constituting her salary.
   Wallach's attorney, George Walker, has told The Washington Post
that Wallach played a ``peripheral'' role in Mrs. Meese taking the
job at the MS Society.
   Wallach's ties to Meese and Wallach's and Meese's involvement
with scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp. triggered McKay's probe of the
attorney general last May 11.
   Since then, the investigation has spread to Mrs. Meese's job and
Meese's actions on behalf of a $1 billion Iraqi oil pipeline
project in which Wallach was acting as a lawyer for one of the
partners.
   In addition, McKay has been delving into Meese's ownership of
$14,000 in regional Bell telephone company stock during a time when
as attorney general he was meeting with executives of the ``Baby
Bell'' companies.
</TEXT>
