<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 1851EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Cubans-Deportation     04-19 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cubans-Deportation,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>About 1,000 Cubans Move Step Closer To Deportation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,000 Cubans in federal custody have been
determined a risk to the community by the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, bringing them one step closer to
deportation, officials said.
   The INS will begin informing the prisoners this week that they
are considered ``non-releasable,'' Duke Austin, an INS spokesman in
Washington, said Monday.
   The agency's action follows an agreement last year between the
government and rioting Cuban prisoners in Atlanta, which called for
a review of the cases of 3,800 Cubans in detention at the time.
   But in Miami, a lawyer who was present at the signing of the
agreement complained that prisoners were not allowed to present
evidence or witnesses during the INS review.
   ``It's a paper review. It's a joke,'' said Rafael Penalver. The
prisoners also will not get hearings during the appeal process, he
added.
   The prisoners, who came to the United States in the 1980
boatlift from the Cuban port of Mariel, had committed crimes in
this country and served out their prison terms before the INS
detained them indefinitely.
   In addition to the 1,000 judged non-releasable, about 2,100 of
the detainees have been released or approved for release, INS
officials said. The rest still are being reviewed.
   Once they get their notices, the prisoners have 30 days to
appeal to the INS. If that fails, they can appeal to a special
Justice Department panel.
   Anyone failing both appeals can remain in detention
indefinitely. But many of the non-releasable detainees also will
receive deportation notices, said Justice Department spokesman
Patrick Korten. The deportation process includes two further
chances at appeal.
   ``I think this is due process, and then some,'' Korten said.
   Korten would not say when deportation notices would be sent, or
how long the appeals could take.
   The prisoners rioted last fall, days after the State Department
announced on Nov. 20 that an immigration pact with Cuba had been
renewed.
   Under the accord, up to 20,000 Cubans could come to the United
States each year as immigrants and up to 3,000 more could arrive as
refugees. Cuba, in turn, agreed to take back at least 2,545 Mariel
felons in INS custody.
   The news sparked riots at prisons in Atlanta and in Oakdale, La.
Many of the detainees had spent years in INS detention and expected
to be released under an INS review that started last June.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
