<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PENFictionAward     04-19 0142</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PEN Fiction Award,130</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For release at 6 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Boyle Wins Fiction Award for `World's End'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American writer T. Coraghessan Boyle was named
the winner Tuesday of the $5,000 PEN@Faulkner award for fiction for
his 1987 historical epic, ``World's End.''
   The novel traces the destinies of three families for 300 years.
   The award is administered by the Folger Shakespeare Library for
the PEN@Faulkner Foundations. It is supported by grants as well as
proceeds from public readings at the library.
   Boyle, 40, is the author of four previous books. He will receive
the award at a ceremony May 14 at the library.
   Four other writers, of 200 nominated for the award, will receive
$1,000. They are Richard Bausch for ``Spirits''; Alice McDermott
for ``That Night''; Cynthia Ozick for ``The Messiah of Stockholm'';
and Lawrence Thornton for ``Imagining Argentina.''
</TEXT>
