<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HabitatforHumanity     04-19 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Habitat for Humanity,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Habitat To Build 20 Atlanta Homes In Largest Project To Date</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Habitat for Humanity announced Tuesday it will
build 20 homes for Atlanta's working poor in a five-day crash
project starting June 27, the 12-year-old volunteer agency's most
ambitious project.
   The effort, named the Jimmy Carter Work Project '88 after
Habitat's best-known volunteer, is intended ``to fill a void
between a market economy that does not reach down to some economic
classes and a government with other spending priorities,'' said
project director Bruce Gunter.
   Carter said Habitat ``arouses the conscience of the world to the
problem of the homeless'' and to the ``disgrace in our own rich
nation of the homeless situation.''
   The Americus-based Habitat has built more than 4,000 homes for
the working poor on a non-profit, no-interest basis since 1976 and
expects to complete 2,000 this year. It has chapters in 277
American cities and 26 other countries.
   Recipients of the homes, who have to help build them, pay back
the cost usually over 20 years with mortgages averaging $118 a
month. The money goes into a revolving fund used to build more
houses. Most of the labor is volunteer.
   The houses are wood-frame structures designed to be simple but
adequate with all of the basics and few frills.
   Habitat has built 24 homes in Atlanta since it started in the
city in 1983 and hopes to complete 75 by 1990. City figures show 31
percent of Atlanta's housing to be substandard, compared with a
nationwide average of 8 percent.
   ``Habitat is doing what the federal, state and local governments
should be doing,'' said Mayor Andrew Young, who also is active in
the Habitat organization. ``Habitat is showing us the way.''
   So far 10 families have been picked for the 20 homes to be built
in the $600,000 project.
   The first house has already been built to serve as the temporary
project office.
   After construction is over, Evelyn Jackson will move into the
three-bedroom house with her two children. The Oglethorpe
University housekeeper has lived all her life in the
down-at-the-edges southeast Atlanta neighborhood where the block of
homes will be built.
   ``This means I can keep my roots here,'' she said. `We helped
frame it up and insulate it.''
   ``There was a lot I didn't know and they showed me how,'' she
said. ``Now if something goes wrong maybe I can fix it myself.''
   Habitat also will build five row houses in Philadelphia starting
June 20 and has announced a 12-week, 1,200-mile march from
Portland, Maine, to Atlanta starting June 26 during which Habitat
volunteers plan to build 120 homes and collect $1.2 million in
donations to initiate more construction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
