<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 1940EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PentagonAdvisoryPanels     04-19 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pentagon Advisory Panels,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Needs Better Ethics Oversight of Advisory Panels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department needs to improve its
compliance with a law designed to eliminate conflict of interest
questions about Pentagon advisers, the General Accounting Office
said Tuesday.
   The Pentagon ``is generally complying with'' the Federal
Advisory Committee Act, but ``some key steps still have not been
implemented and should be,'' said Rosslyn Kleeman of the
congressional watchdog agency.
   The testimony before the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee
centered on expert panels created to advise the Strategic Defense
Initiative Organization, the office created in 1983 to oversee
President Reagan's Star Wars anti-missile program.
   The SDIO was chosen for a review because it uses a large number
of expert committees. Throughout the government, there are more
than 1,000 advisory committees on a wide range of topics.
   Five years ago, the Pentagon was sharply criticized for lax
management of conflict-of-interest and ethical questions and the
SDIO advisory committees were created after that review.
   Although the Defense Department is doing a better job, it's
still not good enough, the GAO said.
   ``Specifically, the advisory committees need to document the
reasons why individuals were selected for advisory committees and
panels in order to demonstrate how they went about achieving the
balanced membership required in the act,'' Kleeman said.
   In addition, the GAO study said the committees need better
documentation of financial disclosure statements made by panel
members, and need a better review process to make sure ethical
questions are answered.
   Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, chairman of the panel, said the
Pentagon has taken steps to improve its oversight of the committees.
   But he added that the Pentagon's ``compliance ... remains open
to question'' with a requirement for documenting why people are
picked.
   David O. Cooke, deputy assistant secretary of defense for
administration, testified that the Pentagon has tried to improve
its oversight of the panels.
   ``Problems regarding the administration of DoD advisory
committees sometimes surface,'' he said. ``When they do, we address
them promptly.''
   William Carroll, general counsel for the SDIO, admitted that his
office had found ``a weakness in our internal management controls''
which delayed appointments of consultants.
   David Parnas, a computer scientist at Queen's University in
Ontario, Canada, testified that three years ago he was offered
$1,000 per day to serve on a panel advising the SDIO on computer
software. He said he was appointed despite the fact he told
Pentagon officials he already was a part-time employee of the Naval
Research Laboratory.
</TEXT>
