<DOCNO> AP880419-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 1739EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Demjanjuk     04-19 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Demjanjuk,0637</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israelis Praise Demjanjuk Verdict, Family Says Trial Unfair</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland-Jews, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A death camp survivor said Tuesday that the
conviction of John Demjanjuk for Nazi war crimes avenged millions
of Jews killed in the Holocaust, but Demjanjuk's family contended
he was the victim of biased judges.
   ``This verdict is revenge for all those who did not survive,'' a
jubilant Pinchas Epstein told Israel radio.
   Epstein had testified during the 14-month trial that he
recognized the retired U.S. autoworker as ``Ivan the Terrible,''
the nickname used by prisoners at Treblinka death camp for one of
their guards.
   Demjanjuk's son, John, condemned the verdict as ``ludicrously
sweeping'' and said it resulted from ``judges who lost their
impartiality.''
   ``Five, 10, 15 years from now, when people look back at this
trial, John Demjanjuk is going to be remembered as the victim,''
his son said.
   Israeli officials applauded the conviction Tuesday, and Justice
Minister Avraham Sharir called for the death penalty. Demjanjuk is
to be sentenced next Monday.
   Demjanjuk, of suburban Cleveland, was convicted of operating gas
chambers that killed 850,000 Jews at Treblinka in Nazi-occupied
Poland in 1942 and 1943. In a 450-page decision, the judges
rejected all defense arguments.
   The Ukrainian-born Demjanjuk, 68, has maintained he is a victim
of mistaken identity who was a Nazi prisoner of war and was not at
Treblinka.
   Epstein, one of five survivors who identified Demjanjuk as
``Ivan the Terrible,'' left the courtroom in tears Monday when
judges described atrocities committed by the Nazi guard.
   Israel's prime minister, Yitzhak Shamir, praised the trial and
conviction. ``Every Jew feels a certain degree of satisfaction from
the conviction of Demjanjuk,'' the Polish-born Shamir told Israel
radio on Tuesday. His parents were killed in the Holocaust.
   Speaking from Paris, Justice Minister Sharir called for
Demjanjuk to be sentenced to death. ``A man convicted of such
terrible crimes deserves no other sentence,'' he told Israel radio.
   However, he has no authority over the state prosecutor, who will
argue the sentence at Monday's hearing.
   In a rare public comment, former Prime Minister Menachem Begin,
who also lost family in the Holocaust, lauded the legal proceedings.
   ``It was a just trial,'' Begin, who has lived in seclusion for
the past five years, told Israel radio. ``Thanks to the trial, the
younger Israeli generation learned about the fate of the Jews in
the Holocaust.''
   About 6 million Jews were put to death in the Holocaust.
   Zvi Terlow, who helped prosecute Adolf Eichmann, the only other
man tried in Israel for Nazi war crimes, said he was certain the
judges would not have convicted Demjanjuk if there were doubts
about his identity.
   ``No stone was left unturned, there was a mountain of
evidence,'' Terlow said.
   Eichmann, the architect of the Holocaust, was convicted and
hanged in 1962.
   Demjanjuk's son-in-law, Ed Nishnic, said the judges
automatically rejected defense arguments.
   ``It was as though the judges were sitting there with their ears
covered and their eyes closed during the defense side of the
case,'' he said.
   John Demjanjuk Jr. said: ``Judging by the way they conducted the
trial and totally disregarded our evidence in their verdict, we
don't expect anything less than the death penalty.''
   Demjanjuk's attorney, John Gill of Cleveland, said although he
had expected a guilty verdict at the emotionally charged trial,
``It totally surprised me that they (the judges) could be so
devastatingly sweeping.''
   Gill said he would argue against the death penalty on Monday and
planned to appeal to the Supreme Court.
   There is no minimum sentence but Demjanjuk is considered
unlikely to receive anything short of life imprisonment.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880419-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 1946EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Wheat-Soviets     04-19 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wheat-Soviets,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Large Soviet Grain Purchases Brighten U.S. Farm Prospects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financial prospects for American farmers
continue to brighten, and one reason is a pickup in grain exports
this year, an Agriculture Department report said Tuesday.
   Large purchases by the Soviet Union, particularly wheat sold at
subsidized prices, have played an important role.
   Overall, the Soviet Union's total grain imports are at a
three-year high, despite bumper harvests the last two seasons, the
report said.
   ``The gain is primarily from larger wheat purchases,'' the
department's Economic Research Service said. ``Aided by the Export
Enhancement Program and Soviet demand for milling-quality wheat,
the U.S. share of import volume is likely to rise to about half
this year, up from less than 1 percent in 1985-86.''
   The Soviet Union is expected to import 32 million metric tons of
grain from all foreign sources in the international marketing year
that runs through June 30, 1988. That would be the most since
imports were a record 55.5 million tons in 1984-85.
   The wheat share of this year's imports is estimated at 22
million tons, the most since 1984-85 when wheat rose to 28.1
million tons.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat.
   Soviet wheat imports dropped sharply in 1985-86 to 15.7 million
tons, when the U.S. share declined to a trickle.
   Under a five-year agreement, the Soviet Union is committed to
buy at least 4 million tons of wheat and 4 million tons of corn
annually. The pact expires Sept. 30 and covers the year that began
last Oct. 1.
   Although the agreement year is three months out of step with the
July 1-June 30 marketing year, it does show a similar trend in
Soviet grain imports.
   For example, Soviet wheat purchases fell short of the pact's
minimum in 1984-85 when they dropped to 2.9 million tons, and in
1985-86 when they were only 200,000 tons. That coincided with the
``less than 1 percent'' U.S. share cited in the latest report.
   The Export Enhancement Progam allows exporters to sell
designated commodities to specified countries at reduced prices and
then collect free USDA-owned commodities as bonuses, or subsidies.
   Subsidized wheat sales to the Soviet Union began a year ago. So
far Moscow has bought more than 8.8 million tons for delivery in
1987-88, the final year of the grain pact.
   In addition, the Soviets have bought 4.1 million tons of U.S.
corn, 818,400 tons of soybeans and 1.3 million tons of soybean meal
for delivery through Sept. 30.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
