<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Scotus-Vaccine     04-19 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scotus-Vaccine,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Fights Lawsuit By Polio Victim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan admnistration, supporting sweeping
legal immunity for the government, urged the Supreme Court on
Tuesday to kill a lawsuit in behalf of a boy who contracted polio
after receiving a dose of federally approved vaccine.
   Some justices reacted skeptically to arguments by Justice
Department lawyer Michael K. Kellogg, who said the government
should be shielded from paying damages.
   ``If you win, you might as well repeal the (Federal) Tort Claims
Act,'' Justice Byron R. White told Kellogg.
   The act permits the government to be sued in limited instances
when officials negligently cause personal injuries. The law does
not surrender government immunity for injuries resulting from an
official's ``discretionary function or duty.''
   Kellogg urged the court to protect the government from suit
``even if a specific (federal) employee is negligent'' _ and is not
exercising discretion.
   The court is expected to announce by July whether it will revive
a suit in behalf of polio victim Kevan Berkovitz, who was less than
three months old on May 10, 1979 when his pediatrician in
Charleroi, Pa., gave him a dose of Orimune.
   The drug, manufactured by Lederle Laboratories, is a form of
Sabin oral vaccine. Orimune was licensed by the government in 1963.
   Kevan was stricken with polio within a month and the U.S.
Communicable Disease Center determined he contracted the disease
from the vaccine. He is paralyzed and deformed and breathes with
the help of a respirator.
   Ms. Ellen M. Viakley, a lawyer representing the Berkovitz
family, urged the court Tuesday to revive the suit to allow the
family to prove that it may have been ``pure, sheer negligence'' by
government workers that caused the child's polio.
   She alleged that in licensing the vaccine, federal workers
approved it even though the number and size of lesions it caused
exceeded the government's standards. It was not a discretionary
decision by the government that the defective vaccine was safe, she
said.
   ``The allegation is that the numbers (of lesions) didn't add
up,'' Justice Sandra Day O'Connor later said to Kellogg, the
government lawyer.
   He did not dispute that interpretation. But Kellogg said even
when an employee is negligent, the government agency he works for
may be using its discretion in approving the vaccine.
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals threw out the Berkovitz's
suit last year.
   The appeals court said the Food and Drug Administration is
exempt from the suit because the FDA exercised policy-making
authority _ in effect, its own discretion _ when it initially
decided to verify test results by vaccine manufacturers.
   The FDA's decision on how to go about testing the safety of
polio vaccine is a discretionary act that immunizes the government
from suit, the appeals court said.
   The administration has argued that if the government can be sued
in such cases, it will be forced into becoming an insurer of
vaccines and may withdraw from licensing them.
   Federal officials said Sabin oral vaccine, administered
routinely to all children in the United States, has all but
eliminated polio even though each year a few who take the vaccine
have adverse reactions.
   The case is Berkovitz vs. U.S., 87-498.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
