<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0679 04-19 0906</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0679,0929</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Deports 8 More Palestinians</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TUN2</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 13 grafs, Arab dies and other dvpts; picks up 12th
`A 15-year-old' with editing to trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel deported eight more Palestinians from
the occupied lands to Lebanon on Tuesday, including six involved in
a stoning attack on teen-age Israeli hikers in a West Bank village,
the army said.
   In other developments, Ezer Weizman, a Cabinet minister without
portfolio, said the assassination of PLO military commander Khalil
al-Wazir last week may lead to more terrorism. The army censored a
newspaper editorial criticizing Israel's reported role in the
killing.
   Army officials said for the first time that the April 6 attack
on the hikers was planned. A teen-aged Jewish settler and two
Palestinians were killed.
   The officials said the planning was done by some of those in the
group of deportees, and described them as members of an outlawed
Palestine Liberation Organization youth group.
   An army spokesman said soldiers set up roadblocks to stop Arab
residents of the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip from entering
Israel for two days beginning Tuesday night.
   He said the measure was aimed at preventing terror attacks on
Memorial Day, which began after nightfall Tuesday, and Independence
Day, which begins Wednesday night and marks the 40th anniversary of
the nation's birth.
   A Palestinian died Tuesday of wounds suffered the day before in
a clash with soldiers in the Pekoah, a West Bank village, an army
spokesman said.
   At least 168 Palestinians have been reported killed since riots
began Dec. 8 in the West Bank and Gaza, which Israel has occupied
since capturing them from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East
war. An Israeli soldier and civilian also have been slain.
   Curfews continued on 17 refugee camps and towns in the West Bank
and seven of eight refugee camps in Gaza. Major cities also
remained off limits to non-residents, including journalists.
   Hospital officials said a 16-year-old Palestinian was wounded
during clashes in Gaza City. The army reported relative calm
elsewhere.
   ``There is no doubt that the number of disturbances has declined
in the past three days,'' said an army spokeswoman, who attributed
it to the clampdown.
   Three Arabs have been killed since Saturday, when 15 died in
riots that began with the news that al-Wazir had been killed in
Tunis.
   Tuesday's deportations brought to 20 the number expelled since
the rebellion began. Six were from Beita, the West Bank village,
where residents stoned 16 teen-age Jewish hikers from a nearby
settlement and their two armed guards.
   A 15-year-old Israeli girl, Tirza Porat, and two Beita residents
were killed in the clash. An army report said Ms. Porat was killed
by a bullet fired from the weapon of one of the Israeli guards.
Initial reports said she had been stoned to death by Palestinians.
   Col. Raanan Gissin, deputy army spokesman, said one deportee,
Njjah Jamil Saada Daweikat, led the hikers into the village.
Previous reports said they followed after receiving promises of
protection.
   Daweikat admitted inciting another villager to attack an Israeli
youth, Gissin said. He added that another deportee, Mahmoud Adnan
Bani-Shamseh, took the gun away from one of the Israeli guards and
did not surrender it until he was arrested several days later.
   A military official who demanded anonymity said the six Beita
deportees were organizers in Shabibeh, an outlawed PLO youth group.
For more than a month, he claimed, the group had run Beita after
declaring it a ``liberated village.''
   ``They had planned an attack on hikers in advance. When this
group came from (the Jewish settlement of) Elon Moreh, the
opportunity presented itself. They had planned to take a group into
the village and hold them hostage,'' he said.
   The army bulldozed 14 houses of those who allegedly took part in
the stoning. One resident later was found to have tried to help the
settlers and the army promised compensation.
   According to the military official, those deported were planners
of attacks on civilians, not stone-throwers. ``They had planned it
beforehand,'' he said.
   Hanna Siniora, editor of the pro-PLO daily Al Fajr, predicted
expulsion would ``inflame the situation and actually add to the
determination of the Palestinian people in their struggle for their
national aspirations.''
   Elias Freij, mayor of Bethlehem, said it had been proven that
Ms. Porat died from a bullet fired by a Jewish guard and the
deportees were ``innocent victims of provocation by the Jewish
settlers.''
   The United States has condemned deportations, saying
international law bans transfer across borders of civilians living
in occupied zones.
   On Tuesday, State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley
criticized the latest expulsions. Israel says only mass
deportations are illegal.
   Israeli sources say Israeli commandos shot and killed al-Wazir
at his home, but the nation's leaders have been silent on the
subject.
   NBC-TV reported the attack was approved at a Cabinet meeting
last week, with dissenting votes cast by Foreign Minister Shimon
Peres and Weizman, a former defense minister.
   Weizman declined to say if Israel was responsible but told
Israel radio the killing would lead to more terrorism. ``It
distances the peace process and will bring greater hostility and
make us more vulnerable around the world.''
   Israel's military censor took the unusual step of censoring an
entire editorial in the Yediot Ahronot daily.
   Newspaper sources said the editorial dealt with Israel's role in
al-Wazir's killing.
</TEXT>
