<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Primaries,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israelis Worried About Jesse Jackson Popularity</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Primary Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli leaders privately expressed concern
about Jesse Jackson's rising popularity, but avoided saying
publicly whom they want to see in the White House next year to
avoid embarrassment after November elections.
   Political observers said Israel's favorite is Vice President
George Bush.
   ``Bush would likely be best because he is a known quantity,''
said political scientist Rafaela Bilsky of Jerusalem's Hebrew
University, adding that Democratic presidential hopeful Michael
Dukakis ``is an unknown.''
   She said Israeli leaders were not expected to voice their
preference. ``It's a matter of political wisdom, etiquette. If we
say who we'd like, then what happens if the other guy is elected?''
she said.
   In a recent interview, right-wing Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir
refused to state his preference in the U.S. presidential race.
   All candidates have stated views on the Arab-Israeli conflict
that conflict with the position of Shamir, who opposes territorial
compromise with the Arabs.
   Asked about the views of the presidential contenders, Shamir
said: ``I would prefer to discuss this with the people in the
government.'' He declined to elaborate.
   Some Shamir associates, however, broke with tradition and
expressed apprehension about prospects that Jackson would run on
the Democratic ticket.
   ``We have fears because Mr. Jackson has said some very tough
things about Jews and voiced sympathy for the PLO (the Palestine
Liberation Organization),'' legislator Sarah Doron of Shamir's
right-wing Likud bloc said in a telephone interview.
   Ms. Doron refused to say which candidate she favored.
   ``We prefer to refrain from interfering in the American
elections, just the same as I would expect any other country to
refrain from interfering in our politics,'' she said.
   The Israeli public has shown great interest in the U.S. campaign
and the local media have covered it extensively.
   Most commentaries focused on Jackson's popularity, debating what
it means to the Jewish state.
   The mass-circulation Maariv daily called on American Jews to
vote against the Democrats if Jackson was on the ticket.
   ``He has publicly embraced (PLO chief Yasser) Arafat. In many
years there has not been such a prominent political leader in the
United States who has shown such hostility toward Jews in general
and particularly toward Israel,'' the newspaper said in a recent
editorial.
   ``We hope that American Jews will draw the proper conclusions
about the party in which Jesse Jackson plays a key role.''
   An opinion column in the liberal Haaretz daily, however, urged
Israeli leaders to accept Jackson's status and open a dialogue with
him ``because he is one of the most influential leaders in the .. .
Democratic Party.''
   Most commentators agree the outcome of the November elections
will have little influence on U.S.-Israeli ties.
   ``It will only be a matter of whether things will be harder or
easier,'' Ms. Bilsky said.
</TEXT>
