<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Lighthouse     04-19 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lighthouse,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Little Red Lighthouse Considered for Landmark Status</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SHANAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A little red lighthouse brought to life in a
1942 children's story was proposed for landmark status Tuesday by a
9-year-old who clambered up to the microphone at a hearing to
retell the tale of the proud beacon.
   Standing on a chair at the Landmarks Preservation Commission
hearing, Jonny Goldin said that his father, City Comptroller
Harrison Goldin, read him ``The Little Red Lighthouse and the Great
Gray Bridge'' when he was ``a little boy.''
   ``I found it hard to imagine it really existed,'' Jonny said at
the City Hall hearing. But his father later took him to see it on
the bank of the Hudson River in the shadow of the George Washington
Bridge in upper Manhattan.
   ``We should make sure that it is always there for boys and girls
to enjoy forever,'' Jonny said.
   Supporters of making the 67-year-old lighthouse known
technically as Jeffrey's Hook Light a landmark say the beacon
recalls the age of mariners in America and has special significance
to children of all ages.
   Once a structure is designated a landmark, changes in it require
commission approval.
   Gene A. Norman, commission chairman, said it could take several
months to examine staff studies before deciding whether The Little
Red Lighthouse should become a landmark.
   The children's story by Hildegarde Hoyt Swift and Lynd Ward
tells how the lighthouse coped with suddenly being overshadowed by
the bridge.
   ``You know the story,'' Jonny told the commission. ``The
lighthouse is proud of its job warning ships and tugboats and
barges not to come too close to the rocky shore of the Hudson
River.''
   However, the George Washington Bridge is built later, the story
goes, and the beacon is in danger of being closed because the
bridge has a warning light on one of its towers.
   ``At the end of the book, though, the lighthouse is still seen
as necessary for safe navigation, and the bridge calls it `Little
Brother','' young Goldin related.
   Real life wasn't as kind to the lighthouse. Six years after the
1942 book was published, the Coast Guard took the light out of
service.
   Built in 1921, it was a replacement for a simple light pole with
two 10-candlepower oil lanterns. The bridge opened in 1931.
   The lighthouse is a cylindrical steel and cast-iron structure,
40 feet high and 14{-feet in diameter. Resting on a concrete slab,
it rises 61 feet above the water.
   The commission also is considering a proposal to make a
60-foot-high Pepsi-Cola neon sign on the East River waterfront in
Queens a landmark.
   Built in 1936, it is considered by the commission staff to be an
excellent example of neon display technology that began to
transform outdoor advertising in the 1920s.
   Its designation as a landmark was opposed by Queens Borough
President Claire Shulman, who said it could delay development of a
$155 million project for residential, commercial and recreational
use of the area.
   Former Parks Commissioner Gordon Davis, an attorney for Pepsico
Inc., asked for a delay in any designation so the soft drink firm
could study the proposal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
