<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras-Rights,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Orders Former Honduran Military Chief's Arrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A civilian court acting on
complaints by human rights groups ordered Tuesday that Gen. Gustavo
Alvarez Martinez, the former military commander, be held for
possible trial.
   The warrant ordered Alvarez Martinez into house arrest for six
days. During that time Judge Suazo Lara of the First Criminal Court
must either issue a formal indictment on charges of murder and
other human rights abuses or order the case dropped for lack of
evidence.
   Suazo acted on a petition by the Committee of Relatives of
Disappeared People and the Human Rights Commission, which claim
Alvarez Martinez was responsible for the killings of 30 people and
the disappearance of 130 others in the custody of security forces.
   They say the killings and disappearances occurred during the
four years Alvarez Martinez was chief of the armed forces and
effective head of state. He was forced out by fellow officers April
31, 1984, and went to live in Miami but returned to Tegucigalpa on
April 9.
</TEXT>
