<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TVRatings 2ndLd-Writethru a0764 04-19 0770</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TV Ratings, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0764,0784</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>End of TV Season Has Networks Evaluating Extent of Erosion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `NBC topped ...' to ADD weekly rating. Picks
up 5th graf pvs, `NBC ended ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC won its third television season in a row
Tuesday and is already looking toward another win next season when
its Summer Olympics coverage could give it a jump on the
competition if the writers' strike continues.
   If the 6-week-old strike isn't settled soon, ABC and CBS might
not have new shows ready for air in September and could be forced
to continue summer reruns _and that could speed a continuing
defection of viewers to cable and other alternatives.
   NBC, meanwhile, will start the season with the historically
high-rated Olympics, and NBC's Vice President for Research Projects
Gerald Jaffe said Tuesday that advertising interest in the Olympics
is ``picking up.''
   NBC topped off the season by winning the final week, though the
60th Annual Academy Awards on ABC was the No. 1 show of the week,
according to the A.C. Nielsen Co. figures. For the week, NBC had an
average rating of 13.9, ABC 13.5 and CBS 11.8. The rating is a
percentage of the nation's 88.6 million homes with television.
   NBC ended the season with an average, prime-time rating of 16.0.
ABC, which had been third for three years running, eked out second
with a 13.7, thanks to the World Series, Super Bowl and Winter
Olympics. CBS was third for the first time ever, with 13.5. The
rating is a percentage of the nation's 88.6 million households with
televisions.
   NBC had never won a season before 1985-86. This was NBC's
biggest win yet, and the biggest margin of victory for any network
since CBS won in 1963-64.
   But Nielsen ratings showed the three-network average down 9
percent from last year. That figure was disputed by Jaffe, who said
his own comparison of more extensive local-market surveys showed a
network decline of only 3 percent.
   He attributed the discrepancy to inaccuracies in Nielsen's new
people meter audience measurement system.
   Last week, CBS released preliminary figures from a competing
ratings company, AGB, that showed CBS coming in slightly ahead of
ABC. Nielsen is still the ratings company used by advertisers to
negotiate advertising rates, though. CBS has estimated that the
lower people meter figures will cost the networks a combined $50
million in advertising revenues.
   The three networks have hired a consulting firm to scrutinize
the new ratings system, said Bill Rubens, NBC vice president for
research. The results are expected sometime this summer.
   Whether 9 percent or 3 percent, though, the networks are losing
viewers to cable, independent stations and VCRs.
   Jaffe said the decline is reversible if networks can put on
enough popular shows like ``The Cosby Show,'' which increased total
network viewing on Thursday night.
   ``The 3 percent is not immutable,'' Jaffe said. ``There is no
law of nature that says the networks will decline 3 percent every
year, ad infinitum.''
   ``The Cosby Show'' was the No. 1-rated show for the third year
in a row, followed by its spinoff, ``A Different World,'' NBC's
``Cheers'' and ``Golden Girls,'' ABC's ``Growing Pains,'' ``Who's
the Boss?'' NBC's ``Night Court,'' CBS' ``60 Minutes'' and
``Murder, She Wrote,'' and ABC's new show, ``The Wonder Years.''
   Of the two new shows that made the top 10, both were
significantly helped by their popular lead-ins, ``A Different
World'' by ``Cosby'' and ``Wonder Years'' by ``Who's the Boss?''
   The only other new shows to make even the top 30 were NBC's ``My
Two Dads'' at 21st, ``In the Heat of the Night,'' at 19th, and
``Aaron's Way'' at 30th. The latter two premiered late in the
season.
   Despite the lackluster performance by the new shows, Jaffe
predicted a third of them will be renewed, following the pattern of
previous years.
   The networks have parted company with big-event, multipart
miniseries. Of 12 miniseries last year, all but two were
two-parters. The top-rated ``Elvis and Me'' on ABC had rating of
24.5.
   ``The Ann Jillian Story'' on NBC was the top-rated TV movie with
23.8.
   News ratings are measured quarterly, not by season, but
beginning with the traditional television season in September when
Nielsen converted to the people meters, ``NBC Nightly News''
dropped into a third-place slump. Last week, the ``CBS Evening
News'' was No. 1 with a 10.1 and 21 share, narrowly edging ABC's
``World News Tonight'' with 9.9 and 20. ``NBC Nightly News'' had an
8.7 and 18.
   The share is a percentage of sets in use.
</TEXT>
