<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Gangs     04-19 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Gangs,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Buy Bigger Motorcycles to Battle Motorcycle Gang</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have bought powerful motorcycles to battle
a Moscow motorcycle gang called the Rockers that has caused
accidents and disturbed residents of the capital, Tass reported
Tuesday.
   The official news agency said police purchased German-made BMW
motorcycles that can travel up to 136 mph, but it did not say how
many.
   Tass said the Rockers will not be able to escape police pursuers
because their motorcycles are no match for the BMWs.
   It quoted N. Kurbatov, a captain of the police unit assigned to
stop the gang, as saying his officers concentrate in Moscow's ``hot
spots'' where ``motorhooligans'' prowl the streets, with the noise
of their machines awaking residents.
   ``The Rockers become active with the onset of warm days,'' Tass
said. ``Beginning April 1, a day hasn't gone by when because of
them there hasn't been a traffic accident with casualties. In these
accidents not only the hotheads suffer but also passengers sitting
behind their backs, as a rule minors who like to ride with the
wind.''
   It said 10,000 people are killed yearly in motorcycle accidents
throughout the Soviet Union.
   The agency said that since the beginning of April, Moscow police
have detained 62 ``supermen on motorcycles'' for lacking proper
documents, license plates or mufflers and for speeding or ignoring
traffic signs.
   Last year, Moscow's automobile clubs, youth organizations and
the city council tried unsucessfully to persuade the Rockers to
join official organizations or ride in designated areas where they
wouldn't disturb anyone.
   ``Now that they rejected this and that, maybe that's enough
persuasion,'' Tass said. ``It's time to move on to legal action.''
</TEXT>
