<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sudan-Refugees     04-19 0613</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan-Refugees,0633</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sudan Says It Will Not Allow Any Influx of Ethiopian Refugees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi said Tuesday
that Sudan was ``saturated'' with refugees and he would not accept
the expected influx of hundreds of thousands of people fleeing from
neighboring Ethiopia.
   Western relief officials expressed fear there could be heavy
loss of life among Ethiopia's refugees.
   Mahdi said he discussed the situation with Ethiopia's Marxist
government and with the U.N. Office of High Commissioner for
Refugees and other relief organizations. He said the talks were
aimed at organizing aid shipments to the affected people in the
Tigre and Eritrea regions in northern Ethiopia, or at setting up
camps inside Ethiopia near the border with Sudan.
   Secessionist warfare in the two regions complicates delivery of
relief to millions of people suffering because of famine and
drought.
   In a 30-minute interview at his Khartoum headquarters, the prime
minister told The Associated Press:
   ``We think that Sudan has been saturated and we cannot take any
more refugees.''
   He said he made that known last October.
   The U.N. agency estimates there are around 900,000 refugees in
Sudan including 677,000 Ethiopians. Sudan puts the figure at close
to 2 million.
   Mahdi was elected prime minister in April 1986, a year after a
military coup overthrew President Gaafar Nimeiri.
   Western relief officials here, speaking on condition of
anonymity, say from 2 million to 3 million Ethiopians in Tigre and
Eritrea will be affected by an expected Ethiopian government
offensive against rebels. The officials expect refugees by the
hundreds of thousands to move toward eastern Sudan within the next
month.
   They said there is no stockpile of relief food in the
drought-affected areas. The Ethiopian government recently banned
relief organizations from working in the northern zones.
   Mahdi said Sudan suggested it can help relief agencies send food
to Tigre and Eritrea across the Sudanese border, or set up camps
within Ethiopian territory to receive refugees.
   One relief official said he feared that once the rainy season
begins next month, it would be extremely difficult to move enough
food aid to eastern Sudan to handle the expected influx, whether it
was in Sudanese or Ethiopian territory.
   ``We will be hamstrung, and there could be large numbers of
fatalities,'' the official said.
   Over the weekend, Mahdi handed in his Cabinet's resignation to
form a new coalition government representing a greater number of
political parties. The five-man sovereign council, which acts in
place of a president, accepted the Cabinet's resignation but kept
Mahdi in power so he could form a new Cabinet.
   Mahdi said the new coaltion will include his centrist Umma
Party; the centrist Democratic Unionist Party, Umma's coaltion
partner for the past two years; the Moslem National Islamic Front;
the Southern Parties, and the small National Sudanese Party.
   Mahdi, discussing Sudan's own war in the south, said he hoped
improving relations with Ethiopia would gradually lead to an end of
Ethiopian aid to the rebel group the Sudan People's Liberation Army.
   The rebels are asking for greater autonomy as well as economic
and administrative reforms.
   In Addis Ababa, the capital of Ethiopia, the government said
U.N. aid workers can resume drought relief operations in the
war-torn north but more than 50 other Western workers remain barred
from the region, an official there said Tuesday.
   The policy reversal affects only four of 60 Western relief
workers.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said in Washington
the Ethiopian decision was ``a positive development. It's
important, however, to permit a wide range of private voluntary
organizations to work in the area if the needs of those at risk are
to be met.''
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
