<1ST_LINE>r a AM-US-GulfReax     04-19 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Gulf Reax,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Families of Men Missing in Persian Gulf Wait for News</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The families of two Marines from a
helicopter missing in the Persian Gulf awaited news and held out
hope Tuesday.
   ``There are times that we _ my wife and I _ feel stronger than
at others. There's times, particularly when we look at his
pictures, we find we're not as strong as we think,'' said Bob Hill,
father of Capt. Kenneth W. Hill, 33.
   Hill and the other crewman, Capt. Stephen C. Leslie, 30, are
assigned to Squadron HMLA-167 at the New River, N.C., Marine Corps
Air Station, said Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard.
   Leslie's home of record is New Bern; Hill's is Thomasville, the
Pentagon said.
   The attack helicopter failed to return from a reconnaissance
mission Monday.
   Iran claims to have shot down the helicopter during fighting in
which Iranian ships were sunk or crippled. Defense Secretary Frank
Carlucci refused to speculate about the aircraft's fate.
   President Reagan said nine ships were taking part in the search
Tuesday.
   ``We're just trying to hold out hope that they are going to be
picked up,'' that both of the men are going to found safe and
sound,'' said the elder Hill. ``It's hard to really earnestly hope
for it and believe it, but we hold to it.''
   Hill said the family received word about 9:30 p.m. Monday that
their son was missing. Hill said his son was married with one son.
   Leslie's younger sister, Kris Leslie, said the family received
word around midnight that her brother was missing. She said the
family had received no details since. ``We're very numb right
now,'' Ms. Leslie said.
   Leslie and his wife, Lisa, live in Jacksonville. He has been in
the Persian Gulf area since the end of January, Ms. Leslie said.
</TEXT>
