<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-19 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heavy Snow in Northern California</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A storm brought heavy snow to parts of northern California and
western Nevada on Tuesday, while large areas of the rest of the
nation had rain.
   The high elevations of Lassen Park in northern California
received one to two feet of snow. Rainfall at lower elevations
totaled as much as 1{ inches in northeastern parts of the state.
   The storm also brought nearly a quarter inch of rain to the San
Francisco Bay area, which has had little more than traces of rain
for most of the past 12 weeks. Water authorities said the rain
would provide little relief from the region's drought.
   A winter storm warning continued through Tuesday night over
parts of central and northern California, with two feet or more of
new snow expected in higher elevations.
   Light snow also dusted the mountains of West Virginia and
western New York state.
   Rain and thunderstorms hit central and northeast Florida. Tampa,
Fla. received 0.95 inch of rain in the six hours ending at 1 p.m.
EDT, and Titusville, Fla. was hit with heavy rain and hail three
quarters of an inch in diameter.
   Rain also stretched from central Colorado to southeast Wyoming.
Along the Atlantic Coast, rain also hit eastern Virginia, Delaware
and Maryland.
   The nation's morning low was 12 degrees at Aberdeen, S.D., which
was 3 degrees below the city's previous record, set in 1928.
   The mercury dropped to record lows in three Iowa cities early
Tuesday and tied all-time lows in three other locations. There were
reports of damage to apple trees as lows were registered in the
upper teens and low 20s.
   Temperatures at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 33 degrees at Wallops
Island, Va., to 90 degrees at Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
   Scattered rain was forecast Wednesday over northern Maine and
upper Michigan. Showers and possibly a few thunderstorms were
predicted to extend from the Pacific Coast to the Rockies, with
snow at higher elevations.
   Highs were forecast to be in the 30s and 40s in northern
Minnesota, the northern half of the Great Lakes and northern New
England. Highs were predicted to reach the 70s and 80s across the
south and southwest, stretching as far north as southern Nebraska
and South Carolina. Highs in most other parts of the country will
be in the 50s and 60s.
</TEXT>
