<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Iran     04-19 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Iran,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Makes Formal Complaint about U.S.; Vows Retaliation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran on Tuesday complained to the United
Nations about U.S. attacks in the Persian Gulf where the U.S. Navy
destroyed or disabled two Iranian oil platforms and six naval
vessels the day before.
   Iranian Ambassador Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati said Iran has the
right to retaliate by any means available for the American ``acts
of war'' and ``direct participation ... on behalf of Iraq.'' Iran
and Iraq have been at war since September 1980.
   The United States defended its action as ``necessary and
proportionate'' to the threat posed by Iranian actions. It told the
Security Council that U.S. forces ``exercised their inherent right
of self-defense.''
   A letter from U.S. Ambassador Herbert S. Okun, released Tuesday,
said the American actions were against ``legitimate military
targets'' and the United States does not seek a military
confrontation with Iran.
   Ali Akbar Velayati, the Iranian foreign minister, made his
complaint by letter. He asked Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar and the Security Council to condemn ``this American act of
aggression.''
   ``It is also expected that immediate preventative measures are
taken to stop the future recurrence of such crimes,'' said the
letter, published Tuesday as a U.N. document. It said Iran ``will
under no circumstances surrender to the politics of force and
manipulation and will certainly not leave this latest act of
injustice unanswered.''
   Velayati's letter cited the attacks on the oil platforms, which
it called ``premeditated acts of aggression'' by the ``war-monger
U.S. administration.''
   ``American attacks simply indicate a plan by both the United
States and Iraq to aggress against Iran to divert attention from
the heinous war crimes of Iraq, particularly the chemical
bombing,'' the letter said.
   President Reagan ordered the platforms attacked as retaliation
for a mine that damaged a U.S. warship last week and wounded 10
crew members.
   Okun's letter said: ``U.S. forces have exercised their inherent
right of self-defense under international law by taking defensive
action in response to an attack by the Islamic Republic of Iran
against a U.S. naval vessel in international waters. ... The
actions taken are necessary and proportionate to the threat posed
by such hostile Iranian actions.''
   It referred to Iranian mine-laying and said U.S. forces
``attacked military targets which have been used for attacks
against non-belligerent shipping in international waterways of the
gulf.'' The United States said the platforms were used as bases for
Iranian speedboats that attack neutral vessels.
   Mahallati rejected the claim of self-defense and called the
attacks on oil platforms ``nothing more than premeditated armed
reprisal.''
   He challenged the United States to produce evidence that the
mines were laid by Iran, and declared: ``There is no doubt that
Iraq and its agents have been mining the commercial lanes'' of the
gulf.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
