<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 2050EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-MemorialDay     04-19 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Memorial Day,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel Remembers Its War Dead; Shamir Warns Enemies</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Israel Bjt Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel remembered its more than 16,000 war dead
in Memorial Day ceremonies Tuesday and Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir told the nation's enemies: ``All those who hurt us will be
hurt manifold.''
   Sirens sounded throughout the country Tuesday night, bringing
activity to a standstill for one minute as Israelis remembered the
soldiers killed in wars with their Arab neighbors.
   President Chaim Herzog ignited a memorial torch at the Western
Wall, holiest site of Judaism, in a ceremony attended by relatives
of fallen soldiers.
   ``The whole nation is aware of the heavy loss, the loss of life,
the hopes that went up in the smoke of war,'' Herzog said. ``We
have to be aware that this is the price we pay for our freedom and
our independence.''
   Memorial Day ends Wednesday night with another torch-lighting
ceremony at Mount Herzl that starts the celebration of Israel's
40th Independence Day. Memorial Day always is the day before
Independence Day.
   Israeli authorities increased security for the two holidays,
fearing Palestinian attacks on Israeli targets in connection with
the 4-month-old Arab uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
   Soldiers erected roadblocks in the occupied territories Tuesday
night and officials said only Arabs with special permits would be
allowed into Israel until Independence Day celebrations end
Thursday night.
   Police Commissioner David Krauss said extra police were posted
throughout the country to prevent possible terror attacks and about
1,000 officers would patrol Jerusalem until the Moslem sabbath ends
Friday.
   ``There is information that terror organizations will try to
carry out attacks. ... We ask the public to be alert and call
police if they see a suspect object or irregular activity,'' Krauss
said on Israel radio.
   Shamir declared at a ceremony attended by hundreds of relatives
of soldiers killed in battle: ``Let's hope that our enemies will
realize and understand that Israel knows how to wage war, and that
all those who hurt us will be hurt manifold.
   ``There is no use and purpose in our enemies' repeated attempts
to destroy us. When our enemies realize this and accept the
existence of the state of Israel, we will know that we have won
life and peace because of our fallen soldiers.''
   Army officials said 16,415 Israeli soldiers have been killed
since independence in 1948, including 785 in the 1967 war, 2,679 in
the 1973 war and 1,183 in the 1982 invasion of Lebanon and
three-year occupation.
   Most of Israel's 3.5 million Jews have lost relatives in wars.
The 700,000 Arab citizens do not serve in the army.
   Sirens are to sound again at 11 a.m. Wednesday for the start of
memorial services at military cemeteries. Places of entertainment,
including movie theaters and restaurants, were ordered closed for
Memorial Day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
