<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghan-Supplies     04-19 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan-Supplies,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Arms and Other Supplies Flowing Into Kabul</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tons of Soviet supplies including
arms and ammunition are being flown into Kabul as Soviet troops
prepare to withdraw, Western diplomatic sources said Tuesday.
   The diplomats, speaking in Islamabad on condition of anonymity,
said their contacts in the Afghan capital reported nightly arrivals
of Soviet AN-12 and IL-76 transports at the Kabul airport the past
week.
   They said the mood in Kabul generally was calm in the wake of
the April 14 signing of an accord in Switzerland for the withdrawal
of the estimated 115,000 Soviet military personnel in Afghanistan.
   The sources reported East European diplomats were saying the
Soviet troops probably would first pull back from the eastern area
of Afghanistan when the withdrawal begins May 15. The Soviets sent
troops into Afghanistan in December 1979 to help the Marxist
government fight anti-communist rebels.
   Although the Soviets are to withdraw under the Geneva agreement,
the civil war is expected to continue. Rebel leaders said they
would fight on and America plans to continue providing aid to the
rebels while the Soviets support government forces.
   The Western diplomats said some of the new Soviet supplies are
beging moved south of Kabul in truck convoys, possibly for storage.
   There also have been reports of heavy fighting east and south of
the capital.
   The sources said that on April 11, a Soviet convoy with more
than 450 vehicles including tanks, mobile rocket launchers and
other armored equipment headed for Logar province, immediately
south of Kabul.
   Guerrilla activity has intensified this spring in provinces
bordering Pakistan, according to various reports.
   The rebels usually launch operations as the winter snow melts,
but guerrilla leaders vowed this year to step up the war because of
the Geneva accord that was framed without their participation.
   Prospects of a Soviet pullout have strengthened the Afghan
currency to 167 Afghanis to the dollar compared to 210 in February,
possibly in anticipation of a strong demand from returning
refugees, the sources said.
   They also said the price of Russian vodka on the local market
has doubled in recent weeks to the equivalent of $7.50 a bottle,
with Soviet personnel apparently stocking up before returning home.
</TEXT>
