<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 2200EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0766 04-19 0826</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0766,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede HERSHEY, Pa.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 12 grafs new with Bush comments on plane; pick up 2nd
graf pvs bgng ``Speaking to...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush said Tuesday he
expects to face the winner of the New York Democratic primary,
Michael Dukakis, in the fall general election.
   ``It's a good bet, I think,'' Bush told reporters traveling with
him on Air Force II.
   He also defended supporter Frank Rizzo, former Philadelphia
mayor, and denied that Rizzo could cost him the votes of blacks.
   ``I'm certainly not going to write off the ethnic community in
this country because of a prejudiced view'' toward Rizzo, he said.
He said he had no hesitation to appear with Rizzo.
   He noted that in his last unsuccessful campaign for mayor, Rizzo
had lost narowly.
   ``To have people suggest that I should not appear with him
because I'm worried that will hurt me in some other area ... I
reject it as invalid liberal trash.''
   ``It's reverse discrimination,'' Bush told reporters.
   On the New York primary, Bush said, ``I do think that whoever
wins (in New York) will win the Democratic nomination.''
   Bush said he did not intend to criticize Dukakis right away. ``I
think I'll keep it generic until the convention,'' he said.
   However, he referred to Dukakis as ``an old-world liberal
Democrat.''
   Earlier, with Rizzo at his side, Bush told a Republican rally in
Philadelphia: ``I want to take on whichever one of those Democrats
wins today in New York _ and whip them in the fall.''
   At stops earlier in the day, Bush reiterated strong support for
the American military strikes against Iran's forces.
   Speaking to the Pennsylvania State Association of Township
Supervisors, Bush said support for the U.S. military response ``has
crossed partisan lines,'' both in Congress and ``around the world.''
   ``I'm proud to have stood with the president and in support of
the president,'' Bush said.
   In an interview with local reporters, Bush said, ``One has to
keep one's options entirely open'' for possible future steps in the
Gulf.
   Bush was asked whether arms the Reagan administration secretly
sold to Iran in an effort to free hostages had been used against
the United States or its allies in recent days. Democratic
presidential contender Jesse Jackson has hinted that such arms were
used.
   ``I'm not sure they've used them against us,'' he said. However,
he added ``some of the weapons used in this exchange'' likely came
from ``an inventory of weapons ... from a time when we were
strongly in support of a much more moderate Iran than we have
today.''
   ``Back in the Shah's (of Iran) days, we had a very active
program,'' Bush said. ``There is a certain historical irony to it.''
   On the day of the New York primary, where he was running
virtually unopposed, Bush campaigned across Pennsylvania and said
he doesn't care which nominee Democrats choose.
   ``I can't wait for the fall, I can't wait for the debates with
the Democratic nominee, no matter who he turns out to be. Even if
they unleash Mario Cuomo, I can't wait,'' Bush told a morning
Republican fundraiser in Lancaster.
   The New York governer has said he would not accept a draft, even
in the event of a brokered Democratic convention.
   Bush got a special tour of the Hershey chocolate factory and ate
lunch in the plant cafeteria with workers. He was also presented
with a two-foot chocolate seal of the vice president's office.
``Eat your heart out,'' he joked with reporters.
   Bush had planned to return to Washington for a National Security
Council meeting on the Persian Gulf in early afternoon, but changed
his plans and stayed in Pennsylvania when the meeting was cancelled.
   He also had evening events planned in the Philadelphia area.
   ``Things have quieted down,'' said spokesman Peter Teeley.
   ``He feels he's fully informed on what going on'' and doesn't
need to remain in Washington, Teeley said.
   Bush also reiterated his plans for establishing an ethics office
in the White House if elected.
   ``I'm personally concerned with the breeches of ethics I've seen
over the past years,'' Bush said. ``When a congressman goes bad, or
a member of the executive branch betrays the trust, you know I know
it hurts,'' he told a GOP fundraiser in Lancaster.
   But, he told reporters later in Hershey, ``Please don't
interpret that as criticism of (Attorney General) Ed Meese.''
   ``Democrats are going to try to make some (political mileage on
the) `sleeze issue,''' Bush added. ``Let them try. There's plenty
on the other side.''
   Bush also told reporters he had not yet begun the process of
deciding upon a running mate, brushing aside questions on whether
former Pennsylvania Gov. Richard Thornburgh might be under
consideration.
   The former governor, now director of the Institute of Government
at Harvard University, accompanied Bush on his Pennsylvania swing.
   ``There's no list, long or short,'' Bush declared.
</TEXT>
