<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Cuomo-Primary     04-19 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuomo-Primary,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuomo Says Israel Issue Overshadowed More Important Primary Topics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH EDWARDSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo complained Tuesday
that scrapping over Mideast issues overshadowed equally important
matters during the state's Democratic primary race.
   ``We didn't hear about AIDS, we didn't hear about drugs,'' Cuomo
said. ``We didn't hear about homelessness. We didn't have a
discussion on INF (intermediate-range nuclear forces).''
   The governor said the primary, won by Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis, did not bring about a ``full ventilation of all the
issues.''
   ``If you could get a composite New York voter and read his or
her mind, they would say, `We're disappointed,''' he told reporters
at the state Capitol.
   The governor also said, however, that his state's primary was
not as divisive as some observers said it was.
   ``It is not accurate to say that this was an extremely negative
campaign. That is simply not accurate. It is not accurate to say
that there were obvious signs of severe racial tension,'' he said.
   ``Jesse (Jackson) and Mike (Dukakis) ... were quick to state
that aside from the mayor's comments there was no harsh criticism
from any political leaders,'' Cuomo said.
   ``I saw no fruit thrown. I heard no ugly epithets from crowds. I
saw no disorderly conduct. I saw no one unruly at debates. I saw no
one struck or even abused in any way,'' he said.
   The governor said the Middle East is a ``very important issue''
but one that seemed to have ``an eclipsing effect.''
   Mideast issues, of major concern to the state's large bloc of
Jewish voters, were magnified when New York City Mayor Edward I.
Koch endorsed Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr., in large part because
of Gore's pro-Israel stance.
   Koch said Jews would have to be ``crazy'' to vote for Jesse
Jackson because of his attitudes toward Israel and a Palestinian
state.
</TEXT>
