<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Cuba-O'Connor 1stLd-Writethru a0789 04-19 0674</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuba-O'Connor, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0789,0689</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New York Archbishop Lauds Catholic Spirit in Cuba</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 9th graf pvs, ``The cardinal ... with 1 graf to CORRECT
Del Valle was priest in Havana sted bishop in Santiago.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TINA SUSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAVANA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal John O'Connor of New York said Tuesday he
hoped his visit would advance political as well as church relations
between Cuba and the United States.
   He also said that years of religious restrictions in Cuba had
not hurt the spirit of its worshipers.
   The Roman Catholic prelate _ the first American cardinal to
visit Cuba since Fidel Castro came to power in 1959 _ hugged
Archbishop Jaime Ortega of Havana after stepping off the private
plane that brought him to Jose Marti Airport from Santiago, Cuba.
   He also shook hands with Jose Felipe Carneado, a member of the
Communist Party's Central Committee.
   O'Connor described his day in Santiago, 430 miles away, as
``wonderful,'' and spoke glowingly of the reception he received at
the Mass he celebrated there Monday night.
   ``The moment we arrived, they burst into thunderous applause,
and the applause hardly stopped throughout the entire Mass. They
applauded everything, and it was all spontaneous,'' he said.
   ``It was clear they were overjoyed by our visit and that the
faith is very, very deep.''
   O'Conner added, ``Despite the fact that there have been many
restrictions in the past on the free exercise of their faith, it's
there, it's still there.''
   The cardinal said much of the enthusiasm was due to the presence
of Monsignor Raul Del Valle of the New York archdiocese, who was a
priest in Havana before going to the United States in 1961.
   It was Del Valle's first visit to Cuba since he left.
   O'Connor was invited here by Cuban bishops to celebrate the
200th anniversary of the birth of Felix Varela, a Cuban priest who
served in New York City from 1823-53.
   ``It is my hope that Felix Varela will form a bridge _ a bridge
between the church in Cuba and the church in New York. And who
knows, when there is a strong bridge between the two churches, then
perhaps, many others can go back and forth across that bridge and
other kinds of peaceful reunion (may) take place between two
peoples who are separated by such a small body of water and who
together dream of peace,'' the New York archbishop said.
   O'Connor arrived in Cuba one day after the 27th anniversary of
the Castro government's victory at the Bay of Pigs over invading
anti-communist Cuban exile forces, who were backed by the United
States. When asked if it concerned him, he said ``Oh! Is that
right? I didn't even think of that.''
   He added, ``We'll pray for everybody who was involved and for
all who lost their lives.''
   It wasn't known if the cardinal would meet with Castro during
his three days in Havana. His schedule includes private meetings
with religous leaders.
   In 1985, a group of American archbishops met Castro during a
visit to Cuba.
   ``It would be very presumptuous of me to suggest I would be
seeing him,'' O'Connor said. But he added, ``anyone visiting any
country is always available when the president of the country
wishes to see him.''
   O'Connor said his visit and that of other religious leaders to
Cuba in recent years indicated ``significant movement'' by the
Cuban government in religious affairs, and he indicated he would be
taking careful notes to report to the Vatican.
   Pope John Paul II is scheduled to visit Latin America this year.
   ``I would be surprised if the Holy Father did not want to try to
visit Cuba sometime in the future,'' O'Connor said. ``I am unaware
of any concrete plans, but clearly the Holy See would observe
carefully the visit of any cardinal to any country to see how he
was received and what the response was on the part of the
government.''
   Of Cuba's 10.2 million people, an estimated 41 percent are Roman
Catholic.
</TEXT>
