<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 2242EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-ExitPolls 1stLd-Writethru a0808 04-19 0899</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Exit Polls, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0808,870</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Got NY Boost From Jewish Voters, White Catholics</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New throughout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Support from Jewish voters and a strong boost
from white Catholics lifted Michael Dukakis to victory in the New
York primary Tuesday, while Jesse Jackson's support came chiefly
from black voters, polls said.
   Racial division was a prominent feature of the race, with
Jackson winning a huge proportion of the black vote but just a
moderate share of white votes, polls said. Still, Jackson's white
vote was more than twice its 1984 level.
   Dukakis' three-quarter share of the Jewish vote countered
Jackson's black support, and Jackson led well but not
overwhelmingly among Hispanics, polls said. That left Catholic
whites as a swing vote, and many chose Dukakis.
   In incomplete returns, ABC News-Washington Post and NBC News
exit polls said Dukakis won about 70 percent of the white Catholic
vote, roughly 75 percent of the Jewish vote and 60 percent of the
smaller group of white Protestants. The numbers could change
slightly as final results came in.
   Jackson won about 95 percent of the black vote, which made up
about a quarter of the Democratic turnout, the ABC-Post, NBC and
CBS News-New York Times polls said. Jews and white Catholics each
made up about 25 percent of the total as well.
   ``The Jewish and black cancel each other out, then the ethnic
Catholic white vote is an important balance,'' said pollster I.A.
Lewis of the Los Angeles Times. ``It is going very strongly for
Dukakis.''
   Racial and religious antipathy marked the primary race _ Mayor
Edward I. Koch said Jews would ``have to be crazy'' to support
Jackson because of his position on Israel _ and polls indicated
that bad blood lingered.
   In early results from the Los Angeles Times exit poll, nearly
two-thirds of the Democratic voters said they believed there was
``an element of racism involved in the vote against Jackson,''
while about another third said they believed Jackson is
anti-Semitic.
   ``There's a very strong racial element here _ bitter racial
antagonism, I'd say,'' Lewis said.
   ABC News pollster Doug Muzzio called it ``a dual electorate'' in
which Dukakis won every demographic and socioeconomic group when
blacks were factored out.
   ``It's the same old song: Blacks voting overwhelmingly for
Jackson, whites less monolithic, but still, in this case, solidly
for Dukakis,'' he said.
   The NBC News poll said Jackson won just 18 percent of the
non-Jewish white vote; ABC had it at roughly one-fifth, which would
be about the same he got in the last two primaries, Wisconsin and
Connecticut. Among all whites, Jews included, the polls had Jackson
with about 15 percent.
   As expected, black turnout was highest in New York City,
accounting for 34 percent of the total in the NBC News poll.
   Muzzio noted ``an element of negative voting'' in the returns;
about a fifth of the voters said they were casting their ballots to
stop a candidate from winning rather than to help a candidate they
liked. Three-quarters of those negative voters went for Dukakis, he
said.
   There was some weakness in the support for Dukakis; NBC's poll
said more than half his supporters wished someone else were
running, and the CBS-Times poll said 72 percent of Dukakis' voters
said they would have voted for Gov. Mario Cuomo if he had been in
the race.
   Moreover, ``Only one in five blacks tells us that Dukakis really
cares about people like them, and only three in 10 blacks have a
favorable view of Dukakis,'' said NBC News poll chief Laurily
Epstein. ``So he's got his work cut out in that community.''
   Late pre-election polls gave Dukakis a lead of 9 points or more,
but pollsters stressed that turnout was the key _ chiefly, whether
non-Jewish whites would turn out and boost Dukakis or weaken him by
staying home.
   Fully one-third of the voters told NBC they had made their
decision in the last seven days of the race; 57 percent of them
went for Dukakis, 23 percent for Jackson and 19 percent for Gore.
   Most of Jackson's voters _ 70 percent _ made up their minds more
than a month ago, and 80 percent backed him strongly, NBC said. But
only half of his supporters said they thought the nation was ready
to elect a black president.
   NBC said liberal voters went for Jackson by a slim margin, 48
percent to 44 percent for Dukakis. Liberals made up 44 percent of
the total, the poll said. Moderates, a third of the total, favored
Dukakis over Jackson by 56-31; conservatives, 12 percent of the
total, split 56-23.
   Jackson did better with younger voters, the polls said, Dukakis
better with the older. Those most concerned with issues such as
drug abuse or helping the poor and elderly backed Jackson; those
concerned with the federal deficit and experience in office favored
Dukakis.
   Pre-election polls never showed much movement toward Sen. Albert
Gore Jr. of Tennessee; his peak was 12 percent in a CBS poll late
last week, after his endorsement by Koch. He did best among
conservative Democrats, the CBS-Times poll said, but was third even
there to Dukakis and Jackson.
   ``Gore just didn't play well here at all,'' said Pama Mitchell,
a CBS poll analyst.
   The polls had a margin of sampling error of about 4 percentage
points.
</TEXT>
