<2ND_LINE>AM-Gore, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0852,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tennessee Governor Says Gore Considering Dropping Out of
Presidential Race</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 12 grafs new with Gore comments; pick up 7th graf pvs
bgng ``I need to...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. said ``I guess this was
somebody else's Super Tuesday'' as New Yorkers turned thumbs down
on his candidacy and he considered quitting the Democratic
presidential race.
   Tennessee Gov. Ned McWherter, a close friend and adviser, said
the senator was weighing an end to his campaign after six weeks
without a primary or caucus win. Gore scheduled an announcement
Thursday.
   ``I told him he should gracefully get out and let this one
conclude,'' McWherter said from Nashville, Tenn.
   McWherter said, ``I've always been a person when reality rears
its head, recognize it, but do it gracefully and then go get a shoe
shine.''
   Gore spokesman Arlie Schardt told reporters here, ``I know the
senator hasn't made up his own mind. He has to talk to his advisers
and close friends.''
   But Gore dropped his attack stance of late and sounded a call
for unity as he spoke to supporters in New York, where he finished
a dismal third.
   ``I guess this was somebody else's Super Tuesday,'' he said. ``I
want to congratulate Mike Dukakis for a really impressive victory.
New York is a real marathon and he beat us by a mile. And I want to
congratulate Jesse Jackson for another tremendous showing. I never
wanted to stop Mike Dukakis or stop Jesse Jackson. I just wanted to
start Al Gore.
   ``Here in New York, and all across this country, in November,
the Democratic Party's going to be unified and we're going to stop
George Bush this November.''
   Gore called McWherter from New York where he was awaiting the
results of that state's presidential primary.
   ``He told me things were not good in New York. I told him to use
his own judgement,'' said McWherter, who coordinated Gore's
Southern campaign for Super Tuesday.
   McWherter declined to say whether Gore will drop out or not.
   ``Al Gore has worked hard for a year, and I don't think he needs
a big fat governor making the announcement for him,'' he said.
   ``I need to let him make that decision. I should not make any
suggestions of what he plans to do,'' McWherter said.
   In Ohio, Gore state director Rob Mulligan said national campaign
officials were reviewing the returns from New York before making a
decision.
   ``What I've been told is the campaign will see what it looks
like tonight and the senator will talk to his advisers to see what
direction the campaign will take,'' Mulligan said.
</TEXT>
