<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 2356EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Contras     04-19 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contras,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras Call Managua Visit `Triumph'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contra leaders Tuesday held out little hope that a
peace agreement with the Sandinistas could be reached within the
60-day timetable established March 23 but hailed the first round of
talks as a ``triumph.''
   The Contra directors returned from Managua on Monday night after
three days of peace negotiations with the Sandinista government.
The two sides did not reach an agreement but decided to meet again
for three days beginning April 28.
   ``What the Sandinista government wants is an absence of war
without eliminating the causes of war,'' said Adolfo Calero, one of
the five directors of the Nicaraguan Resistance, as the rebels are
formally called.
   He said the Contras will continue to insist on steps toward
democracy before they agree to lay down their arms.
   But he and directors Alfredo Cesar and Pedro Joaquin Chamorro
Jr. hailed the visit itself as a victory, pointing out the
Sandinistas originally refused to meet face to face.
   ``Our arrival in Managua after everything the Sandinistas said
was a triumph,'' said Calero.
   ``The resistance is creating a unique precedent in Latin
America,'' said Cesar. ``We are an intact guerrilla force
negotiating in the capital without giving up our troops or our
arms.''
   There are difficult problems to solve before the negotiations
can be completed, the Contra leaders said, saying the timetable
agreed to in Sapoa, Nicaragua, last month probably cannot be met
and will be extended.
   He dismissed questions about the Sandinistas' sincerity, saying
they had no choice but to negotiate because their political
position inside Nicaragua was weak.
   Calero noted that when the rebels toured the capital's streets
in a small bus, Nicaraguans cheered, saluted and flashed them ``V''
signs.
</TEXT>
