<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 0740EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APArts:India-Books Adv21   04-19 0780</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: India-Books, Adv 21,0801</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thurs PMs, April 21 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Books in 13 Indian Languages for 283 Million Readers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arvind Kumar should be the envy of most
book publishers.
   As director of India's National Book Trust, 44-year-old Kumar
heads an organization with a potential market of 283 million
Indians.
   But not too many would like to work Kumar's seven-day week as he
tries to juggle 13 Indian languages and keep ahead of critics who
say the trust publishes too few books in any one of them.
   The trust was set up in 1957 to produce and encourage the
production of good literature at moderate prices _ a sweeping
objective considering the size of the reading public and the
diversity of languages.
   India's 800 million people speak more than 1,600 dialects, and
15 languages are listed as official in the country's constitution.
The 13 in which the trust publishes rant state.
   Some of India's languages, little known outside the country, are
spoken by more people than some European tongues. Sixty million
people speak Marathi and 62 million Telegu, almost as many as the
63 million people who speak Italian in Italy and far more than the
11 million who speak Greek or the 9 million in Sweden who speak
that language.
   The trust's translations of Indian works include such books as
``Tin Malayalam Natak'' and the Punjabi version of ``Three
Malayalam Plays,'' set in the shady jungles of Kerala.
   The translation involves a change in script _ India's languages
also are written in 13 different scripts _ and sees the book
traveling 1,240 miles north to the dusty plains of Punjab where,
Kumar says, it is doing good business.
   Good business because the Punjabi translation adds 14 million
potential buyers to the 22 million Malayalam-speaking population. A
translation of a book from any other Indian language to Hindi, the
national language, adds 153 million people to the potential market.
   The trust has recently published a book of Punjabi folk tales in
Urdu, the Telugu novel ``What Was Left'' in Punjabi and the Hindi
novel ``Darkness'' in Urdu, Gujarati, Marathi and Tamil. The story
about India's partition became a popular TV series.
   The trust also publishes many books in English which, though not
an official Indian language, is spoken by most educated Indians.
These range from historical works such as a biography of Guru
Nanak, the first prophet of India's Sikh faith, to books about
India's rivers, its Hindu temples and its orchids.
   Despite its exotic output, the trust has received severe
criticism. A government committee complained the organization had
published only 3,101 books since 1957 and has spent most of its
funds on staff salaries. The trust receives a $3 million grant from
the government.
   ``There were heavy losses due to underpricing and incorrect
pricing of its publications,'' the government review said.
   Kumar agrees but only in part. He says more books should have
been published and he is planning a 70 percent increase in
production this year which would add 250 titles.
   ``But we are not a commercial enterprise,'' he says. ``There
will be losses because the books are underpriced as per government
orders.''
   The increase in production, Kumar says, is only a token effort
to tackle the problem: ``It's like a few drops of rain in a
desert.''
   Most of the additional titles will be in English and Hindi. But
efforts will be made to increase translations into other Indian
languages for what Kumar calls ``unifying the country through
literature.''
   Language has been a prickly subject in India. Riots have broken
out in south India over what people view as the forcible imposition
of Hindi, which is mainly spoken in the country's north.
   The trust steers clear of potential disputes by appointing
advisory boards for each language to decide which books to publish.
   The trust's other responsibilities include participating in the
government's plans to make 80 million more Indians literate by
1995. This means providing books for primary schools and adult
education centers in more than 500 cities and towns. Only 35
percent of India's people can now read and write.
   But Kumar says the trust by itself cannot fulfill the
government's literacy campaign.
   ``We can support it but we cannot hug it too hard,'' he says.
``We cannot succeed on our own. We have to float on a current and
that current will have to come from the people.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Thur April 21</NOTE>
</DOC>
