<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   04-19 1197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00,1248</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What happens when one of the biggest grossing
movies of the season hits the home video market? The happy studio
that owns it makes sure there are enough copies available for sale
and rental and launches a $1 million advertising campaign.
   As if ``Beverly Hills Cop II'' would need much promotion.
   The movie, starring Eddie Murphy in a reprise of his role as a
hip and irreverent Detroit cop let loose in ever so chic and snotty
Beverly Hills, has raked in more than $153 million for Paramount
Pictures since its release in May 1987.
   According to Eric Doctorow, senior vice president and general
manager of Paramount Home Video, distributors, retailers and mail
order firms had already ordered over 500,000 videocassettes of the
movie by March.
   Avid Murphy fans, ignoring the dousing the movie received last
year from critics, are already lined up at video stores for copies
of ``Beverly Hills Cop II,'' available on VHS for $89.95 and Beta
for $29.95.
   Another Paramount megahit, ``The Untouchables,'' the Brian De
Palma gangland action thriller that won an Academy Award for Sean
Connery, is available on videocassette on April 20.
   The movie has grossed more than $76 million since its release
last year and is priced at $89.95 for VHS and $29.95 for Beta.
   Elsewhere, Vestron Video has announced that it will release a
video version of Jonathan Miller's Broadway production of Eugene
O'Neill's ``Long Day's Journey Into Night.''
   Starring Jack Lemmon as the unbending family patriach James
Tyrone, Bethel Leslie, Peter Gallagher and Kevin Spacey, the VHS
video, priced at $59.98, will be available on June 22.
   Vestron will also release Hector Babenco's ``Ironweed'' in June.
Based on the Pulitzer Prize winning novel by William Kennedy, the
movie won Oscar nominations for co-stars Meryl Streep and Jack
Nicholson.
   Videos reviewed this week:
   
   ``Beverly Hills Cop II'' (VHS _ $89.95, Beta _ $29.95, Rated R)
   
   Eddie Murphy is back as Axel Foley, tooling around undercover in
a red Ferrari as Detroit's answer to Sonny Crockett until the
shooting of his buddy Police Capt. Andrew Bogomil carries him back
to Beverly Hills.
   There he teams up with Rosewood (Judge Reinhold) and Taggart
(John Ashton) to chase down a pack of gun smugglers, triggering a
non-stop round of shootouts, broken glass, squad car smash-ups and
exploding trucks.
   Anyone who has the sneaking feeling they've seen all this before
is right. Director Tony Scott (``Top Gun'') took the formula that
proved so successful the first time around and slapped it on film
again, chocking up 1987's biggest box-office winner in the process.
   Unfortunately, this version has more of everything except the
thing it needs most: Eddie Murphy being funny.
   The writers toss in some scraps of character development,
telling us that Bogomil has a daughter, Taggart has a divorce-happy
wife and Rosewood has a gun fetish. This go-round also has Rambo's
former squeeze, Brigitte Nielsen _ nostrils flared _ destroying
massive amounts of property without so much as smudging her makeup.
And it includes a gratuitous stop at the Playboy mansion where Hef
himself gets to say a few words, such as they are.
   There's an R-rating and lots of profanity. There's more noise
but less really graphic violence than the original; adolescent boys
probably would like it a lot.
   Diehard Murphy fans will want to catch his occasional funny
moments. For others, the laughs might prove too few and far between
to make this worth tolerating.
   _ By Lisa Levitt Ryckman, Associated Press Writer
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Less Than Zero'' (CBS@Fox, VHS@Beta stereo, and available
closed captioned for the hearing impaired, $89.98, Rated R)
   
   Naming this movie ``Less Than Zero'' was a forfeit to critics:
Who among them could resist giving this dumb, sentimental Hollywood
version of Bret Easton Ellis' novel less than zero? The release of
the video provides another chance to give it one last kick in the
rump.
   The movie stars Andrew McCarthy, an attractive young guy whose
acting skills are unfortunately limited to a) smirking and b)
gawking. He plays Clay Easton, a reasonably grounded college
student who has come home for the holidays to find that his budding
bimbo girlfriend (Jami Gertz) has been consorting with an old
school chum (Robert Downey Jr.), who is busy flushing himself down
the tubes because of drugs.
   Ellis' book of the same title _ it has little else in common
with the movie _ was a declaration of insignificance, a scary
ramble through the lives of visionless, overprivileged, untended
youth. The book's pointlessness was its point. The movie is
immediately hobbled by a contrived good vs. evil plot. Even the
soundtrack is vapid with such tunes as the Bangles' remake of
``Hazy Shade of Winter.''
   Marek Kanievkska (``Another Country'') directed. The best thing
about the movie _ except for unintentional laughs _ is the
attractive photography of the high-style, minimalist Southern
California architecture. Unfortunately, nobody is home.
   _ By Kathryn Baker, AP Television Writer
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``The Pick-Up Artist'' (CBS@Fox Video, VHS@Beta, $89.98, Rated
PG-13)
   
   Meet Jack Jericho, a horny grade-school teacher who hits on
anything that moves and has more lines than Disneyland.
   Jack, played by Robert Downey Jr., was undoubtedly intended to
be a funny, endearing hero. Somehow, though, even Jack's kindness
to kids and his diabetic granny fail to save him from coming across
as a sleazy little jerk, a sort of human pimple on the face of
Manhattan womankind _ hard to get rid of and bound to pop up
somewhere else.
   That's what Randy Jensen discovers after she boggles Jack's mind
by giving him her body within moments of their first meeting but
refusing to give him her phone number. Is this woman hip and
liberated, or just cruising for a disease?
   Molly Ringwald's Randy is either sullen or whiny and sometimes
both, the perfect foil for the vacuous Jack, who spends the rest of
the movie mooning after her and scheming to help rustle up the
money her alcoholic father owes a drug-dealing thug.
   Dennis Hopper, as Randy's father, and Harvey Keitel, as the
thug, provide the only real mystery in this utterly predictable 81
minutes: How did these two excellent character actors get mixed up
in this insipid piece of celluloid?
   Little acting, even less action and lines such as, ``You know
what this cheeseburger is like? Life!'' make writer-director James
Toback's movie too moronic for adults and for those teen-agers
whose IQs are greater than their shoe size.
   _ By Lisa Levitt Ryckman, Associated Press Writer
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
