<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--TalkingHeads Adv29-01   04-19 1071</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Talking Heads, Adv 29-01,1125</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv29-01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, April 29 to May 1 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: More Talking Heads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Byrne was in a hotel bathtub in
Minneapolis when he wrote lyrics for ``No More Flowers'' for the
Talking Heads.
   This is just one bare fact the group revealed when talking about
themselves in an interview to promote their latest LP, ``Naked.''
   Byrne, the group's lead singer and lyricist, was in Minneapolis
to visit his wife, costume designer Adele Lutz, who was doing a
play there.
   ``I would work with this microcassette recorder,'' he said. ``I
would have it sitting just outside the tub. I would reach out and
speak into it. I'd be singing in the tub. I'd catch a phrase that I
thought was apropos; I'd put it on the little recorder.''
   The album is on their new label, Fly Records. It jumped onto
Cashbox magazine's best-selling album chart at No. 20 on April 2.
   ``This record actually goes back to our earliest songs and
albums `Remain in Light' (1980) and `Speaking in Tongues' (1983),
where we would each contribute ideas,'' said drummer Chris Frantz.
   ``We rented a rehearsal studio in New York and each threw out
ideas. We had a little cassette recorder and had all our
instruments there. We'd take an idea, play it and play it, trading
instruments, until it fell apart. Then we'd strike up a new idea.
We ended up after 10 days with many snippets of songs.
   ``We went to Paris into a recording studio and commenced to put
them all together into song form.''
   They went to Paris for several reasons. They laid down tracks
with Paris-based Third-World musicians who play Caribbean Zuok and
Algerian-Moroccan rai. Frantz said they also wanted to hang out
together, which they're more apt to do in Paris than in New York
where they have different sets of friends.
   ``My feeling is that lately there has been less openness here,''
said Byrne, the group's lead singer and lyricist. ``I wanted to get
away from that feeling. There is that kind of vibe here that
whatever is Top 10 in the United States is all there is. There is a
lot going on in other places.''
   Byrne, Frantz and Tina Weymouth met at the Rhode Island School
of Design, and still design their striking album packages. They
added Jerry Harrison to the trio and put out their first album in
1977.
   Wally Badarou, who played keyboards on ``Speaking in Tongues,''
found the Paris studio and brought in other musicians.
   ``One guitarist had a big smile the entire time he was playing
with us,'' Weymouth said. ``When you're putting down music with
that kind of heartfelt feeling, you know it's coming across in the
record.''
   Harrison said the album has two moods. ``This organic, larger
band is primarily on the first side of the album,'' he said. What
Weymouth terms ``the more experimental or ominous'' songs are on
Side 2.
   After 15 basic tracks were recorded, Byrne improvised melodies
and then wrote the words.
   ``I heard a story about a French screenwriter who, when it was
time to write a script, would rent a hotel room at the Rafael and
lock himself in the bathroom,'' Byrne said. ``His secretary would
deliver food. He didn't allow himself to go out of there until it
was all done. He could barely afford to stay there. He had to work
every day.
   ``I tried lyrics for all 15. On some the words and melodies
weren't quite right. It was nice that we had enough. There was one
about marijuana _ it's a great song. Too bad. It was lagging behind
in the race for the record so it didn't make it.''
   Byrne, who is British, married the American Lutz last July in
Paris. Harrison has a son who is 1 years old, and Weymouth and
Frantz, who are married, have two sons, who are 5 and 2.
   Since they all have individual commitments to pursue the next
Talking Heads project probably will be another album instead of a
tour.
   ``I put together `Storytelling Giant,' a compilation of all the
band videos, and shot some extra material to go between them, to
kind of link them.
   ``I hope to direct another movie, with Robert Wilson, in the
summer in Europe. That's still in the planning stage. We did
something a couple of years ago, `The Knee Plays.' I think that's
going into a theater in Chicago.''
   Byrne's last film was ``True Stories,'' a musical romp about an
``average'' Texas town.
   Byrne also composed music for some scenes in Bernardo
Bertolucci's ``The Last Emperor,'' which won nine Acaemy Awards.
   Harrison, who produced the BoDeans' ``Inside Looking Out,'' is
putting together a band to tour behind the album he just released
on Sire Records, `Casual Gods.'
   ``I did `Casual Gods' in Wisconsin in a basement studio,'' he
said. ``My mother was ill and my father had passed away. I went
back to Milwaukee to take care of her whenever I could be there. I
found a basement studio I could rent by the week rather than by the
hour, owned by the younger brother of someone I had grown up with.
   ``Musicians would pass through town or I used local musicians. I
was paying for it myself. When I was offered a production job I
would always do it. That caused my record to extend over the years.
I think it made it much better. The songs are more diverse and I
think my singing got better.''
   Weymouth said she and Frantz just finished ``Conscious Party''
by Ziggy Marley and the Melody Makers. It is their only production
outside of the Tom Tom Club.
   ``We are going into the studio to finish up our third Tom Tom
Club record,'' Frantz said. ``After it's released in June, I think
we'll tour in Europe. We're in demand in Europe.
   ``Ziggy Marley, who's 19, writes all the material. His brother
Steve, 15, sings one song. Cedella is 20. Rita and Sharon, who's a
mother of two, sing backgrounds.'' The Melody Makers, formed by the
late reggae king Bob Marley, have been around since Ziggy was 8.
   ``It's hard for me to imagine doing all this when I was 19,''
remarked Byrne.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, April 29-May 1</NOTE>
