<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0554</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James E. Olson, whose bulldog tenacity led him
from manholes in North Dakota to the chairmanship of AT&T, has died
unexpectedly after a month-long battle with colon cancer. He was 62.
   Olson's death on Monday came after just 1{ years as leader of
American Telephone & Telegraph Co.
   Robert E. Allen, 53, AT&T's president and chief operating
officer, will serve as acting chairman and is considered the
favorite to succeed Olson.
   The century-old AT&T has enough management depth that the loss
of Olson is not expected to damage the company.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving Bank Corp. has agreed to sell a majority
stake of the company to Banca Commerciale Italiana, Italy's
second-largest bank, for $617 million as an alternative to Bank of
New York Co.'s hostile bid.
   Irving also announced a complex restructuring plan Monday that
includes the sale of its 50-story Wall Street headquarters and a
cost-cutting program.
   The company put the total value of the $65 a share cash offer
and restructuring at between $1.1 billion to $1.2 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennzoil Co. says it will acquired Facet
Enterprises Inc. for $250 million, but says the purchase of the
oilfield equipment company has nothing to do with the $3 billion it
recently received to settle its four-year legal battle with Texaco
Inc.
   Under the buyout, which was approved by Facet's board of
directors, Pennzoil will begin a cash tender offer of $32 per share
as soon as practicable, Pennzoil spokesman Robert Harper said
Monday.
   Tulsa, Okla.-based Facet had been fighting a $27.50 a share
hostile takeover bid Prospect Group Inc., which was extended
through Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armtek Corp. has agreed to sell its
Armstrong Tire Co. for $190 million in cash to Italy's Pirelli
Group, one of Europe's largest tiremakers.
   Pirelli had sought last year to acquire 80 percent of Armstrong
Tire, but the talks ended after the two companies could not agree
on the value of the proposed buyout, Armtek stated Monday.
   This time, they signed a binding agreement for the sale of 100
percent of Armstrong Tire, Armtek and Pirelli announced.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A presidential commission has concluded the
U.S. air transport system is safe, but is urging appointment of a
``safety czar'' in a newly independent Federal Aviation
Administration that would be insulated from political pressures.
   ``The nation's air transportation system is safe, for now,''
said John M. Albertine, chairman of the Aviation Safety Commission
whose final report was issued Monday after a nine-month study of
the rapidly growing airline industry.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court has rejected appeals by natural gas pipeline
companies to invalidate a key federal regulation aimed at promoting
competition in their industry, a ruling that affects billions of
dollars in sales.
   In other business-related matters, the court affirmed Monday
that workers may not be fired for refusing on religious grounds to
pay union dues. It also rejected the use in cosmetics of color
additives that could cause cancer, and it agreed to decide whether
donations to the Church of Scientology are tax-deductible.
</TEXT>
