<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The operating rate of American industry fell
for a second month in March despite a rebound at auto plants, the
government says.
   The Federal Reserve said Monday that U.S. factories, mines and
utilities operated at 82.3 percent of capacity last month, down
from an operating rate of 82.4 percent in February.
   U.S. factories had operated at 82.6 percent of capacity in
January, the highest level in more than eight years. In spite of
the declines, analysts said the economy still shows plenty of
strength.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. plans to eliminate bonuses for top
executives in years when it earns too little to share profits with
workers, the automaker's chief negotiator says.
   Anthony St. John, a Chrysler vice president, revealed the plan
Monday after opening early national contract talks with the United
Auto Workers.
   St. John said the No. 3 automaker agrees with the union's stand
that it isn't fair for workers to receive no profit-sharing in
years when executives get fat bonuses or stock grants.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Koppers Co. says it spent at least $3.5
million in the first quarter resisting a hostile takeover bid by
Beazer PLC, helping generate a quarterly loss of $8.5 million.
   Meanwhile, the Beazer group on Monday extended its stalled, $1.7
billion tender offer until midnight EDT Friday. Also, Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. defended its controversial role in backing the
takeover.
   The extension of the offer was expected since Friday, when a
federal judge in Pittsburgh blocked the tender offer indefinitely
over apparent violations of securities laws.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co., beset by sluggish retail
sales and sharp declines in income from three of its four major
divisions, says its first-quarter profit fell more that 37 percent
from the same period a year ago.
   But sales were up 16 percent and industry analysts agreed Monday
with Sears Chairman Edward A. Brennan that the rest of the year
should be better.
   The nation's largest retailer reported net income of $179.5
million, or 47 cents a share, for the first three months of 1988,
down from $287.9 million, or 75 cents a share, for the year-earlier
period.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan again has asked the United States to lift
trade sanctions imposed last year by President Reagan following
American complaints over semiconductor sales.
   Japan said Monday it had complied with requests to open its
markets to U.S.-made computer chips and that continued sanctions
only would irritate Japanese manufacturers.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The British pound advanced again Monday, hitting a six-year high
of more than $1.90 as an outbreak of fighting in the Persian Gulf
heightened the importance of the North Sea oil fields.
   Stocks weakened over fears of inflation and Gulf shootouts as
the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slumped 5.81 points to
2,008.12.
   Gold prices rose and crude oil futures advanced.
   Bond prices fell in the credit markets.
</TEXT>
