<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 0237EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BankBid Bjt   04-19 0733</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Bid, Bjt,0756</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irving Accepts `White Knight' Cash Tender Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ``white knight'' that Irving Bank Corp.
sought for help in its bitter battle against hostile suitor Bank of
New York Co. turned out to be Italy's second-largest bank.
   Irving said Monday that state-run Banca Commerciale Italiana has
agreed to acquire a 51 percent stake in Irving for $65 a share in
cash, or $617.5 million, countering Bank of New York's overtures.
   Irving also announced a complex restructuring plan that includes
the sale of its 50-story Wall Street headquarters, a cost-cutting
program and a boost in its annual stock dividends.
   The company put the total value of the cash offer and
restructuring at between $1.1 billion to $1.2 billion.
   Irving spokesman D. Emerson Phelps said the deal would allow
Irving management to retain control of the company, although the
board of directors would be expanded to include four Banca
Commerciale representatives.
   In addition to the Banca Commerciale tender offer, which begins
today, Irving shareholders will get a special dividend of $10 a
share upon completion of the deal, Irving said.
   The company said stockholders could receive cash for about half
of their shares, and retain the other half.
   ``Our shareholders will benefit far more from the affiliation
with BCI than the proposal advanced from BNY (Bank of New York),''
Irving Chairman Joseph A. Rice stated. ``Irving anticipates
increases in its revenues as a result of its ongoing relationship
with BCI.''
   Irving's announcement comes just days after Bank of New York
shareholders voted to support management's $1 billion-plus hostile
offer for Irving. Bank of New York last month began a tender offer
of $15 in cash and 1.575 of its common shares for each of Irving's
roughly 18.1 common shares outstanding.
   Bank of New York, which holds a 4.9 percent stake in Irving,
also is running a slate of 16 nominees to Irving's board of
directors. Irving's annual meeting is scheduled for Thursday,
although most business will be conducted at a reconvened meeting on
Saturday to give shareholders time to digest the BCI offer, Irving
said.
   Irving over the past seven months repeatedly has spurned Bank of
New York's takeover proposals, maintaining it wanted to remain
independent but recently disclosing it was seeking a ``white
knight'' friendly merger partner as an alternative.
   Bank of New York spokesman Owen Brady said his company would to
study the Banca Commerciale offer, but it felt its own bid was
superior.
   Brady also said the foreign offer for Irving could run into
problems gaining regulatory approval from the state of New York and
the Federal Reserve, contending Banca Commerciale might have
problems meeting capital adequacy requirements.
   Michael Starr, a banking analyst with Duff & Phelps Inc. in
Chicago, said Bank of New York could sweeten its current offer, but
it would have to resubmit to the lengthy regulatory process that
includes hearings before the Federal Reserve and New York State
Banking boards.
   Analysts said they weren't surprised Irving sought help from a
foreign bank, because many large U.S. banks lack the capital for
big acquisitions. But some experts said they found the complexity
of the deal may have accounted for the relatively lackluster
activity in Irving stock.
   Irving shares rose slightly on the New York Stock Exchange on
Monday before declining to close $1 lower at $60.37{. Bank of New
York shares gained $1 to $31.65{.
   As part of its restructuring Irving said it would enact a hiring
freeze as part of an intensive cost saving program. The program
could raise net income to about $1.60 a share in 1988 and $2.75
next year.
   In addition, the company said said it immediately would increase
its annual common dividend from $2.42 a share to $4.50.
   To pay for the special $10-a-share dividend, Irving said it
planned to sell its Wall Street headquarters and its 39 percent
equity interest in Banca della Svizzera Italiana for more than the
current market price of about $325 million.
   Banca Commerciale, based in Milan, has assets of about $60
billion and is Italy's second largest bank, behind Banca Nazionale
del Lavoro. About 64 percent of Banca Commerciale is owned by the
giant state holding company Istituto per la Ricostruzione
Industriale. Irving's assets total $24.12 billion.
   Irving lost $193.27 million last year, after raising its
loan-loss reserves to cover troubled Third World debt.
</TEXT>
