<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 0238EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BankBid-Chronology     04-19 0710</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Bid-Chronology,0736</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Bank Bid Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here's a chronological look at Bank of New York Co.'s hostile
takeover attempt of Irving Bank Corp.:
   _Sept. 25, 1987. Bank of New York makes an unsolicited $1.4
billion cash-stock bid for Irving Bank.
   _Oct. 9. Irving's board of directors rejects the $1.4 billion
bid, activates the company's sharholders' rights, ``poison pill''
defense.
   _Oct. 21. The Federal Reserve asks the Bank of New York to
provide further details on its takeover offer, saying the
application was ``seriously deficit'' in key information.
   _Nov. 9. Irving Chairman Joseph A. Rice asks Bank of New York to
withdraw its $1.4 billion bid, which it called ``disruptive,
illusionary and unreal.''
   _Nov. 20. Bank of New York lowers its offer to $1.2 billion,
citing depressed share prices and changing economic conditions
following the Oct. 19 stock market crash.
   _Dec. 15. Irving's board rejects Bank of New York's revised
offer.
   _Jan. 25, 1988. Bank of New York lowers its bid to $1.08
billion, saying it reflects several factors, including Irving's
decision to add another $225 million to its fourth-quarter
loan-loss reserve to cover shaky Third World debt.
   _Feb. 1. Irving sues the New York State Banking Board, alleging
it withheld ``substantial information'' about the Bank of New York
merger application and misled Irving on how soon the board might
consider the application.
   _Feb. 3. A New York State Supreme Court judge orders the New
York State Banking Department to give 10-day written notice before
acting on Bank of New York's application.
   _Feb. 5. Bank of New York sues to have Irving's proposed
convertible preferred stock issuance declared illegal, saying it
dilutes the rights of outstanding common shares.
   _Feb. 16. Irving's board rejects Bank of New York's $1.08
billion offer.
   _Feb. 23. Irving announces it placed $100.1 million of
cumulative convertible preferred stock with 15 private investors.
Each share guarantees voting rights beyond those of common
shareholders.
   _Feb. 25. Bank of New York's takeover proposal receives approval
from the Fed and New York State Banking Board, with both groups
contending a merger wouldn't hurt competition.
   _March 4. Irving files notice of an appeal in U.S. District
Court in Washington, D.C., saying it would ask the court to review
the Federal Reserve's decision approving the merger.
   _March 15. Irving amends its ``poison pill,'' under which
shareholders' rights would go into effect only with the present
board in existence or unless the new board was elected by at least
two-thirds of the outstanding common shares.
   _March 18. Bank of New York receives SEC permission of its
registration statement, giving it the go-ahead to proceed with its
tender offer.
   _March 25. Irving says in a Securities and Exchange Commission
filing that it is seeking a ``white knight'' friendly bidder and
other alternatives to Bank of New York's offer.
   _March 28. Irving announces its board approved another amendment
to its poison pill, activating shareholders' rights after 5 percent
of the company's outstanding shares are acquired. Bank of New York
begins solicits proxy votes in an effort to gain control of
Irving's board.
   _March 31. Bank of New York amends its complaint of Irving's
poison pill.
   _April 4. Irving releases a letter to shareholders predicting a
1988 profit of more than $200 million, in an effort to paint Bank
of New York's offer as inadequate. Irving also announces it filed
suit in New York state court to block Bank of New York's proxy
solicitation.
   _April 7. Irving files an amendment to an SEC filing to include
an affadavit from a Goldman Sachs & Co. official saying Irving was
negotiating with third parties, including a possible ``white
knight,'' contrary to accustions from Bank of New York. The filing,
though, does not name any parties.
   _April 14. Bank of New York holds its annual shareholders'
meeting. The company says preliminary voting shows it has won
permission to issue as many additional common shares and
convertible securities as needed to merge with Irving.
   _April 18. Irving says its board accepted a $65-a-share cash
tender offer from Banca Commerciale Italiana for 51 percent of its
common shares.It also announces a complex restructuring.Meanwhile,
the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Washington, D.C, upholds the
Fed's approval of the Bank of New York bid for Irving.
</TEXT>
