<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EnhancedRecovery     04-19 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Enhanced Recovery,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Enhanced Oil Recovery Projects Down 28 Percent in Two
Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of enhanced oil recovery projects
operating in the United States fell by 28 percent over the past two
years due to the sliding price of crude oil, according to an
industry magazine.
   The projects, which are aimed at boosting oil recovery from
known reservoirs, suffered from crude prices that were too low to
provide incentives for expansion and from a lack of capital to
invest in new projects, the Oil and Gas Journal reported in its
Monday issue.
   The Journal's report came as about 1,000 industry
representatives attended a three-day symposium on enhanced oil
recovery methods beginning here on Monday.
   Oil prices, which remain in the $18-a-barrel range, are forcing
larger American producers away from high-cost enhanced oil recovery
methods and into areas with quicker payoffs, said Lowell R. Smith,
chairman of the Tulsa symposium and head of research for Amoco
Production Company's Tulsa facility.
   A Journal survey indicated 366 active EOR projects in the United
States, compared with 512 projects at the same time two years ago.
Over the same period, production from enhanced recovery operations
increased slightly to 637,000 barrels of oil a day.
   Enhanced oil recovery techniques include the the injection of
steam, gases or liquids into oil-producing formations. Thermal
recovery methods, mostly steam injection, account for about 73
percent of the additional production resulting from EOR operations,
the Journal said.
   Some $960 million will be spent on enhanced recovery projects
planned for 1988 and 1989 in the United States and elsewhere, based
on investment information for 76 projects during that period, the
magazine stated.
</TEXT>
