<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Koppers     04-19 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koppers,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shearson Defends Koppers Takeover Role</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. continues
defending its controversial role in the hostile $1.7 billion
takeover bid being waged for Koppers Co., while Koppers says its
first quarter net loss stemmed partly from expenses in defending
against the bid.
   The group led by Shearson and Britain's Beazer PLC on Monday
extended its stalled $60 a share tender offer through midnight EDT
Friday.
   The one-week extension had been expected following a federal
judge's ruling last Friday that indefinitely blocked the bid
because of apparent securities law violations.
   Koppers stock fell 37{ cents to $53.25 a share in New York Stock
Exchange trading on Monday.
   U.S. District Judge Maurice B. Cohill Jr., who issued the
injunction blocking the tender offer, has said the takeover was the
first known instance of an investment bank being the outright owner
of a takeover vehicle.
   He also has called Shearson a ``major equity participant'' in
the deal and said that although the firm had only limited voting
rights in the company created to acquire Koppers it was one of the
entities on whose behalf the hostile bid was made.
   Peter A. Cohen, chairman of Shearson Lehman Brothers Holdings
Inc., parent of the investment bank, told reporters on Monday that
the firm's role in the takeover attempt was not unusual or out of
line.
   BNS Inc., the company formed by Shearson, British industrialist
Brian C. Beazer and National Westminster Bank to acquire Koppers.
   Shearson paid $23 million for a 46 percent interest in BNS,
which compares with the 49 percent interest worth $24.5 million
held by Beazer, chairman of the British construction and building
materials company bearing his name.
   Cohen and other Shearson executives said the firm doesn't hold
real equity because it can force Beazer to buy its share within
five years and Beazer can force Shearson to sell through a ``call.''
   Cohen said equity ``is something that's got a continuous life,
and ours doesn't.''
   For several years takeover lenders have been accepting warrants,
or the right to purchase stock at a specified price, ``and
warrants...the last time I looked (were) characterized as an equity
security,'' Cohen said.
   Shearson probably will make less than $30 million on its equity
in BNS, he said, declining to say what Shearson stands to make in
fees.
   Separately, Koppers said it spent at least $3.5 million in the
first quarter to resist the hostile bid, helping generate a
quarterly net loss of $8.5 million. The company posted a $3 million
net loss in first quarter 1987.
   At least half of the additional $7 million Koppers incurred in
first-quarter overhead was in fees for attorneys, financial
advisers and other defense costs, said company spokesman Robert J.
O'Gara.
   O'Gara said he could not quantify the defense expenses beyond
saying they were a majority of the $7 million. The tender offer was
launched March 3, two-thirds of the way through the quarter.
   Koppers said its first-quarter sales climbed 13 percent from
$271.7 million to $306.7 million.
   The company's construction materials and services businesses had
operating losses totaling $2.3 million, compared to losses of $4.1
million a year earlier. Operating earnings in chemicals and related
products climbed to $8.6 million from $6.4 million.

</TEXT>
