<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 1142EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-FirstCity     04-19 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-First City,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First City: Tender Offer Successful</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH RENDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials of First City Bancorporation of Texas
announced today that the company's tender offer for debt holders to
submit their securities was successful, paving the way for a $1.6
billion federal bailout plan.
   Last month, the company _ which officially becomes the First
City Acquisition Corp. under the plan _ lowered the required
participation level from 90 percent to 70 percent.
   In making today's announcement, however, company officials
declined to confirm that senior and subordinated debt holders had
surrendered 70 percent of the bank holding company's debt.
   First City officials announced last week they planned to
complete the deal by today. A Monday afternoon deadline, the
company's sixth, passed without word from First City on whether the
company had completed the last obstacle to finish the
reorganization plan.
   As of last week, 66.1 percent, or $149.3 million, of the bank's
$225.8 million in bonds had been tendered. First City needs at
least $158 million of the outstanding debt tendered to complete the
deal.
   Chicago investor A. Robert Abboud's effort to rescue
Houston-based First City with the help of $970 million from the
Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. has been slowed by bondholders'
reluctance to part with the debt.
   First City senior debt holders have been offered 45 cents on the
dollar for their debt, while subordinated debt holders have been
offered 35 cents.
   Bonds not tendered by the deadline become the obligation of the
revitalized First City and would be worth more than what Abboud is
offering.
   The bailout plan, announced in September, calls for $970 million
in assistance from the FDIC, a spinoff of $1.79 billion in book
value of poorly performing assets and $500 million infusion of
capital raised privately by a group headed by Abboud.
   Also on Monday, CNN Business News reported that Abboud has
agreed to put up more than $500 million in private money through
new stock underwritten by Donaldson Lufkin & Jenrette Securities
Corp. The report said Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. has pledged $100
million _ under certain conditions _ as part of that sum.
   A First City spokesman said he was not aware of Drexel Burnham
Lambert's involvment with Abboud. Calls to the New York investment
company from The Associated Press were not returned.
   First City, with 59 banks in Texas and one in South Dakota, grew
quickly during the Texas oil boom, but was hit by energy and real
estate losses when oil prices plummeted.
   For 1987, the state's fourth-largest bank holding company posted
a $1.1 billion loss.
   In a 10K report filed late last month with the Securities and
Exchange Commission, First City reported it expected to lose $43
million by the time the reorganization is completed.
   If the First City doesn't redeem enough bonds, the FDIC says it
will resort to an alternative that will hurt bondholders more than
Abboud's proposal.
   The FDIC won't say what the alternatives are, but analysts
suspect the agency would declare First City insolvent, seize it
under its emergency powers and then turn it over to Abboud. If that
happens, bondholders would get wiped out.
   Another alternative would be to declare First City bankrupt and
negotiate with bondholders in court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
