<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Narrowly Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened narrowly
mixed today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Soybean futures showed no clear trend either higher or lower.
Higher soybean oil prices provided some impetus on the positive
side, but lower values for soybean meal exerted downward pressure.
   Soybean traders have been keeping a close watch on the Brazilian
soybean harvest, which was reportedly about 55 percent complete as
of last Friday, said Dale Gustafson, an analyst with Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc. in Chicago.
   ``That's compared to 45 percent last year and a normal of 50
percent, so it's proceeding about on average,'' he said.
   Corn and wheat prices were nearly unchanged in early trading.
Some observers had expected wheat prices to fall in reaction to
sluggish export sales and the government's auction sale last Friday
of 11.2 million bushels of surplus wheat.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to } cent higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.11{ a bushel; corn was unchanged
to \ cent higher with May at $2.03} a bushel; oats were 1 cent to
1\ cents higher with May at $1.65} a bushel; soybeans were } cent
lower to { cent higher with May at $6.65} a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .05 cent to .60 cent higher with April at 74.50
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .23 cent to .50 cent higher with
April at 79.30 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent lower to .40 cent
higher with April at 44.75 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.20 cent to .50 cent higher with May at 52.15 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures closed mostly lower on Monday.
</TEXT>
