<1ST_LINE>u f PM-OilPrices 1stLd-Writethru   04-19 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices, 1st Ld-Writethru,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Futures Prices Fade After Runup On Persian Gulf Fighting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with morning activity; uppicks
6th graf pvs: U.S. Navy...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices dropped sharply today, as
profit-taking continued in the wake of the runup that erupted on
Monday's explosion of U.S.-Iran fighting in the Persian Gulf.
   In midday trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange, West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, stood at $18.12 per
42-gallon barrel, down 15 cents from Monday's closing price.
   May contracts for wholesale unleaded gasoline were trading at
52.40 cents per gallon, down 0.90 cent, while wholesale heating oil
contracts were down 0.85 cent at 49.65 cents per gallon.
   Analysts said selling hit the market from the start, continuing
a trend that began early Monday afternoon.
   Anticipating that diminished Middle East oil supplies might send
prices higher, many traders rushed to buy Monday despite widespread
realization that any shortfall could easily be diminished by other
world producers, analysts said.
   As a result, when the initial excitement died down, prices
slipped back because of profit-taking and technical factors, they
said.
   U.S. Navy vessels destroyed two offshore Iranian oil platforms,
sank a defending Iranian patrol boat and bombed two Iranian navy
frigates in retaliation for a mine attack that nearly sank a U.S.
vessel. Iran attacked oil facilities off Sharjah and fired on at
least two U.S. vessels.
   Jayne Ball, an analyst at the Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
investment firm, said prices soared on those reports, even though
``there's an overall recognition that if you shut down the Gulf,
there's not so big an impact'' on world oil supplies, because of
the number of other producers has grown.
   But the markets still worry to the point that ``anything that
happens in that area has got to have an impact on prices,'' she
added.
   Ms. Ball said the failure of the May crude contract to move
above $19 discouraged traders, who then began the afternoon selloff.
   The May crude contract expires at Wednesday's close, and so ``a
lot of people took advantage of the higher prices and sold off,''
said Stephen J. McKiernan, president of the McKiernan & Co.
commodities trading firm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880419-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 1233EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-PhilipMorris     04-19 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Philip Morris,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Phillip Morris Posts 31 Percent Profit Gain in 1st Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philip Morris Companies Inc., the tobacco, food
and brewing giant, said Tuesday its first-quarter profit rose 30.1
percent on a 10.4 percent increase in revenue.
   The company makes Marlboro cigarettes, Jell-O pudding, Oscar
Mayer meats, Maxwell House coffee and Miller beers. It also has a
financial services unit.
   The company said its profit rose to $502 million, or $2.12 a
share, in the three months ended March 31, up from $386 million, or
$1.62 a share, a year earlier.
   Operating revenue rose to $7.24 billion in the quarter from
$6.55 billion a year earlier.
   Chairman Hamish Maxwell said the company's domestic cigarette
operations had higher operating revenue on higher cigarette unit
volume despite an industrywide volume decline in the quarter.
   Internationally, operating revenue and volume of cigarettes were
up strongly for the period, Maxwell said.
   He said the General Foods division reported higher unit volume
in the quarter, while operating revenue was flat due to a decline
in the domestic coffee business. Domestic results of the division
were helped by gains in baked goods and the introduction of new
Jell-O ready-to-eat puddings.
   The Oscar Mayer operations posted strong volume gains and slight
revenue increases for the quarter as the brand increased its market
share in hot dogs, bacon and sliced luncheon meats, the statement
said.
   The Miller Brewing operation reported that higher barrel volume
and price increases led to higher operating revenue for the quarter.
   Philip Morris Credit Corp. posted higher revenue as well,
Maxwell said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
