<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 1250EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-NASDAQ     04-19 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-NASDAQ,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain Approves NASDAQ as Recognized Exchange</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's Department of Trade and Industry on
Tuesday gave regulatory approval to the National Association of
Securities Dealers Automated Quotations (NASDAQ), the U.S.
electronic stock trading system for over-the-counter stocks.
   The department approval means trading of U.S. and foreign stocks
on NASDAQ can continue in London after April 29, when Britain's
1986 Financial Services Act becomes effective.
   NASDAQ is the first overseas exchange to get recognized
investment exchange status under the act.
   The National Association of Securities Dealers Inc. (NASD),
which operates and regulates the NASDAQ market, hopes to expand its
London membership from about 80 firms currently to about 160 firms,
trading the 4,700 U.S. and foreign stocks that are listed on
NASDAQ, said Joseph R. Hardiman, NASD's president.
   Hardiman said he also wants more European companies to issue
American Depositary Receipts _ U.S.-traded equivalents of European
shares _ through NASDAQ.
   NASD hopes to broaden cooperation with London's Stock Exchange,
he said. It hopes to set up a system that will allow small orders
of stock entered though the one exchange to be executed in the
other, he said.
   ``Today we have the technical and now the legal ability to
create what amounts to a trans-Atlantic stock market,'' Hardiman
said.
</TEXT>
