<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 1325EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f AM-China-Economy     04-19 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Economy,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inflation Hits New High In First Quarter Of 1988</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retail prices rose faster than average incomes in
some cities in the first quarter of 1988 and the nationwide
inflation rate hit 11 percent, the government announced Tuesday.
   The inflation rate, up from a national average of 7.3 percent in
1987, is the highest the government has reported since senior
leader Deng Xiaoping began reducing central planning and price
controls in favor of market reforms in 1978.
   In 32 large and medium-size cities, retail prices rose 13.4
percent, the State Statistical Bureau said, while average per
capita incomes in urban areas only rose 13 percent, to more than 90
yuan, or $24, per month.
   Average per capita income for rural residents rose 25 percent,
to 50 yuan, or $13.50 per month.
   Top officials have acknowledged widespread popular discontent
over the rising prices and have announced corrective measures.
   But they also have warned that inflation will remain high for
several years as China strives to develop its backward economy and
allow market factors to set prices.
   Zhang Zhongji, director of the statistic bureau's Department of
Integrated Statistics of the National Economy, told a news
conference that the industrial sector maintained its rapid growth
in the first quarter, with output up 16.7 percent from the same
period last year, to the equivalent of $71.5 billion.
   Industrial output grew 16.5 percent during all of 1987.
   Vice Premier Yao Yilin, head of the State Planning Commission,
told a recent news conference that the government's goal was to
keep inflation below 10 percent, but added: ``Whether we will be
able to achieve it I can't tell you.''
   His cautious assessment reflected the difficulty of the
government's task: to cool demand that is pushing prices up without
curbing much-needed economic growth.
   Uncontrolled investment in often irrational and competing
projects and inadequate supplies of such goods as televisions and
refrigerators have contributed to inflation.
   The government has blamed inadquate investment in agriculture
for high food prices and short supplies of meat in the cities.
   Zhang said grain production was expected to remain about the
same as last year, or 400 million tons. Despite repeated calls to
stress grain production, China has been unable to repeat its record
1984 harvest of 407 million tons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
