<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Metals     04-19 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Metals,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alcoa Earnings Nearly Quadruple</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alumunum Co. of America said Tuesday that high
demand for the lightweight metal and strong revenues worldwide
helped to nearly quadruple first-quarter earnings to $178.7
million, or $2.02 per share.
   ``Alcoa's fundamentals remain strong worldwide,'' said Chairman
Paul O'Neill. ``Customers do not appear to be building inventory.
The January price increase in aluminum beverage can sheet, Alcoa's
largest volume product, is holding.''
   He said the company expects favorable market conditions and
operating fundamentals to continue.
   The nation's largest aluminum producer reported 1987
first-quarter net earnings of $49.5 million, or 56 cents per share.
   Sales increased 18 percent to $2.1 billion from $1.8 billion,
and shipments rose 2 percent to 536,000 metric tons from 527,000
metric tons.
   The quarter was supported by price increases on most products
and more efficient production rates, although the costs of
purchased metal, particularly used aluminum beverage cans, are
rising, O'Neill said.
   ``With higher prices for ingot and alumina, earnings for Alcoa
of Australia and from Alcoa Aluminio in Brazil accounted for 20
percent of Alcoa's first-quarter earnings in spite of currency
losses of $18.5 million from these two companies,'' he said.
   Alumina is an intermediary form of aluminum during the refining
and smelting processes.
   Pittsburgh-based Alcoa operates 97 facilities around the world,
employing about 55,000 workers.
</TEXT>
