<HEAD>Iacocca Made $17 Million In 1987</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: AMs planned.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. Chairman Lee Iacocca
received $17.9 million in 1987, most of it by cashing in on stock
options that were granted when Chrysler was in financial trouble,
Chrysler reported in its proxy statement Tuesday.
   Iacocca was the nation's highest-paid executive in 1986.
   The proxy, which was mailed Tuesday to shareholders, said $13.5
million of Iacocca's 1987 earnings came when he cashed in stock
options he was granted early in the decade when Chrysler stock was
worth a fraction of its present value.
   He also received a $766,000 salary, $725,000 in a cash bonus,
$248,990 in a stock bonus and a stock grant worth $2.7 million.
   In 1986, Iacocca earned $20.6 million, including $9.6 million in
exercised stock options and nearly $1 million in cash bonuses.
   Chrysler's No. 2 executive, Gerald Greenwald, chairman of
Chrysler's automaking business, earned nearly $6.6 million in 1987.
That included $5.3 million in exercised stock options.
   The United Auto Workers scheduled a news conference for later
Tuesday, at which union Vice President Marc Stepp was expected to
blast Chrysler for paying such high salaries and bonuses to
executives.
   The union last week criticized General Motors Corp. and Ford
Motor Co. for similar 1987 payments to its executives.
   As national contract talks between the UAW and Chrysler opened
Monday, Chrysler announced that it no longer will pay bonuses to
executives in years when profits are too low to award
profit-sharing to hourly workers.
</TEXT>
