<HEAD>Bottler Posts 82.2 Percent Profit Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coca-Cola Enterprises Inc., a bottling company
spawned by the Coca-Cola Co., said Tuesday its profit rose 82.2
percent in the first quarter of 1988.
   The company cited increased volume, improved operating
efficiencies and the inclusion of bottling company acquisitions
completed in the latter half of 1987 and the first quarter as well
as certain tax regulations for the improvement.
   The company was formed in 1986 from Coca-Cola-owned bottling
operations and continued to acquire and consolidate similar
companies around the country.
   Coca-Cola Enterprises, publicly traded since November 1986 but
49 percent owned by Coca-Cola, had net income of $12.9 million, or
9 cents a share, in the quarter ended March 31, compared to $7.1
million, or 5 cents a share, in the comparable quarter in 1987.
   First-quarter revenue rose 14.9 percent to $855.52 million from
$744.64 million a year earlier.
   The results include figures from the Coca-Cola Bottling Co. of
Memphis, Tenn., the Florida operations of the Coca-Cola Bottling
Co. of Miami and all of the Maryland and a portion of the Delaware
operations of the Coca-Cola Bottling Co. of Delaware.
   Those operations were acquired on Jan. 29, but consolidated as
of Jan. 1.
