<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0271</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks strengthened today, bolstered by a mild
rebound in the bond market and improved quarterly earnings of some
leading blue-chip companies.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks rose 26.69 points
to 2,034.81 as of 2 p.m. EDT.
   Gaining stocks outnumbered declines by more than 2-to-1 on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 1,043 up, 444 down and 426 unchanged.
   The NYSE's composite index of all listed issues rose 1.34 to
148.11. The American Stock Exchange's market value index rose 0.95
to 301.87.
   But volume totaled a relatively moderate 148.11 million shares
with two hours of trading left, suggesting that many large-scale
investors remain reluctant to participate.
   ``I don't see any institutional buying,'' said Robert O'Toole,
manager of over-the-counter trading at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
in New York. ``This is just a trader's market.''
   Stocks of some key components in the Dow average were partly
responsible for the gains. Merck rose 2\ to 160, Alcoa rose 3{ to
47 and Philip Morris rose 1[ to 88[. Those companies reported
higher first-quarter earnings.
   Other important stocks that comprise the Dow average also
gained. IBM rose 1} to 115}, American Telephone & Telegraph gained
{ to 26~, International Paper gained 2[ to 44| and General Electric
rose rose } to 40\.
   Wall Street further benefited from a partial recovery in the
slumping bond market, which pushed the yield on the key 30-year
Treasury bond back under 9 percent. That made bonds less attractive
as an alternate investment to stocks.
</TEXT>
