<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Sotheby'sStock     04-19 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Sotheby's Stock,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Auctioneer's Shareholders Trim Back Share Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sotheby's, the world's largest art auctioneer,
said Tuesday its shareholders would sell to the public fewer shares
at a cheaper price than previously planned, apparently because of
the volatile stock markets.
   The shareholders will raise a maximum of $116 million _ compared
with the earlier planned $187 million _ through the first public
sale of Sotheby's Holdings Inc.'s stock, the closely held company
said.
   Fiona Ford, a spokeswoman for Sotheby's, declined to provide a
reason for the substantial trimming down of the sale.
   However, the sale originally had been planned for October but
was postponed because of the stock markets' crash.
   Sotheby's said the shareholders would sell 5.5 million shares at
between $18 a share and $21 a share, raising a total of between $99
million and $116 million.
   The stock being sold will represent 22 percent of the company's
stock, it said.
   Sotheby's previously had said that 7.21 million shares would be
sold at between $23 a share and $26 a share for a total of between
$166 million and $187 million.
   U.S.-owned Sotheby's said 2.9 million shares would be offered
for sale in the United States, and 1.5 million shares in Britain,
on the same day in mid-May. The date hasn't been announced.
   A further 1.1 million shares are to be sold in the international
market, Sotheby's said.
   Alfred Taubman, a Michigan shopping mall tycoon, gained control
of Sotheby's in September 1983.
</TEXT>
