<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 1528EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Disney     04-19 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Disney,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disney Buys Direct-Mail Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walt Disney Co. said Tuesday it has
acquired Childcraft Education Corp. for $52 million, a move that
will significantly expand Disney's mail-order business.
   Disney also said it plans to add 10 East Coast stores to the
corporation's fledgling retail operation.
   Disney currently operates three stores that are not on
amusement-park grounds, all in Southern California, according to
Steve Burke, vice president of Disney's consumer products division.
   Childcraft, based in New Jersey, was a good fit because its
target market is preschoolers who are loyal fans of Mickey Mouse,
Donald Duck and other characters from the Disney menagerie, Burke
said.
   Childcraft's mailing list also will help bolster Disney's
mail-order business. Last year, 2.8 million copies of the Walt
Disney Family Gift Catalog were mailed. This year, Disney plans to
mail 8 million copies, a spokesman said.
   The combined moves will expand by one-third Disney's smallest
division, consumer products, which licenses Disney characters and
runs retail operations.
   In 1987, the consumer products division reported earnings of
$167 million, about 6 percent of Disney's $2.9 billion in 1987
revenue. Last year Disney reported $97 million in operating income.
   ``These are two further steps in the growth of the division,''
Burke said. They ``fit in with a broader strategy of expanding our
consumer products business aggressively.''
   In the past seven months, Disney's retailing and licensing
division also struck a 10-year deal with Sears, Roebuck and Co.,
the nation's largest retailer, to develop and sell new products.
Disney also signed a marketing deal with Mattel, the nation's
second-largest toymaker, to market infant and preschool toys.
</TEXT>
