<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 1520EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet3pm     04-19 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0353</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks strengthened today, bolstered by a mild
rebound in the bond market and improved quarterly earnings of some
leading blue-chip companies.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks rose 23.38 points
to 2,031.50 as of 3 p.m. EDT.
   Gaining stocks outnumbered declines by more than 2-to-1 on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 1,007 up, 472 down and 458 unchanged.
   The NYSE's composite index of all listed issues rose 1.18 to
147.95. The American Stock Exchange's market value index rose 0.49
to 301.41.
   But volume totaled a relatively moderate 128.34 million shares
with an hour of trading left, suggesting many investors remain
reluctant to participate in a market still scarred by the epic
crash exactly six months ago today on Oct. 19.
   ``I don't see any institutional buying,'' said Robert O'Toole,
manager of over-the-counter trading at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
in New York. ``This is just a trader's market.''
   Hugh Johnson, senior vice president of the First Albany Corp.
brokerage, said the market's strength today reflected a gradual
recovery from the shock of last week, when an unexpected bulge in
the trade deficit sent prices tumbling.
   Nevertheless, he said, the sluggish trading level showed that
``you still have a lot of uncertainty in the market. A lot of small
and large investors, as far as I can tell, are still on the
sidelines.''
   Stocks of some key components in the Dow average were partly
responsible for the gains. Merck rose 2\ to 160, Alcoa rose 3| to
47[ and Philip Morris rose 1 to 88. Those companies reported higher
first-quarter earnings.
   Other important stocks that comprise the Dow average also
gained. IBM rose 1[ to 115[, American Telephone & Telegraph gained
| to 27, International Paper gained 2[ to 44| and General Motors
rose 1 to 72~.
   Traders said Wall Street further benefited from a partial
recovery in the slumping bond market, which slightly depressed
yields and made bonds less attractive as an alternate investment to
stocks.
</TEXT>
