<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed sharply higher
Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade and grains followed suit,
reflecting concern that supply problems may surface next fall.
   The Agriculture Department's report on spring planting
intentions is now nearly three weeks old but continues to have an
impact on the market, especially on soybean prices, said Ted Mao,
an analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   The report indicated that soybean acreage would increase this
year by about 1 percent. Analysts said that with only a slight
increase in acreage, weather conditions could play an unusually
large role in the size of the harvest.
   The corn market faces a similar scenario, and early signs of
dryness in the western corn belt may have touched off some buying
interest Tuesday, Mao said.
   ``It's certainly much too early to be too concerned about
weather,'' he said. ``But since it looks like the overall acreage
base is going to be small this year, the market may be more
sensitive to early weather problems.''
   At the close, wheat was 2 cents to 3 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.14{ a bushel; corn was 1{ cents
to 3 cents higher with May at $2.05\ a bushel; oats were 2 cents to
3} cents higher with May at $1.68{ a bushel; soybeans were 6 cents
to 8 cents higher with May at $6.72 a bushel.
</TEXT>
