<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Computer     04-19 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Computer,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Earnings Rise at Wang, Amdahl, Microsoft, Lotus</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Microsoft Corp. built up its lead over Lotus Development Corp.
in revenue and profits in the latest quarter, although both
personal computer software companies announced strong gains Tuesday.
   Among computer makers, Amdahl Corp. reported higher profits and
Wang Laboratories Inc. said its earnings jumped although sales rose
a modest 3 percent.
   Microsoft, of Redmond, Wash., said its net income rose 95
percent to $37.3 million, or 67 cents a share in its third fiscal
quarter, from $19.1 million, or 35 cents a share, a year earlier.
Revenue rose 65 percent to $161.8 million from $98.4 million a year
earlier.
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, Microsoft said its
profit rose 72 percent to $93.9 million, or $1.68 a share, from
$54.6 million, or 99 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 71
percent to $420.4 million from $246.1 million.
   Lotus, of Cambridge, Mass., said its profit rose 34 percent to
$18.3 million, or 40 cents a share, in the first quarter, from
$13.7 million, or 31 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 38
percent to $117.3 million from $84.8 million.
   Analysts last month cut Lotus' earnings estimates for 1988 after
the company announced plans to delay introduction of its Lotus
1-2-3 Release 3 spreadsheet software until the fourth quarter.
   Amdahl, the Sunnyvale, Calif.-based maker of mainframe computers
that use the same software as International Business Machines Corp.
mainframes, said its profit rose 71 percent to $43.2 million, or 81
cents a share, in the quarter ended March 25, from $25.2 million,
or 51 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 15 percent to
$367.7 million from $318.5 million.
   Wang, the Lowell, Mass.-based maker of minicomputers and
office-automation equipment, said its profit nearly quadrupled to
$22.7 million, or 14 cents a share, from $5.9 million, or 4 cents a
share, in its third fiscal quarter. Revenue rose 3 percent to
$767.9 million from $745.9 million.
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, Wang said it
posted a profit of $79.3 million, or 48 cents a share, in contrast
with a loss of $102.7 million in the same period a year earlier.
Revenue rose 12 percent to $2.25 billion from $2.01 billion.
</TEXT>
