<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Phone     04-19 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Phone,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Profit Up At GTE, MCI, Pacific Telesis, U S West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   MCI Communications Corp. on Tuesday reported a record profit and
strong gains in long-distance calling volume in its first quarter.
Profits also rose at GTE Corp., Pacific Telesis Group and U S West.
   MCI, the No.2 long-distance carrier, based in Washington, D.C.,
said its profit more than doubled to $69 million, or 24 cents a
share, on revenue of $1.13 billion. That compared with earnings of
$25 million, or 9 cents a share, on revenue of $955 million for the
first quarter of 1987.
   MCI said its volume of calls was up 39 percent from a year ago
and had increased 14 percent when compared to the fourth quarter.
   GTE, the phone company based in Stamford, Conn., said its profit
rose 8 percent to $286 million, or 84 cents a share, from $265
million, or 78 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 7
percent to $3.9 billion from $3.7 billion.
   GTE owns local telephone companies that do business in 31 states
and is half-owner, with United Telecommunications Inc., of US
Sprint Communications Co. US Sprint is the nation's third-largest
long-distance carrier behind American Telephone & Telegraph Co. and
MCI.
   GTE's results were hurt by a first-quarter pre-tax loss of $138
million at US Sprint, which GTE shared equally with United
Telecommunications. US Sprint's revenue rose 23 percent to $759
million, while its pre-tax loss was 43 percent less than the
year-earlier loss.
   Pacific Telesis, the San Francisco-based holding company for
Bell telephone companies in the West, said its profit rose 28.2
percent to $300 million, or 71 cents a share, from $234 million, or
55 cents a share, a year ago.
   Revenue rose 7.9 percent to $2.31 billion from $2.14 billion a
year ago.
   U S West reported its profit rose 17.8 percent to $240.5
million, or $1.30 per share, from $204.2 million, or $1.08 per
share, in first quarter 1987. The 1987 quarter included one-time
charges of $30.2 million stemmnig from an early retirement plan and
refunds ordered by the state of Oregon.
   Revenue in the first quarter rose to $2.2 billion from $2.04
billion in first quarter 1987.
   U S West is the Denver-based holding company for Mountain Bell,
Pacific Northwest Bell, Northwestern Bell, plus companies involved
in directory publishing, cellular communications and other
communications and computer products.
</TEXT>
