<HEAD>Honeywell Reports First-Quarter Earnings Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honeywell Inc., citing strong profits in its
industrial business, on Tuesday reported its first-quarter earnings
rose 32 percent.
   The international control manufacturer and defense contractor
said it earned $57.7 million, or $1.36 per share, up from $43.7
million, or 96 cents per share, in the same period a year ago.
   The current quarter included $5 million in one-time gains
related to asset sales.
   The company said its worldwide sales in the first quarter
increased to $1.74 billion, compared with $1.48 billion in the
first three months of 1987.
   James J. Renier, Honeywell president and chief executive
officer, said total operating profit increased and was especially
strong in the company's industrial and homes and buildings
businesses. Operating profit also increased in defense and marine
systems, but declined in space and aviation systems, he said.
   Honeywell provides products, systems and services for the home
and building, industrial, space and aviation, and defense and
marine markets.
   The company has 79,000 employees worldwide, with 1987 sales of
$6.7 billion and net income of $254 million.
