<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Bethlehem     04-19 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bethlehem,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dividend Payout, Sign Of Good Times</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bethlehem Steel Corp. announced on Tuesday
plans to pay more than $24 million in overdue preferred stock
dividends and to sell 8 million shares of common stock to pare its
$1.7 billion unfunded pension liability.
   One Wall Street analyst said the dividends are a sign of
Bethlehem's faith in the steel industry's recovery after five years
of massive losses, plant closings and employment cuts.
   ``It shows more of a conviction that what is actually happening
in the steel markets is going to be more sustainable than most
observers believe,'' said Dick Henderson of Donaldson, Lufkin &
Jenrette Securities Corp. of New York. ``Steel demand is strong,
pricing is strong, earnings are going to be strong.''
   The recovery seems ``very, very broad-based,'' he said. ``It
represents the participation of the steel industry in the so-called
reindustrialization of America.''
   Henderson said his enthusiasm for steel industry stocks,
especially Bethlehem's, runs counter to the market. He called
Bethlehem stock undervalued.
   ``People are looking at the recoveries in the industrial and
capital goods markets. They know it's happening, but they don't
believe it will continue,'' he said.
   Bethlehem reported profits in each quarter last year and $174
million profit for all of 1987. It was the first annual profit
since 1981, and during the interim, Bethlehem lost more than $2
billion.
   The steelmaker said Salomon Brothers Inc. has agreed to
underwrite the common stock offering, which follows last fall's
sale of 12 million common shares and would raise the number of
outstanding shares from the current 64.4 million to 72.4 million.
   Bethlehem stock fell $1.62{ per share to $19.37{ in New York
Stock Exchange composite trading after Tuesday's announcement.
   The company's board declared Monday that on June 10 shareholders
of record May 10 will be paid arrearages and second quarter
dividends of $6.25 per share and $3.12{ per share on Bethlehem's $5
and $2.50 cummulative convertible preferred issues respectively.
   Dividends worth $22.5 million were omitted for the second half
of 1986 and the first half of 1987.
   The board also said the company will pay dividends June 11 on
convertible preference shares issued to employees under contracts
with the United Steelworkers and other unions. The dividends will
be paid in additional shares with an aggregate stated value of $1.7
million. The dividend covers the period ending April 1.
   The payments do not cover common stock dividends, which have not
been paid since the board declared 10 cents per share for the third
quarter of 1985. Unlike the preferred issues, on which dividends
accumulate, the common issue does not require the company to pay a
dividend.
   Bethlehem said it would report first quarter income at its
annual shareholders meeting next Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
