<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 1946EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-JapanQuotas     04-19 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan Quotas,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan May Soon Phase Out Citrus and Beef Quotas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan may begin phasing out quotas on U.S.
citrus and beef imports as early as next week to avoid rebuke by an
international panel, according to a top American trade official.
   Japan vetoed a U.S. request two weeks ago for a special
investigation of the quotas by the 92-nation General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade, but the United States plans to push the issue at
GATT's next council meeting May 4.
   ``They know we will not allow a dispute panel to be blocked a
second time,'' Michael Samuels, deputy U.S. trade representative
and ambassador to the GATT, said in an interview with the San
Francisco Chronicle Monday.
   Japanese and American officials will discuss the matter next
week in Tokyo, and Samuels thinks Japan may be ready to agree to a
compromise.
   ``They may not want to go to GATT and be found `guilty' of
policy violations because that might offend their political
sensitivities at home,'' the ambassador said.
   Under a 1984 agreement that expired last month, Japan agreed to
admit 177,000 tons American beef and 86,400 tons of U.S. oranges
this year. Pressure from the powerful Japanese agriculture lobby
has prevented an elimination of the quotas.
   The United States wants a complete lifting of the quotas,
Samuels said, but the Reagan administration is willing to accept a
gradual elimination over a short period of time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880419-0286 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 1740EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Aeromexico     04-19 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Aeromexico,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Declares Mexican Airline Bankrupt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGIO CARRASCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge declared government-owned
Aeromexico bankrupt and ordered it into receivership, leaving the
airline's more than 9,200 workers jobless Tuesday.
   The decision followed a strike by the airline's technical
workers that shut down the airline on April 12 in protest of
management plans to reduce the fleet and route system to bring
Aeromexico back into the black.
   The airline filed a petition for bankruptcy on Friday, saying it
was losing $1 million a day because of the strike.
   Civil Court Judge Sergio Higuera Mota issued the bankruptcy
decree late Monday, the Department of Communications and
Transportation announced.
   President Miguel de la Madrid said the bankruptcy petition was
not an isolated case but part of a new policy to sell, cut out or
close down all money-losing companies and agencies owned or
operated by the government.
   ``The country cannot give itself the luxury of having
inefficient enterprises, which constitute a burden to the entire
society,'' de la Madrid said at an appearance Monday in the
northern industrial city of Monterrey.
   Mexico has been suffering from acute inflation and other
economic ills since 1982, when international prices for oil, its
No. 1 export by far, first dropped.
   The strike had grounded all Aeromexico's 223 daily flights to 42
international and domestic destinations.
   The Aeromexico Technicians and Workers Union called the protest
strike after the airline's management announced plans to sell 13
aircraft, saying the sale would leave more than 2,000 ground
workers and cabin attendants without jobs.
   Pilots and cabin attendants have their own unions and did not
support the strike.
   Rene Arce, the union's president, said his organization would
fight to keep the airline alive and reiterated that it was
interested in trying to buy it. He said the union could muster the
support of a number of Mexican and foreign investors, but he did
not identify them.
   Arce estimated the airline would cost $200 million to purchase,
including $70 million in estimated severance pay to workers.
   In Monterrey, de la Madrid told reporters that from now on the
government ``will demand greater productivity, including some
radical re-structuring, as in the case of commercial aviation,''
from its hundreds of money-losing enterprises.
   Aeromexico started business in 1934 and has been owned by the
government since 1957. The strike and the bankruptcy have not
affected Mexicana de Aviacion, the other major Mexican airline,
which has been controlled by the government since 1982.
   Aeromexico employs 7,200 ground workers and technicians, 1,200
cabin attendants and 800 pilots.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880419-0287 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 1743EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   04-19 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0581</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mild stock rally fizzled late Tuesday,
overwhelmed by computerized selling strategies and anxiety that has
afflicted investors since the historic crash exactly six months ago.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 blue-chip stocks, up more than 32
points at midafternoon, slid in the final hours and finished down
8.62 to 1,999.50, back under the 2,000 level for the first time in
two weeks. Most broader market indices also fell.
   ``People are willing to venture into the market on a day-by-day
basis, but not much longer,'' said Joseph Barthel, technical
analyst at the Butcher & Singer Co. investment firm. ``Without some
sort of clarification, I think we're doomed to this type of
whipsawed action.''
   The market strengthened through the early hours, largely because
of sharply higher earnings reported by some leading companies that
comprise the Dow average. A partial recovery in the slumping bond
market also helped by easing interest rates, thereby making bonds a
less attractive alternative to stocks.
   But bonds weakened in the afternoon on renewed fears of
inflation and fighting in the Persian Gulf. Traders said this
helped provide an excuse to bail out of stocks and erase the day's
gains.
   Some said the decline was speeded by index arbitrage program
trading, the controversial strategy of selling large amounts of
stocks and buying equivalent groups of stock-index futures, or vice
versa, to profit from price disparities.
   The result was a seesaw market dominated by professional
traders, as reflected in the relatively light New York Stock
Exchange volume of 161.91 million shares. On Monday the volume was
even lighter at 144.65 million shares.
   ``Volatility and uncertainty about the economy are keeping a lot
of people on the sidelines,'' said Hugh Johnson, senior vice
president of the First Albany Corp. brokerage.
   ``This is the six month anniversary,'' he said, referring to
Black Monday, Oct. 19. ``It just sort of makes me think that even
though it's six months later, we haven't come a long way.''
   The number of rising and falling stocks finished about even in
NYSE composite trading, with 789 up, 733 down and 466 unchanged.
Earlier in the day gainers outnumbered losers by more than 2-to-1.
   Among the most prominent blue chips, Aluminum Co. of America
jumped 3 to 46{. The company reported sharply higher first-quarter
earnings.
   Other notable stocks benefiting from higher corporate earnings
included Philip Morris, up | to 87|; Honeywell, up 1[ to 68~; and
Monsanto, up 1] to 81~.
   Bethlehem Steel fell 1| to 19]. The company said it had plans to
sell 8 million shares of common stock and apply the proceeds to its
$1.7 billion unfunded pension liability.
   The Wilshire Associates 5,000 Equity Index, the market value of
5,000 NYSE, American and over-the-counter issues, was $2.58
trillion, off $7.81 billion from Monday.
   Nationwide turnover in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the OTC market, totaled
192.30 million shares.
   The NYSE composite index of all listed issues fell 0.60 to
146.17.
   Standard & Poor's index of 400 industrials fell 1.55 to 300.50,
and S&P's 500-stock composite index fell 1.29 to 257.92.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index fell 1 to
299.92. The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
closed at 376.86, up 1.76.
</TEXT>
