<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-3M,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>3M Reports Record First-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPLEWOOD, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minnesota Mining & Manufacturing Co. on
Tuesday reported its first quarter earnings rose 30 percent as
sales and productivity increased and the dollar and taxes fell.
   3M said it earned $277 million, or $1.22 per share, up from $213
million, or 93 cents per share, in the same period a year earlier.
   Sales for the quarter rose to $2.6 billion from $2.21 billion.
   Allen F. Jacobson, chairman and chief executive officer, said
3M's U.S. and international businesses posted solid results.
Earnings benefited from double-digit worldwide unit growth,
increased productivity, weakening of the U.S. dollar and a lower
effective tax rate.
   Jacobson said 3M expects another year of higher sales and
earnings. ``While the outlook for the economy is somewhat
uncertain, we expect to benefit from a strong flow of new products,
as well as from continued emphasis on quality, productivity and
increased penetration of international markets,'' he said.
   ``In addition, the weaker dollar and a lower effective tax rate
will continue to aid results.''
