<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BostonMarathon-Money Bjt   04-19 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boston Marathon-Money, Bjt,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hancock Reaps Rewards For Marathon Sponsorship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Hancock Financial Services pumps $1 million
per year into the Boston Marathon. But the insurance conglomerate
figures it gets back at least $8.2 million in publicity due to
massive coverage of the event.
   ``The number of people reached is very impressive,'' Jack
Mahoney, John Hancock's special events director, said Tuesday.
   Two years ago, Hancock estimated conservatively that at least
some mention of its sponsorship of the race reached 750 million
people worldwide, which it said was the equivalent of roughly $8.2
million in advertising.
   The race on Monday ended in the closest finish in the 92-year
history of the Boston Marathon with Ibrahim Hussein of Kenya
crossing the finish line a second ahead of Juma Ikangaa of Tanzania.
   ``It was a great race,'' Mahoney said. ``The only thing that
could have been better would have been a dead heat.''
   Hancock is not alone in reaping the harvest of good will and
free publicity.
   Most of the major newspapers in the country carried photographs
of the runners. Ricoh Corp.'s name was emblazoned on the runners'
number tags.
   Coverage of the race was likely to mention that the men and
women winners got a Mercedes Benz.
   And any pictures from the finish area were likely to catch a
glimpse of the silver Mylar blankets bearing the Nestle@Chunky logo
that were given to each of the 6,700 runners.
   Hancock goes to great lengths to make sure there are no snags in
the transmitting of all that publicity.
   On race day, journalists occupied two large function rooms at
the Copley Plaza Hotel near the finish line. Part of the staff of
some 900 Hancock volunteers kept a steady flow of information
coming to the reporters from a Ricoh copier brought in for the
occasion. Camera crews and pool reporters moved ahead of the
leaders in a Mercedes Benz media truck.
   ``I still think it will grow in terms of media,'' said Mahoney.
Some 1,200 journalists covered the Marathon on Monday, he said.
   In the early 1980s, the question of whether the marathon would
have corporate sponsorship was debated hotly. Some argued that the
race should retain its amateur status but some race organizers were
concerned that Boston would be eclipsed as the premier marathon by
others offering prize money.
   Race Director Guy Morse of the Boston Athletic Association
doesn't miss the old days.
   ``We've been able to protect the Boston Marathon as a unique,
tradition-steeped event while at the same time bringing those
elements needed to make it among the best in the world,'' Morse
said.
</TEXT>
