<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dial-A-Porn 1stLd-Writethru f0262 04-19 0709</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dial-A-Porn, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0262,0726</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Votes Ban On Telephone Pornography Services</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: New throughout with compromise plan killed, Senate action
likely Wednesday, education bill passed.
^By STEVEN KOMAROW</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Tuesday approved a nationwide ban
on ``dial-a-porn'' telephone pornography services despite arguments
that the bill was unconstitutional.
   The legislation, identical to an amendment approved earlier in
the Senate, was included in an $8.3 billion education bill passed
397 to 1 after lawmakers handed Democratic leaders a defeat and
rejected a less-sweeping anti-porn provision.
   Final Senate action on the package was expected Wednesday.
   ``Some may question the constitutionality of this measure,''
said Rep. Ralph Hall, D-Texas. ``But it is the most
straightforward.''
   Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of the House Committee on
Energy and Commerce, called the measure ``extraordinarily shaky''
on constitutional grounds.
   Barry W. Lynn, legislative counsel of the American Civil
Liberties Union, said the ban ``clearly intrudes on the privacy and
the free-speech rights of adult Americans. This is a hopelessly
inept way of dealing with the issue of children's access to
dial-a-porn, which should be the only matter under consideration.''
   He predicted ``years of litigation, and in the process,
increased access by children to dial-a-porn.'' The situation would
get worse because current Federal Communications Commission rules
protecting children from telephone pornography would be thrown away
in the process, he said.
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., first won the dial-a-porn ban
amendment 98-0 when the Senate first passed the otherwise
non-controversial education bill. But the House had included no
similar provision in its version of the bill and a compromise, less
legally controversial provision was approved by House-Senate
conferees.
   While the Helms amendment contained a total ban on the services
for adults as well as children, the education bill's provision
would have had telephone companies block access to dial-a-porn
unless the telephone customer, an adult, specifically requested
they be made available.
   Opponents of the compromise said it was too weak and pointed out
that about 12 percent of the nation's telephone exchanges did not
have the technology to block out the service to some homes but not
to others.
   In an attempt to satisfy both sides, House leaders on Tuesday
orchestrated the vote on a new, separate but otherwise identical
dial-a-porn bill. The plan was to have both versions approved, with
the education bill's language available if the total ban failed to
pass constitutional muster.
   The separate bill passed the House 379-22. But then, in a defeat
for Democratic leaders, the House inserted it into the education
bill in place of the compromise.
   House Republicans carried the day after accusing the Democratic
leaders of trying to block the flat-out ban.
   Rep. Thomas Bliley, R-Va., who sponsored the Helms amendment in
the House, called the Democrats' process ``a charade'' by lawmakers
hoping the ban would be blocked in the Senate.
   He called the limited protections in the education compromise
``akin to telling someone it's illegal to sell someone drugs,
unless someone walks up to them ... and asks for some.''
   Voting against the dial-a-porn ban, when it came up as a
separate bill, were Reps. Anthony Beilenson, D-Calif., Howard
Berman, D-Calif., Douglas Bosco, D-Calif., Ron Dellums, D-Calif.,
Julian Dixon, D-Calif., Mervyn Dymally, D-Calif., Don Edwards,
D-Calif., Barney Frank, D-Mass., Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn., Bill
Green, R-N.Y., Augustus F. Hawkins, D-Calif., Charles Hayes,
D-Ill., William Lehman, D-Fla., Bruce Morrison, D-Conn., Peter
Rodino, D-N.J., Edward Roybal, D-Calif., Pete Stark, D-Calif.,
Gerry Studds, D-Mass., Henry Waxman, D-Calif., Ted Weiss, D-N.Y.,
Alan Wheat, D-Mo., and Sidney Yates, D-Ill.
   Rep. Donald Pease, D-Ohio, voted ``present.''
   Not voting were Reps. Gary Ackerman, D-N.Y., Doug Barnard,
D-Ga., Mario Biaggi, D-N.Y., Beau Boulter, R-Texas, William Clay,
D-Mo., William Clinger, R-Pa., George Crockett, D-Mich., Hal Daub,
R-Neb., Jack Davis, R-Ill., Kika de la Garza, D-Texas, Bill
Emerson, R-Mo., Jack Fields, R-Texas, Robert Garcia, D-N.Y., Bill
Grant, D-Fla., John Kasich, R-Ohio, Jack Kemp, R-N.Y., Gerald
Kleczka, D-Wis., Connie Mack, R-Fla., Thomas Manton, D-N.Y., Alan
Mollohan, D-W.Va., Jim Moody, D-Wis., Constance Morella, R-Md.,
Major Owens, D-N.Y., Melvin Price, D-Ill., Charles Rangel, D-N.Y.,
Richard Ray, D-Ga., Gus Savage, D-Ill., Norman Sisisky, D-Va., and
Edolphus Towns, D-N.Y.
   The only lawmaker to vote against the education bill including
the dial-a-porn language was Rep. Philip Crane, R-Ill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
