<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Space, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0274,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Calls For Long-Term Investment In Space</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to UPDATE with speech being delivered.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Tuesday took issue with
critics of administration space plans and asked Congress and the
American people to ``join me in making the long-term investment
required to advance U.S. leadership in space.''
   ``Can we afford to stop our exploration and wait for others to
pass us?'' Reagan asked in a speech at the annual
government-industry dinner of the Electronic Industries Association.
   ``The space station is vital to our leadership in space and
contributes to our pre-eminence in manned space flight,'' the
president said. ``Some say we can't afford the space station.''
   But, he asked, ``can we afford to jettison the next generation
of technical spin-offs?''
   ``Tonight I ask Congress and all the American people to join me
in making the long-term investment required to advance U.S.
leadership in space,'' Reagan said. ``We must begin that investment
by funding the increases I've proposed for our civil space
program.''
   Reagan also said it was administration policy ``to encourage
private sector investment and involvement in outer space.''
   ``We will help develop a highway to space by using private
launch services to the greatest extent feasible, and we are working
to win legislation to limit liability for commercial launch
providers,'' he said.
   ``It's a future beyond the most distant star in our dreams that
beckons us,'' Reagan told the electronics executives. ``And to
those who say it can't be reached, that it's impossible, I'd just
point toward your industries and ask if a few years ago they
thought what you are doing today would also be impossible.''
   The president also put in a plug for the Strategic Defense
Initiative, or Star Wars, his proposal for a space-based defense
against nuclear missiles.
   ``Five years ago I proposed SDI and, much to my satisfaction, we
have made tremendous progress in that research,'' he said. ``We
must not stop dreaming because a few naysayers insist on limiting
our options for a safe and secure future.''
</TEXT>
